aVG. Srinivasan\u000a\u000aNew Delhi, Sept. 2\u000a\u000aAs an integration of climate and development agendas risks widening the divide between developed and developing countries with both blocs refusing to budge from their stance, the United Nations aptly argues that addressing the climate challenge cannot proceed on \u201cad hoc and incremental actions\u201d.\u000a\u000aIn a new report titled Promoting Development, Saving the Planet, released worldwide on Wednesday, the UN World Economic and Social Survey 2009 concedes that the developed world needs to make much stronger efforts to cut emissions. But this in itself is unlikely to be adequate to cope with the frightening climate challenge unless there is active participation from the developing nations, it said.\u000a\u000aOpen secret\u000a\u000aAchieving such a transformation depends on the creation of \u201ca global new deal,\u201d capable of raising investment levels and funnelling resources for lowering the carbon content of economic activity and building buffers against unavoidable climate change, it said.\u000a\u000aBut it is an open secret that most developing countries do not currently have the financial wherewithal, technological know-how and institutional capacity to deploy such strategies at a pace to cope with the urgency of the climate challenge.\u000a\u000aNo wonder, the UN report laments that the failure to honour long-standing commitments on global support in those three major areas continues to be the single biggest stumbling block to meeting the challenge.\u000a\u000aIn the effort to wind up negotiations for a new global pact to address climate change ahead of the Copenhagen Climate Change Conference with major emerging economies such as India and China pitching for a joint stance, an incontrovertible fact is that the adverse effect of climate change is most acutely felt in the developing countries.\u000a\u000aThese are also the countries where the greatest impacts are also forecast \u2014 more severe droughts in some areas, more intense precipitation in others would wreak havoc with the world\u2019s water supplies and agricultural capacities. These occurrences are now happening at a discomforting scale in tropical countries such as India.\u000a\u000aThe UN report is not off the mark when it states that advanced countries, in their climb to the top of the development ladder, have used up a good part of the atmospheric space for greenhouse gas emissions over the past six decades.\u000a\u000aGenuine fears abound that given the close link between energy use and economic growth, there is real concern that the \u201csustainable development ladder\u201d has already been kicked away and with it any real chance of combining climate and development objectives.\u000a\u000aEnergy transition\u000a\u000aReducing greenhouse gas emission would call for large and interconnected investments across several sectors, with the aim of arresting deforestation and land degradation, retrofitting buildings to make them more energy-efficient and redesigning transportation systems.\u000a\u000aThe UN report admits that it is an energy transition that would be at the core of an alternative integrated strategy for meeting climate change and development goals.\u000a\u000aEnergy use is responsible for 60 per cent of total greenhouse gas emissions, all stabilisation scenarios show that a huge share of emissions reductions, perhaps as much as 80 per cent, will have to come from the reshaping of energy systems.\u000a\u000aBut expanding cleaner energy services and to realise scale economies and the benefits of technological learning, the Survey argues that large upfront investments would need to be made, particularly by the public sector, in new energy infrastructure and in complementary research and development to prune costs. But these efforts would be hampered by constraints on domestic resource mobilisation and the limited ability of many developing countries to raise capital in global markets.\u000a\u000aIn this context, the report rolls out a range of multilateral measures in support of a global investment programme, including global clean energy fund, a global feed-in tariff regime in support of renewable energy sources, a climate technology programme and a more balanced intellectual property regime for aiding the transfer of clean technologies.\u000a\u000aThe Union Minister of State for Environment and Forest, Mr Jairam Ramesh who is spearheading India\u2019s stance on the forthcoming Copenhagen meeting, would do well to sensitise international community about the imperatives for collaborative efforts to help ease resources problems for developing world in its pursuit of green growth, development economists say.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated September 3, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated
