aVThe governments report card on greenhouse gas emissions, the cause of global warming, has estimated that per person emissions will rise to only 2.1 tonne by the year 2020 and stabilise at 3.5 tonne by 2030. This means even two decades from now, Indias per capita emissions would be well below the global average 25 years earlier.\u000a\u000aThe report is the first mapping of detailed emissions data by the government after 2004, when the per capita greenhouse gas emissions was calculated at 1.3 tonne. The results of India most sweeping emissions summary will buttress the governments negotiating position at the Copenhagen UN Climate Change Conference in December this year.\u000a\u000aThe study was released by deputy chairman of the Planning Commission Montek Singh Ahluwalia, along with the minister for environment and forests Jairam Ramesh on Wednesday. Ramesh said it is notable that the estimated per person emissions of India in 2020 are expected to be well below those of the developed countries, even if (they) were to take ambitious emission reduction targets.\u000a\u000aThe results will ease apprehensions that Indias greenhouse gas emissions are poised for a runaway increase over the next two decades.\u000a\u000aThe report is a compendium of five studies prepared by Ncaer, McKinsey, Teri and the Integrated Research and Action for Development (see chart).
