aVClimate change mitigation.\u000a\u000aIndia can emerge a leader in the development of carbon capture and sequestration technologies, but this will be difficult without external financial and intellectual resources. The urgency is thus greater in concluding climate negotiations than trade talks, says M. RAMESH.\u000a\u000aA year ago, the Commerce Minister, Mr Kamal Nath, left Geneva saying he did not want to \u201crisk the livelihood of millions of farmers\u201d by concluding a lopsided agreement, even at the cost of putting the Doha Round negotiations in suspended animation. When the Environment Minister, Mr Jairam Ramesh, packs his bags at the end of the Copenhagen climate meet this December, his frame of mind may be no different. Clouds of uncertainty seem to be gathering over the Danish capital. It is not that the positions, unlike in the trade talks, are so irreconcilable. Indeed, given the universality of science and its consequent imperatives of action, there is not much to disagree on \u2014 at least, on the principles. Ironically, despite the common plank, an agreement is most likely to elude the negotiators at the climate talks.\u000a\u000aThe cornerstone of the developing countries\u2019 stand, as clearly espoused by India in its submission to the UNFCCC, is that the world would not get anywhere in terms of climate mitigation unless the developed nations bankroll anti-polluting measures. The developed countries, recognising they are fundamentally responsible for the current environmental mess, do not disagree.\u000a\u000aA good illustration of this is what Todd Stern, the US\u2019 Special Envoy for Climate Change, said in a speech: \u201cThe United States recognises our unique responsibility, both as the largest historic emitter of greenhouse gases and as a country with important human, financial and technological capabilities and resources.\u201d\u000a\u000aWhere\u2019s the money?\u000a\u000aBut the problem is, where is the money? There are numerous estimates of the costs of climate mitigation. The UNDP estimates that \u2018adaptation\u2019 to climate change alone could cost $86 billion annually. The British economist, Lord Stern, author of the 700-page Stern Review, has said that the cost of reducing carbon would amount to 2 per cent of global GDP, or about $1.1 trillion.\u000a\u000aIn contrast, the funding available is laughably small. The Global Environmental Facility (managed by the UN and the World Bank) is $1.3 billion for the period 2007-10. Since 2005, the GEF has provided $110 million for adaptation projects.\u000a\u000aIn today\u2019s global economic scenario, it is difficult to see commitments for large financial flows from the developed world. True, \u2018environment\u2019 is good business and, as China has shown, could be a ladder to clamber out of the current economic morass. But then, the position taken by developing countries \u2013 legitimately \u2013 is that the financial flows are \u201centitlement, not aid\u201d. This means that when a developed country gives money for a climate mitigating project, it only has a right to see that the funds are spent for the purposes given, but no right to seek any economic gains out of it. This de-linking of financial flows and economic benefit to the donor is a very fundamental principle with which the developing world goes to Copenhagen.\u000a\u000aGiven this, one wonders which country is today in a position to commit large funds, even as atonement for acknowledged past polluting sins. Today, while there are talks about funds, information on the sources of funds is somewhat nebulous.\u000a\u000aWhen Todd Stern was asked in Bonn a few months ago about funding, the absence of specificity in his reply is revealing: \u201cThere are a variety of different kinds of institutional arrangements that could be involved,\u201d he said. \u201cYou could be talking about a centralised fund. You could be talking about using the existing different kinds of resources lodged in different institutions.\u201d He went on to observe that the question of funding is complicated.\u000a\u000aIt is not that there are no funds available in the world, but today each country needs them to get out of the economic pit. When that will happen is uncertain. The US, a leading polluter emitting about 2 giga-tonnes (gt) of CO{-2}, is in deep trouble. (The figure of 2gt is according to Mr Todd Stern; however, other estimates put the US\u2019 emissions close to 6gt.) It is, however, inconceivable that it will set apart funds without seeking a commensurate gain to itself.\u000a\u000aClearly, the toughest arm-wrestle will happen over the de-linking of funds and benefits to the giver. This is an area where India and other developing countries might be pressured for a compromise, which they must resist. \u201cWe cannot be hustled into an agreement,\u201d Mr Jairam Ramesh told Business Line last week. And that is exactly why he, like Mr Kamal Nath in Geneva last year, may well leave Copenhagen with an unfinished agenda.\u000a\u000aClash of the titans\u000a\u000aMr Stern once said that he was well aware of the \u201chistorical affection\u201d for the year 1990 \u2014 the year that Europe and others want to fix as the baseline for agreeing on emission reduction targets.\u000a\u000aThe base year for emission targets has become a contentious issue and 1990 is perhaps as good a benchmark as any. But the US\u2019 \u2018hysterical disaffection\u2019 for the year 1990 is more easily explained. By wanting to peg the base year as 2005, the US wants to tom-tom a more respectable figure of \u201c17 per cent\u201d reduction by 2020. The same effort, with the base year as 1990, works out to 4 per cent. The world\u2019s second leading polluter obviously does not want to be seen as having achieved only such a limited reduction.\u000a\u000aChina wants the US to reduce its emissions by 40 per cent of 1990 levels. The huge hiatus between the two positions is the second reason why the Copenhagen talks are not likely to succeed. The current climate talks are reminiscent of the Cold War talks between the US and the Soviet Union. Only, this time, it is China sitting across the table from the US. The two are the most polluting countries in the world, accounting for 40 per cent of the GHG emissions. Each is reluctant to move unless the other does first, and China, with its development-first agenda, is not likely to move much, even if the US does so first.\u000a\u000aComparing the climate negotiations to the Cold War jostle, a recent New York Times article observed that instead of mega-tonnes of nuclear warheads, this time it is giga-tonnes of carbon. And carbon, just like the nukes, is putting the world at peril and the fate of the planet rests, again, with just two countries \u2014 the US, a historic polluter, and China, current polluter.\u000a\u000aChina, India\u000a\u000aSixteen of the world\u2019s 20 most polluted cities are in China. China emits 7gt of carbon into the atmosphere, which, according to the US, is four times the US emissions and six times Japan\u2019s. It is difficult to see China agreeing to emission cuts of the order required. There is no reason to suppose that the US will ease up on the stand taken at Kyoto, that unless China (and India) are brought within the purview of targeted emission reductions, it will not play ball.\u000a\u000aUnfortunately, this is not good for India, which has tall green ambitions and needs both technology and funds to realise them. The bulk of India\u2019s pollution (which, incidentally, is 1 tonne a person a year, as compared with 4 tonnes in China and 19 tonnes in the US), happens from coal-based power plants. Even such of those efficiency-enhancing technologies that are within reach \u2014 super and ultra supercritical and CFBC, to name two \u2014 are expensive.\u000a\u000aIndeed, India needs more than this \u2014 it needs technologies for carbon capture and sequestration (CCS). CCS is an evolving area. India is in a unique position to emerge a leader in the development of these technologies, but it is very difficult to do so without external financial and intellectual resources. The urgency in the conclusion of climate negotiations is greater than in trade talks. Any protraction in negotiations is not good.\u000a\u000a( blfeedback@thehindu.co.in)\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated September 4, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated
