aVEven as over 170 countries get ready to attend a crucial summit on global climate change at Copenhagen in December, its echoes are being heard at the ministerial summit on the Doha Round held in New Delhi.\u000a\u000aAddressing a conference organised by Ficci on Thursday, WTO director general Pascal Lamy said trade measures cannot be the only means to address climate change problems.\u000a\u000aRelying on trade measures to fix global environment problems will not work. I am of the firm conviction that the relationship between international trade and indeed the WTOand climate change would be best defined as a follow up to a consensual international accord on climate change that successfully embraces all major problems, Lamy said\u000a\u000aThe Copenhagen summit is taking place in the backdrop of a warming planet due to enhanced emission of green-house gases like carbon-dioxide. Usually, enhanced global trade leads to more emission of green-house gases. But it is felt that the climate change initiative can lead to adoption of environment friendly technologies and thus help in the bringing down emissions.\u000a\u000aAt the WTO platform, the linkage between environment related initiatives and tariff liberalisation is a grey area. Many developing countries, like India believe that environment and climate related initiatives should not be part of process like the Doha Round, which is meant for tariff liberalisation.\u000a\u000aAustralian trade minister Simon Crean on Thursday had maintained that climate change norms should be consistent with global trade rules.\u000a\u000aWhatever comes out of Copenhagen have to be WTO consistent. There cant be another set of rules that are not WTO consistent. I think that some trade ministers have to get engaged in these negotiations. That is a clear area that we need to get involved into, he said at another Ficci conference.\u000a\u000aEuropean Commission Agriculture commissioner Mariann Fischer Boel told FE that climate change is the biggest threat to farmers across the world. We need to find solutions and EC is ready to deliver financial support to developing countries so that they can deliver their share of the green house gas emission reduction commitments.
