aVM. Ramesh\u000a\u000aChennai, Sept. 4 China has assured India of solidarity with it in the forthcoming climate negotiations in Copenhagen.\u000a\u000a\u201cChina attaches the highest importance to its partnership with India on climate change issues. Negotiators on both sides have good co-ordination with each other and this will continue,\u201d says a note from the Ministry for Environment and Forests, prepared as a summary of the Minister of State for Environment and Forests Minister, Mr Jairam Ramesh\u2019s visit to China.\u000a\u000aFurther, China will inform India in advance in case it decides to take any form of voluntary commitments before Copenhagen.\u000a\u000a\u201cAt the same time, it believes that its voluntary commitments should be preceded by developed countries agreeing to cut their emissions by 40 per cent by 2020 on 1990 reference levels,\u201d the note says.\u000a\u000a(This demand of China, incidentally, is a contentious issue and a potential deal-breaker as the US is not likely to cut its emissions that much. The US wants to cut emissions to 17 per cent of 2005 levels, which roughly works out to 4 per cent of 1990 levels.)\u000a\u000aMr Ramesh met the China\u2019s Climate Change Negotiating Team led by Mr Xie Jhenhua, Vice Chairman of the National Development and Reforms Commission, Beijing, on August 24.\u000a\u000aChina, like India, believes that finance and technology are key to a successful agreement at Copenhagen. It also agrees with India\u2019s view that countries that are making significant additions to their forest and tree cover should be recognised and rewarded as part of any global agreement.\u000a\u000aChina has entered into an MoU with the US on co-operation in energy efficiency and renewable energy without prejudice to its basic negotiating position. It has briefed India on this MoU and would appreciate India keeping China informed about its bilateral engagement on climate change with the US.\u000a\u000aTechnical workshop\u000a\u000aTo take this co-operation forward, the two countries will organise a technical workshop in New Delhi on October 24 and 25 to discuss the implementation of each other\u2019s national action plans on climate change.\u000a\u000aThe Chinese also told the Indian team that they are not happy with the \u201c2 degree\u201d reference in the L\u2019Aquilla Declaration of the Major Economies Forum. The Declaration \u201crecognised the scientific view that the increase in global average temperature above pre-industrial levels ought not to exceed 2 degrees Celsius,\u201d a goal to be achieved by 2050. China regards this \u201cas one of the many scientific views, not a definitive finding,\u201d the note says.\u000a\u000aThis, again, is a significant point because China\u2019s stance is crucial to the successful conclusion of Copenhagen talks.\u000a\u000aChina is the world\u2019s largest GHG emitter (17 per cent of population and 23 per cent of emissions). India with 16 per cent of population accounts for around 4.6 per cent of emissions. China and the US account for 40 per cent of global emissions.\u000a\u000aChina and India have also agreed to set up a joint expert working group to prepare an action plan for co-operation in forests and carbon sequestration, afforestation management and technology, forestry survey and monitoring, wildlife management, including tiger conservation. First meeting of the working group will be held in Beijing in the first half of November 2009.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated September 5, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
