aVHow does the West know that people in the developing countries will mind the suffering caused by global warming more than they would the suffering caused by slower growth?\u000a\u000aEconomic climate, political climate, social climate and, finally, the mother of them all, the real climate, meaning weather, environment, glaciers, oceans, and, above all, the ozone layer \u2014 all are said to be worse today than say, a decade ago. That is probably true but it also worth bearing in mind that each has helped make the other one worse. More importantly, perhaps, while the economic, political and social climates can be improved by some minor tweaking of policies and governance, the real climate is largely autonomous and likely to be only mildly affected by what we puny humans do or don\u2019t do.\u000a\u000aNevertheless, as the Copenhagen Conference approaches, this essential truth has been abandoned in favour of policy-tweaking because, presumably, they satisfy more urgent economic, political and social needs. But even that doesn\u2019t wash because of what the numbers show: India\u2019s total GHG emissions are about 5 per cent of global emissions and its per capita emissions are perhaps a twentieth of the US and a tenth of Western Europe and Japan. The West admits that the warming problem has been caused by it because it deposited all that stock of carbon in the atmosphere in the last 150 years. Nor does it deny that all this depositing has enabled it to achieve its current standard of living. But it does deny that it wants to maintain this standard of living by asking India and China to go slow on growth.\u000a\u000aThe Minister of State for Environment and Forests, Mr Jairam Ramesh, has recently been quoted as saying \u201cWe are looking forward to a fair and equitable agreement that recognises the common and differentiated responsibility principle\u2026An agreement that is flexible enough to have agreement in areas where there is relatively less discord\u2026\u201d As Minister, he is obliged to sound reasonable but India is surely free to act more aggressively because, not to put too fine a point on it, this is the first time in several centuries that the developing countries have the upper hand. Not only do they have morality on their side \u2014 which they always did anyway \u2014 they also have the gun in their hands. If they don\u2019t reduce emissions who will suffer more \u2014 the developing countries or the West? You will, says the West, but in that case why is it so bothered? The truth is that the West is worried more about its own standard of living than about the fate of the developing countries. But it is trying to frighten the latter and is succeeding. Also, the real question still remains: how does the West know that people in the developing countries will mind the suffering caused by global warming more than they would the suffering caused by slower growth?\u000a\u000aRelated Stories:\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated September 7, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated
