aVOur Bureau\u000a\u000aNew Delhi, Sept. 8 Noted economist and Nobel laureate, Prof Michael Spence, has advocated a softer approach in upcoming climate change negotiations that allows developing countries to meet their growth ambitions, while allowing them to adopt measures progressively to lower emissions.\u000a\u000aProf Spence, who chairs the Commission on Growth and Development, has said that in the long-term, success in curbing emissions depends on the adoption of technological advances and making it available to the developing bloc.\u000a\u000aLobbying is currently on to coax major developing economies, led by India and China, to agree to a low-carbon future and caps on greenhouse gas emissions in the run-up to United Nations talks on climate change in Copenhagen in December.\u000a\u000aIn a working paper titled Climate Change, Mitigation, and Developing Country Growth, Prof Spence has said the consequences of a failure to reach an agreement in Copenhagen could be \u201cfar-reaching and long term.\u201d\u000a\u000a\u201cThe most basic output that is required is a shared understanding of feasible paths that achieve the long-term CO{-2} global emission target\u2026 Trying to get commitments to long-term target emissions from developed and developing countries is unwise and unlikely to result in an agreement,\u201d Prof Spence said in the report.\u000a\u000a\u201cLong-term targets pose significant risks to developing countries. If pursued, this approach will produce a stand-off, followed by growing controversy and attempts to increase pressure, which could spill over into other aspects of international trade and capital flows.\u201d\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated September 9, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
