aVUpdated: Sep 9 2009, 06:13am hrs\u000a\u000aWith about three months to go for the Copenhagen meet on climate change, India on Tuesday listed its key expectations, including financial compensation for its afforestation initiatives, extension of the Clean Development Mechanism (CDM) and an international agreement on green technology transfer from developed to developing countries.\u000a\u000aThe outcome of the summit depends on these three keys issues, said minister for state for environment & forests Jairam Ramesh while addressing an Idea Exchange programme organised by The Express Group in New Delhi on Tuesday.\u000a\u000aRamesh said India, which is adding 1 million hectare of forests through various programmes, must be financially compensated. While we have earned around $6 billion through carbon credits, there is a real need to expand the CDM, Ramesh said.\u000a\u000aNobel laureate and Commission on Growth & Development chairman Michael Spence endorsed that view. There is every reason for the extension of the CDM accord beyond 2012, when it runs out, he said.
