aVUnctad economists contend that climate change mitigation must be seen as a process of structural change that not only entails adjustment burdens for households, firms and economies, but also offers opportunities for product and process innovation, and income growth. Discussing the causes and implications of climate change in its Trade and Development Report, 2009, Unctad compares climate change mitigation process to that of mechanisation, motorisation, digitalisation and other processes of structural change and points out that various synergies are possible between GHG emission reductions and the objective of enhancing development.\u000a\u000aThe report is univocal in pointing out that developed economies must assume the lead in climate change mitigation because they account for the largest share of accumulated GHGs in the atmosphere. Also, they have greater economic, technological and administrative capacities for shifting to a low-carbon economy. The report notes that contribution to climate change mitigation is also in the interest of developing and transition economies.\u000a\u000aThis is especially so since scientific research has suggested that the humanitarian, social and economic consequences of global warming, if unabated, will be dramatic and the negative impact will be particularly strong in most developing countries. Estimates indicate that temperature increases could reach 6 by the end of the century from the mean temperature of 1980-99, if the current upward trend in GHG emissions is not reversed in the coming decades.\u000a\u000aPointing out that the current levels of accumulated GHGs have been influenced largely by the behaviour of consumers and producers the report notes that there are very different levels of emissions for similar levels of development. For instance, CO2 emissions per capita in the US are more than twice the level found in European countries or in Japan, which are at similar levels of development. The large difference in CO2 emissions between the US, Europe and Japan reflects, among other things, different degrees of application of existing technologies. For example, if Chinese coal power plants were to reach the average efficiency of Japanese plants, China would consume 20% less coal.\u000a\u000aThe report notes that stringent restrictions on emissions in developed countries alone will not make a substantial impact on climate change mitigation. This is because most of the growth in GHG emissions over the past four decades has taken place outside developed countries. Thus, while the share of developed countries in total current GHG emissions fell considerably over the past 35 years, this tendency is expected to persist in the coming decades, primarily on account of the strong economic growth projected for developing countries, especially for China and India.\u000a\u000aThe strong growth in energy consumption in developing countries has led to a sharp rise in CO2 emissions. Developing countries accounted for 41% of global energy related CO2 emissions in 2006, compared with some 26% in 1990. By 2020, developing countries are expected to contribute to more than half of global energy-related CO2 emissions and for an even larger share (56%) by 2030. Chinas share in energy-related CO2 emissions is projected to increase from about 20% to nearly 30% by 2030. China, India and West Asia combined are projected to account for more than 40% of global CO2 emissions in 2030, up from some 30% in 2006.\u000a\u000aApart from climate change the GHG emissions will not only increase global warming but also impact the quality of life in many other ways such as changing rainfall patterns, receding glaciers, melting ice caps and rising sea levels. According to most scientific studies, climate change will also result in a higher frequency and intensity of extreme weather events (for example, droughts, floods, storms), declining water resources, increased transmission of vector-borne diseases (for example, malaria) and loss of biodiversity.\u000a\u000aThe report points out that improving the prospects for development and poverty reduction would require a sharp reduction of GHG emissions to a level that would limit the temperature increase to 2-2.5C by 2050. But even in such a scenario Africa, South Asia and West Asia would likely be the worst affected. Achieving this target, which seems viable, both scientifically and politically, however, is not possible without resolute policy efforts that trigger a process of structural change towards more climate-friendly modes of consumption and production around the world.\u000a\u000aA positive change recorded in recent times is the slightly downward trend in the intensity of energy use in developing countries over the past three decades. South, East and South-East Asia, where the intensity of energy use is similar to those in developed countries, have contributed strongly to this trend. Similarly, a number of other developing countries have achieved considerable improvements in their intensity of energy use as a result of policies to strengthen overall productivity, even without the explicit objective of contributing to reducing global warming. Brazil, China, India and Mexico have reduced their CO2 emissions growth over the past three decades by some 500 million tonne per annuman amount that exceeds what the Kyoto Protocol requires them to meet.\u000a\u000aA large amount of GHG emissions could be prevented at the level of end users, through the introduction of efficiency standards and labelling and energy-efficient construction of new buildings. According to IEA estimates, a package of 25 energy efficiency measures could save up to one-fifth of the global emissions projected for 2030 in a reference scenario.\u000a\u000aNoting that much of the technology needed for reduction of greenhouse gas emissions exists but it needs to be applied widely, the report also points out that it is necessary to further develop and use new technologies and renewable sources of energy. This implies considerable potential for growththe market for renewable energy and green technologies as well as for energy-efficient cars, buildings and appliances will grow rapidly in the coming decadesprobably faster than any other market. Thus, for each country the cost of climate change depends on how much value-added resulting from the production of non-fossil energies and climate friendly equipment, appliances, and consumer goods can be generated at home.
