aVNEW DELHI: Even as India is projected to be on course to clock 7.5% growth over the next two decades, it would still remain one of the most energy efficient economies in the world.The final McKinsey and Company's "Environment and Energy Sustainability Report for India" says the Indian economy will be much greener than others who have been on a high growth path. The report had run into controversy in its draft stages with the government and some of its academic reviewers as reported earlier by TOI.But the final report still substantially corroborates Indian government's negotiating positions at the Copenhagen climate talks later this year. It concludes that India was, even without major extra efforts, on path to becoming one of the most efficient of global economies.The authors of the report go to the extent of suggesting that India has the potential to go beyond even the expected levels and achieve even more greenhouse gas emission reduction over the next two decades. "This is so because 80% of the country's infrastructure is still to be built," said Rajat Gupta, director at the consultancy, implying that the new development can be built in a more climate-friendly fashion.For achieving this, the McKinsey report points out that massive investment is required to achieve levels of emission reductions it has suggested. "It would cost 500-700 billion Euros at pure societal costs, our report concludes," Gupta said.But even these figures, some critics of the report point out, could be underdone as the report, based on an input-output model, does not take into account transactional costs, taxes and subsidies involved. It also presumes a much lower discount rate of 8% for investments made. Some economists had earlier argued that such low discount rates are more reflective of developed economies and not emerging one where risks are higher and resources lacking.The study, by sheer design, does not take into account how the greenhouse gas reduction actions would impact the economy by increasing the price of energy a factor that is crucial to study macro impacts of climate mitigation. The report suggests that by using a series of steps, including a massive upscaling in nuclear and solar power, India could reduce its emissions in 2030 from a possible 5.7 billion tonnes of carbon dioxide equivalent to 3.1. But the report points out that only 10% of this reduction in emissions from the 5.7 billion tonnes is readily achievable.
