aVM. Ramesh\u000a\u000aChennai, Sept. 9 India should publicise what it is doing in terms of mitigating climate change. This will help the international community to show India as an example of what developing countries ought to be doing, and consequently also help successful conclusion of climate negotiations, says Sir Richard Stagg, British High Commissioner in India.\u000a\u000aIn a chat with Business Line, Sir Richard said that negotiating countries should strive towards getting a broadly acceptable agreement, and not wait for a \u201cperfect\u201d agreement. He observed that in any negotiation, there will be pluses and minuses. There is nothing to be gained by waiting, he said, adding that if anything, negotiations would only become more difficult.\u000a\u000aSir Richard pointed out that the British Prime Minister, Mr Gordon Brown, had said that climate mitigation efforts would call for funds transfer of the order of $100 billion a year. This, Sir Richard said, showed that the UK realised the scale of what is required to be done.\u000a\u000aAsked where the money would come from, he said, \u201cMoney will come from, in one form or the other, from the citizens of the developed world.\u201d\u000a\u000aHe said that the developed world realised that they were the cause of the climate problem and hence bulk of the solution would need to come from them.\u000a\u000aThe transfer of funds, he said, would be in addition to the Overseas Development Assistance provided by developed countries, and not \u201cre-badging\u201d of ODA.\u000a\u000aTo cut emissions\u000a\u000aNoting that the European Union had decided to cut emissions unilaterally by 20 per cent from 1990 levels by 2020 \u2013 by 30 per cent, with global agreement \u2013 Sir Richard said that the UK would like the entire developed world to agree on similar emission reduction targets.\u000a\u000aHe said that (countries like) India should accept that transfer of funds would come only along with measures for monitoring that the funds are put to the uses they are provided for. There should also be reasonable information on what the countries are doing on their own, so that the world understands the trajectory that global emissions are following.\u000a\u000a(This is indeed India\u2019s position too\u2014as articulated in its submission to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change.)\u000a\u000aGreenhouse gas\u000a\u000aSir Richard also said that India\u2019s greenhouse gas emission levels, which are at less than 2 tonnes per person per year today, will only rise to around 3.5 tonnes by 2030 \u2013 or about 30 per cent of current emission levels of the EU. He also lauded India\u2019s efforts, such as the National Solar Mission, which seeks to build solar power capacity of 20,000 MW by 2020, and steps to increase forest cover.\u000a\u000aIn this context, he said it would be worthwhile if India talked about what it is doing in terms of mitigating the risk of climate change.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated September 10, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
