aVAnother round of negotiations on climate change has just concluded, and the issues have become clearer. The developed countries are still not prepared to discuss the specifics of what they will do to meet the global challenge. They are clearly relying on parallel processes, like the UN Secretary-General\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds High-Level Event later in September, to get us to soften our stand. As the prime minister has warned, we are going to face tremendous pressure on this issue.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aA number of strategic choices have to be made. First, we must be aware that burden sharing rather than environmental protection is the central issue in the negotiations. Second, we should understand why there is a deadlock in the negotiations and how it can be removed. Third, we need to be clear on what we should do as a responsible nation while at the same time securing our national interest.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt is important to focus on the criteria for burden sharing because the recent meeting of the Major Economies Forum decided that a global goal would be agreed before the climate conference in Copenhagen, scheduled to be held this December. Under the current framework any conclusion would lead to limitations in the trajectory of our future emissions, and show us as unreasonable and irresponsible if we did not accept. Unfortunately, there are many voices within the country concurring with this view that we must \ufffd\ufffd\ufffddo something\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd to secure a global deal to save the world.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAs a multilateral issue, climate change is unique in that only developed countries have specific obligations. As in the case of the trade negotiations, they have not met any of their commitments, including for transfer of financial resources and technology, and their submissions in the on-going negotiations remain non-committal on all these issues. Yet they are pressurising developing countries to take on commitments to limit emissions.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAccording to recent UN data for the European Commission, the champions of strong action on climate change, emissions from the energy sector increased by 2.2% in the period 1990 and 2006 \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd transportation emissions increased 25.8% and emissions from energy industries by 3.7%, despite the emissions trading scheme. Emissions in Japan and the United States have grown in double digits. The Climate Convention requires their emissions to have peaked at 1990 levels by the year 2000!\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThere is a deadlock because developed countries are not seeking a fair outcome in the negotiations. The basic assumption of global sustainability that developed countries will do whatever has to be done, laid out fifty years ago, no longer holds. This suggests the need for a new framework.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aDefining climate change in terms of assessments of damage leads to determining emissions targets and timetables. Consequently, efforts to reduce global emissions pit old against new emitters, and means that the key issue for the negotiations is when emissions of all countries will peak. Developing countries rightly see it as an effort to shift the burden onto developing countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThis environmental framework ignores the scientific evidence that energy and ecological services are directly related to human well being. Development of infrastructure, urbanisation, manufacturing, services and food production are all essential for alleviation of poverty. For example, the per capita generation of electricity in India is one-fifteenth that of the United States. Estimates suggest that currently, world-wide 1.6 billion people lack access to electricity. As developing countries still need to build their infrastructure and food security, the global leaders should really discuss how their economic growth can take place in an environmentally sustainable manner.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a
