aVIndias GDP is projected to grow fourfold to $4 trillion and its cities are expected to house close to 550 million by 2030. It makes it challenging to ensure an energy and carbon efficient growth path.\u000a\u000aA recent report, Environmental and Energy Sustainability: An Approach for India, by management consulting firm McKinsey & Company, discusses the outlook for India as the country aims to address challenges of environmental and energy sustainability. The report outlines various opportunities that could help reduce GHG emissions by 45% and reduce energy consumption by 22% by 2030.\u000a\u000aThe report suggests that India is likely to witness a dramatic growth in demand in key sectors such as power, basic materials and transport. For example, a five-fold increase in building floor space will complement a seven-fold increase in the number of vehicles on Indias roads.\u000a\u000aThe implications of this rapid economic growth are critical in terms of energy security as well as environmental sustainability. Take energy, for example. By 2030, says the report, India is likely to need between 760 gw and 790 gw of installed power capacity. Coal demand is likely to cross 2.4 billion tonne per annum. India may have to import 10 times its own production of oil and up to 40% of its coal needs by 2030. Despite the implementation of a range of measures, Indias GHG emissions could rise from 1.6 billion tonne CO2e in 2005 to 5.7 billion tonne CO2e in 2030.\u000a\u000aWhat is heartening is the fact that there still is time for correction. Rajat Gupta, director, McKinsey and co-author of the report, says, India could emerge as the worlds third largest energy consumer by 2030. However, 80% of what India could be in 2030 is yet to be built, providing the country an opportunity to effectively manage the economic and environmental costs of growing energy requirements.\u000a\u000aFor example, he adds, our research suggests that by 2030, savings in oil consumed in the road transport sector could be double of what India consumed in this sector in 2005. Further, by reducing demand for electricity, 80% of the total installed capacity could be averted and coal demand in the power sector could be halved. Leapfrogging inefficient technologies, adopting new technologies and practices that are more energy efficient could reduce GHG emissions to 3.1 billion tonne CO2e by 2030, he explains.\u000a\u000aAn analysis of McKinseys India GHG abatement cost curvea map of the countrys abatement opportunities in 10 of the largest consuming and GHG emitting sectors ranked from lowest-cost to highest-cost optionssuggests that the opportunities to reduce GHG emissions are concentrated in five areas: clean power; energy-efficient industry; green transportation; sustainable habitats; and sustainable agriculture and forestry.
