aVNEW DELHI: In an attempt to rid itself of the obstructionist tag, India has indicated its willingness to voluntarily take on unilateral mitigation measures with broadly indicative targets as part of its response to climate change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe government is considering a law on the lines of the Fiscal Responsibility and Budget Management Act, which would have broad indicative targets but not mandatory targets. Sources said first draft of the proposed legislation is being considered by the minister of state for environment and forests Jairam Ramesh.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThis voluntary and unilateral move could give Indian negotiators more room to maneuver in the run-up to and during the Copenhagen meet. India is willing to take on a larger menu of mitigation measures as long as it is consistent with growth, but it continues to be firm on its position that it will not take on legally binding targets.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThis will help convey what Mr Ramesh considers to be the single-most important message that India needs to give the world \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdwe are proactive, constructive, we want a fair and equitable agreement in Copenhagen\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd. He argues India needs to rethink its approach to mitigation and accept it as a responsibility to the Indian people and not under pressure from the global community. The move to do things voluntarily was unveiled by Mr Ramesh at an event organised by CII for the Danish Prime Minister Lars Lokke Rasmussen. Mr Ramesh said: \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdIndia could have a legislative agenda for (GHG) mitigation which will bring credibility to the actions through domestic political consensus.\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe proposed law like FRBM will outline recommendation. Its rules could list out various steps with broadly indicative targets in the 2020-2030 period. Mr Ramesh said it could be mandated that by 2030 15% of electricity is from renewable sources, or that all public buildings be energy-conservation compliant, or allocate percentage of agricultural land to organic farming. The minister said India should take on mitigation responsibility on its own, and \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdstop looking at world as source of technology, India can be a world leader in some areas like coal combustion and nuclear fast-breeder reactors\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIndia has maintained that its per capita emissions will always be lower than the developed countries. However, the per capita argument has come under attack from the developed world on account of india\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds rising population. During her visit to India, US secretary of state Hillary Clinton argued in her meetings with Jairam Ramesh that since India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds population goes up on an average by 14 million people a year, India was hiding its emissions behind its increasing population.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThough India is not abandoning its per capita argument, the minister believes that it is time to move to a position of actual mitigation. He said that a law could be considered that would embody India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds mitigation efforts, which would have to pass muster in Parliament. Mr Ramesh made it clear that India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds efforts at mitigation would be voluntary and unilateral, and would have to be in keeping with our growth efforts.
