aVNEW DELHI: Taking a position that echoes the Indian stance, the World Bank has urged developed countries to step up their funding on clean air research and mitigation efforts in the developing world. Holding the economically advanced countries responsible for much of the greenhouse gas emissions of the past, the Bank put the onus of creating a \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdclimate smart world\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd on the developed world.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aMaking the case, the Bank\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds World Development Report 2010 \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd Development and Climate Change states that development will get harder with climate change and developing countries will be disproportionately affected by it.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe report notes that growth and poverty alleviation remain the overarching priority for developing countries and that climate change will only complicate this challenge. For India, which has been considered by the developed world as obstructionist, this validation by the World Bank will come in handy.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aCountries like India have refused to accept legally binding emission targets and demanded that the developed world shoulder the cost of the damage caused by their historical emissions. India has maintained that while it is not unmindful of its responsibilities, it will not take any steps that would undermine its growth trajectory. The Bank\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds report reiterates this view.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt says that developed countries, which produced most of the greenhouse gas emissions of the past, must act now. These countries can ramp up funding for mitigation in developing countries, where most future growth in emissions will occur. This, the Bank maintains would be an \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdequitable deal\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWorld Bank president Robert Zoellick said: \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdDeveloping countries are disproportionately affected by climate change \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd a crisis that is not of their making and for which they are the least prepared. For that reason, an equitable deal in Copenhagen is vitally important.\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe report calls on industrialised countries to make rapid cuts in their greenhouse gas output, to create \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdemissions space\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd that would allow rising fossil fuel use in the developing world. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdHigh-income countries can and must reduce their carbon footprints. They cannot continue to fill up an unfair and unsustainable share of the atmospheric commons,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd the report states.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAt the same time, the report makes the case that there is scope for developing countries to shift to lower-carbon trajectories without compromising development. But this ability varies from country to country. The extent to which developing countries can make this transition will depend on the extent of financial and technical assistance from high-income countries.
