aVOur Bureau\u000a\u000aHyderabad, Sept. 16 The Government of India will unveil a new policy on solar energy on November 14, as part of its target to produce 20,000 MW of solar power by 2020.\u000a\u000aThe policy will aim at bringing down cost of solar energy and will be industry-friendly to promote investments in the sector, the Union Minister for New and Renewable Energy, Dr Farooq Abdullah, told newspersons here on Wednesday.\u000a\u000aThe Minister will take up with the Finance Minister the need to review Customs duty on certain components used in solar energy equipment.\u000a\u000aAlthough he did not spell out the contours of the policy, he indicated that it will contain a slew of concessions and \u201clots of financial inputs\u201d for companies manufacturing solar power equipment.\u000a\u000aThe idea, he pointed out, is to reduce the manufacturing cost of such equipment.\u000a\u000aAdmitting that solar power generation lagged wind power in India, he said the new policy will spur growth in this sector. \u201cI dream to see every house in India having a solar panel,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aThe Government has taken an initiative to make Shirdi run by renewable energy, Dr Abdullah said, adding that it is planning similar initiatives for other religious places such as Tirupati and Ajmer.\u000a\u000a\u201cAs these places are visited by a large number of people, they can see the benefits of using renewable energy,\u201d he pointed out.\u000a\u000aTest Facility\u000a\u000aDr Abdullah said a testing and accreditation facility for solar products would be set up at the FabCity near the Shamshabad International Airport.\u000a\u000aHe was responding to the Andhra Pradesh Chief Minister, Mr K. Rosaiah, who said the late Chief Minister Y.S. Rajasekhara Reddy had requested the facility.\u000a\u000aThe Minister formally launched the phase-I manufacturing facility set up by Solar Semiconductor, for the manufacture of PV modules and solar cells at the FabCtiy.\u000a\u000aSolar Semiconductor has set up a Reliability Lab, solar water pumping facility on its 50-acre campus at FabCity. It is investing up to $100 million in the Phase-I unit, which would have an installed capacity to manufacture 120 MW solar PV modules and 60 MW solar cell lines.\u000a\u000aEarlier, Dr Abdullah also released the brochure for SolarCon India 2009, the global exhibition-cum-conference on solar energy related issues slated to be held in Hyderabad from November 9 to 11.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated September 17, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated
