aVNEW DELHI: Environment minister Jairam Ramesh\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds proposal to bring in an overarching legislation to reduce greenhouse gas emissions appears to be complicating India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds position in the global negotiations.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aEven domestically, Mr Ramesh is treading on the turfs of power, renewable energy and agriculture. By setting targets, the proposed legislation is likely to impact functioning of these ministries as well.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAccording to sources, at the recently concluded meeting of the Major Economies Forum (MEF) in Washington, India was informally asked why it still opposed internationally binding emission targets if it was planning a binding domestic legislation.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWhile this matter was discussed on the sidelines of the MEF meeting, it may come up more forcefully at negotiations leading up to Copenhagen. The Indian negotiating team could find itself in a bind, having to defend domestic binding targets even while rejecting internationally binding caps.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aMr Ramesh accepts that there has been a \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdnuanced shift\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd in the Indian position. However, the minister holds that there has been no shift in India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds negotiating stand. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdThe stand remains the same. We are not going to accept any legally binding commitments on carbon emissions,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd Mr Ramesh argues. However, the matter may not be that simple. A domestic legislation may give Indian administrators the muscle to move to a low-carbon development trajectory.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aHowever, if India is unable to meet its domestically set goals, it could weaken its position in subsequent negotiations. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdIndia has always made a big deal about living up to its commitments. What happens if India fails to meet targets set for itself,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd an expert involved in the negotiations asked. There is every possibility of India not being able to live up to the goals that the proposed legislation will set.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe proposed legislation suggests increasing the share of renewable as a source of electricity bought by a distributor. This could impact the power ministry\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds attempt to keep the unit cost of electricity low, thereby impacting other targets.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAt the global level, a national commitment for domestic targets could make it difficult for India to access finance and technology. The EU would like to ascertain that India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds effort is indeed \ufffd\ufffd\ufffda deviation from business as usual\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd before making any commitment. This could mean that India would have to open up for international review and verification, a move that it has resisted so far.
