aVJairam Ramesh finally got India out of the box on climate change. We can accept the implementation of the favoured alternative of our energy policy and accept it as a commitment, because we should do it anyway. We can occupy the high ground again. Having modelled this for Rio Plus Ten, I am happy. This can mean that we play a leadership role, if we ignore the babus who know all and therefore nothing. It may be useful, for starters, to get back to first principles.\u000a\u000aIn the week leading to October 2, my favourite is Gandhi. Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi is difficult. The social psychologist Erik Erikson includes him as one of the truly greats through human civilisation, someone who really changed the world. Women and men who are so great that not only do they have an alternative vision, but they have developed the style of implementing it with the kind of energy and detail that after they are gone you can neither meet their expectations, nor ignore them. Gandhiji did that as he was growing up and perfected it in his mediation, Erikson says,\u000a\u000abetween the siblings Ambalal Sarabhai and his sister in the Ahmedabad textile strike and the dispute between the mill owners, Ambalal and the Majoor Mahajan she presided over.\u000a\u000aThe truly disturbing thing about Gandhiji is that whenever you come across him, you cannot ignore him because he is disturbingly contemporaneous, across decades. He matters through time and space. In the early '70s, I worked on an experts committee on employment. I read a lot, but there was in fact very little relevant material apart from Gandhi. Land was in short supply, so the poor man could be given a goat, he argued in Young India. The doodhwala was to perfect that one. Towards the end of the last century the Gandhi Smarak Nidhi asked fifty Indians to give fifty lectures on Gandhi in the fiftieth year of independence. I worked hard like the others and looked at Gandhi in the 21st century. As always remarkably fresh. There is enough for everybody's need, he said, but not their greed. By the time India and China reach a quarter of the OECD's living standards, the world, we argued in the Hague Declaration drafted by Jan Pronk and Mahbub ul Haq for forty of us, will not be there, so something has to be done before that and Kyoto followed. The agenda included communities looking after land and water or the deserts and soil and sea erosion would engulf us. Gandhiji was again there  the man who in a practical way talked of the village commons, of the need to look after not only your house, but also the space outside.\u000a\u000aHe anticipated the great turn of history in the '80s of the last century. The "large" became unfashionable and uneconomic as the new technology took over. The neo-Fordist era it was called, the era after the Model T. By the early '90s the great think tanks the world over were screaming their heads off. The new technology can spread to the small man, and will do so if the interdisciplinary knowledge prerequisites are there. Otherwise vast areas and peoples will be left out. This was quintessential Gandhi. Not against technology, but wanting to empower the crying child left outside the door. Gandhi knew that it wasn't the technology. Technology would only help. It was the man behind the machine and, more important, the organisations behind it all. These had to be based on the people. It was an infuriatingly simple and powerful message. He told the colonisers, discovered by some for "good governance", that we were right and they were wrong and they had to go. It was as simple as that. Your empire is the mightiest power on the globe. But you are wrong, we are right and you will have to go. He built such a great machine around that simple idea that the sun had to set on empire.\u000a\u000aThe writer, a former Union minister, is chairman, Institute of Rural Management, Anand express@expressindia.com\u000a\u000aALSO READ Degrees of irresponsibility\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
