aVWhat view the Government takes of taxing incomes from carbon credits remains to be seen.\u000a\u000aThe corporate world is still finding its feet on accounting norms for carbon credits, a huge incentive to pursue projects under the Clean Development Mechanism.\u000a\u000aRamakrishnan Vaidyanathan\u000a\u000aSivabalan Sekhar\u000a\u000aTo set the record straight, the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) adopted the Kyoto Protocol (the Protocol) in February 2005 to address the threat of global warming. The Protocol limited greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions by countries and has currently classified the globe into \u2018Annex I countries\u2019 (developed nations in the European Union, among others) and \u2018host countries\u2019 (developing or under-developed nations in the Asian or African continents, for instance).\u000a\u000aThe Annex I countries\u2019 GHG emissions, under phase 2 of the protocol, need to fall to 92 per cent of their 1990 baseline levels during the committed period between 2008 and 2012; the host countries do not have any such targets owing to their low GHG emissions.\u000a\u000aNow, moving to the accounting context of the protocol, the corporate in Annex I countries would buy \u2018carbon credits\u2019, which are allowances equal to the amount of emissions allowed, and accordingly get reflected in the financial statements.\u000a\u000aTo make this mechanism a success, market-based transactions such as Clean Development Mechanism (CDM), in which India has demonstrated an increasing momentum, have been laid down by the protocol wherein entities in host countries can develop GHG reduction projects.\u000a\u000aConsequently, such Certified Emission Reductions (CERs); that is, certified projects under CDM earn carbon credits and sell the same to companies in Annex I countries through an exchange.\u000a\u000aThe accounting for CERs prescribed by various generally accepted accounting principles (GAAPs) has recently evoked much attention because of ambiguities relating to recording, measurement and disclosure of such transactions. The Institute of Chartered Accountants of India (ICAI), too, has issued an exposure draft for guidance on accounting for self-generated CERs (the draft) which requires certain anomalies to be ironed out; the draft is recommendatory in nature.\u000a\u000aACCOUNTING AMBIGUITIES\u000a\u000aReflecting conservative accounting, the draft recommends that entities should record revenue only on sale of CERs; that is, neither after the receipt of certification by the designated authority (that is, the CDM Board) nor on the commencement of the project.\u000a\u000aThe CERs, contingent upon the project certification, bear the nature of contingent assets and hence, should not be brought into the balance sheet, goes the rationale. The draft could have considered the treatment stipulated by AS12, Accounting for Government Grants, wherein revenue is accrued on reasonable assurance of complying with related conditions.\u000a\u000aResearch and development expenses and pre-implementation costs of the project ought to be charged-off rather than being inventoried; only costs such as certification expenses for CERs would be recorded as assets on receipt of certification.\u000a\u000aMoreover, such recording of assets need to be classified as inventory rather than intangible assets since CERs are not held for use in the production or supply of goods or services by the entities. However, depreciation needs to be accounted as period costs which is otherwise usually absorbed into cost of inventories.\u000a\u000aRevenue-to-cost mismatches may arise through such treatment, further compounded by costs which would be insignificant in comparison to the revenue from sale of CERs.\u000a\u000aTiming mismatches are also bound to arise since costs relating to the certification are recorded in one financial period and sale of CERs would occur in another period. Also, the thumb-rule of stating inventory at net realisable value remains applicable to CERs.\u000a\u000aCONFUSED CORPORATES\u000a\u000aAs the draft remains silent on the event of withdrawal of the CERs, all costs inventoried till-date should be written-off. Questions on \u2018whether income on receipt of CERs needs to be classified as part of revenue, other income or non-operating income?\u2019 remain open in the draft. Besides, ceteris paribus, would revenue from CERs be reported as an exclusive business segment?\u000a\u000aWhile being less complex than derivatives transactions, the supposed naivete of the corporates vis--vis the vagaries in treatment of financial transactions under the Protocol have resulted in many deliberations across board-rooms.\u000a\u000aInterestingly, how the Exchequer treats carbon incomes for purposes of taxation and the associated implications also remain to be seen.\u000a\u000aFor future cash-flow purposes, disclosures of relevant information on the cost of underlying CDM projects and expected realisations from sale of CERs would be greatly beneficial.\u000a\u000aIt is expected that in 2012, when the commitment period under Phase 2 ceases, the emissions exchange would be highly active resulting in boosted earnings of many entities. Thus, it is worth debating if the draft satisfies all parameters related to the pronounced treatments. Around the world, accounting for the Protocol looks murkier with efforts by various bodies having become defunct.\u000a\u000aFor example, the IFRIC 3, Emission Rights, issued as part of the International Financial Reporting Standards (IFRS), was withdrawn after considerable pressure from business communities although accounting for the \u2018cap and trade\u2019 scheme was well aligned with the IFRS. Another example \u2014 EITF Issue 03-14, released by the Emerging Issues Task Force (EITF) under the US GAAP \u2014 stands withdrawn from its agenda.\u000a\u000a(Ramakrishnan is with Deloitte and Sivabalan with ICRA. Their views are personal.)\u000a\u000aCarbon money is a huge incentive offered by the Protocol for the corporate world to pursue projects under the CDM. The probability of sustaining the desired GHG targets through CDM projects would also weigh heavily on the funding arrangements between the potential buyers of funds and the sellers. The impending ratification of the Protocol by nations such as the US, Australia and Canada further casts a long shadow on the successful accomplishment of its objectives.The damage that man has caused to Nature has resulted in the adoption of policies such as the Kyoto Protocol, soon to be replaced by a new and more relevant version after the Copenhagen climate meet in December.But, strangely, wouldn't financial tweaking to make the protocol more acceptable take these `future-saving' policy decisions to the fringes of greed?\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated October 1, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
