aVNEW DELHI: India, along with the G-77 and China, have resisted yet another attempt by developed countries to impose legally binding emission reduction targets on developing countries. Developed countries, led by United States, Australia and Canada, sought to introduce a \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdnew framework\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd for \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdcommon mitigation action\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd by all countries. While the demand is not new, there has been considerable apprehension that the pressure would intensify following India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds offer to provide annual reports under the UNFCC and announcment of its plans to legislate greenhouse gas emissions.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAt ongoing meeting of the Ad-hoc Working Group on Long-term Cooperative Action in Bangkok, the United States suggested that some common mitigation actions could be placed in national schedules of all countries and these would be subject to international review. Developing countries, particularly Brazil, India and China strongly opposed this proposal arguing that it was an attempt \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdto impose new commitments and obligations\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd, which were contrary to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe differential treatment of developed and developing countries is clearly laid out in the Kyoto Protocol and the Bali Action Plan. Developed countries have, on account of their historical emissions, \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdmitigation commitments\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd, that is legally binding emission reduction targets while developing countries undertake mitigation action, which is dependent on finance and technology support. Developing countries take action that is considered nationally appropiate, that is keeping in mind the country\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds growth , poverty eradication and development needs.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIndia and other developing countries argued that the proposal put forward by United States, Canada, Australia and European Union was an attempt to blur this differential treatment. The proposed obligations would be in contravention of the Kyoto Protocol and Bali Action Plan.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIndia took the opportunity to stress that the developing countries are nto in a position to take on mitigation actions unless the developed or Annex 1 countries agreed to providing financial resources to meet the incremental cost of taking on these measures. India has also objected to the redefining of funds from developed countries as \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdassistance\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd as this would mean that developing countries would have to commit resources to undertake mitigation actions. This would necessarily impact their poverty eradication and development programmes.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aClimate change experts in India have been apprehensive that New Delhi\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds offer of annual reports under the UNFCCC would ultimately result in opening up for international monitoring, verification and reporting. At Bangkok, the Indian negotiators sought to drive home the point that India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds offer was one of showing flexibility in order to ensure a positive outcome at Copenhagen.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aUnder the Kyoto Protocol, which expires in 2012, only developed countries are committed to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and submit annual reports on their measures. Developing countries are required to submit a \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdnational communication\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd report every six years to the UNFCCC. The report is generic and can\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdt be questioned or scrutinised by other countries. The US proposal in Bangkok sought to bring mitigation actions of developing nations under the purview of international review.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe Indian negotiators stressed that imposing reporting and review obligations on developing countries would be in conflict with the UNFCC. and it distorts the concept of responsibility for causing climate channge under the Convention. China, too argued that developed countries have to take the lead to reduce emissions, not only because of their financial and technological ability but because of their historical responsibilities.
