aVNEW DELHI: New Delhi\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds attempt to recapture the narrative of climate change came in for a shock at the 7th session of the Ad-hoc Working Group on Long-term Cooperative Action in Bangkok. Minister of state for environment Jairam Ramesh\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds offer of annual reporting under the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change was cited by the US and other developed countries to do away with the differential treatment of developed and developing countries under the Kyoto Protocol and Bali Action Plan.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe US, EU, Australia, Canada, Russia Norway and Japan sought to present the offer by Mr Ramesh as an overture to treat developing countries like India at par with developed countries when it comes to mitigation commitments. The Convention and the Bali Action Plan clearly differentiate between the mitigation commitments of developed countries which are economy wide and mitigation actions of developing countries under nationally appropriate actions.\u000a\u000aThe Bangkok incident only served to strengthen the growing apprehension that India may have to compromise on its stated stance\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdno internationally binding emission targets and no monitoring, reporting and verification of unsupported measures. The government, however, steadfastly maintains that this view is rather alarmist.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aInstead it argues that India is merely offering to provide more detailed and regular reports. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdThere is already a legal obligation on part of developing countries to provide reports on norms developed by the IPCC. India is merely offering to make this more detailed and regular. it is no more than that already agreed to,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd a senior official said.\u000a\u000aUnder the Kyoto Protocol, which expires in 2012, only developed countries are committed to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and submit annual reports on their measures. Developing countries are required to submit a \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdnational communication\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd report every six years to the UN climate body. The report is generic and can\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdt be questioned or scrutinised by other countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aLike other developing countries, India too would like an outcome at Copenhagen. The government argues that the offer of annual reporting is an attempt to ensure an outcome. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdIf all parties to the negotiations remain rigid in their positions how can we expect an outcome at Copenhagen?\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd a government official asked.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aCountering the view that India has diluted its position, Prime Minister\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds Special Envoy on Climate Change Shyam Saran said, \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdIn order to be constructive and promote an agreement, we are prepared to be flexible and address some of the concerns raised by developed countries.\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdWithout giving up on our critical interests, we are prepared to report our domestic climate change related actions in our National Communication to the UNFCCC, which could be made more regular and detailed, through an agreement in the current negotiations.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aFor India this is not a problem,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd he stressed.\u000a\u000aWhile the official view is that India has not weakened it stance, but merely shown flexibility, there is a growing concern that perhaps India has opened its cards a little too early. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdEven if the government had to make this offer of an annual reporting, it should have done so at a later date. After all, this offer is in the nature of a bargaining chip. With the offer on the table, India has nothing more to give away, and international monitoring could well be the next thing that is on the table,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd an expert close to the negotiations said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aSince he put the offer on the table, Mr Ramesh has explained that it isn\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdt a sellout by India as the only forum for accountability is Parliament. Instead that the country needs to be \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdmore confident\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd about itself. The minister has argued that the offer of an annual report is about having an \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdhonest discussion\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd and put all issues on the discussion table.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aSources close to the negotiations argue that while there is broad agreement on the importance and need for transparency, this should be done on India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds terms. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdThe question is not about transparency. The act of reporting means providing material to an international agency on parameters acceptable to them. Once that is done it opens the door for more questioning. It is alright for India to state its climate change policy in terms of demand side management but the moment it is done in terms of emission equivalents, there is the chance that verification will follow\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd, a climate change expert said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aExperts argue that in some measure, India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds recent \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdflexibility\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd and its desire to be a \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdpart of the solution\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd is a function of the \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdIndia now sits at the high table\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd syndrome. But there are others who argue that the spate of concessions being made by New Delhi in the fortnight could be seen as an effort not to be isolated and at the same time demonstrate that it is willing to pull its weight in dealing with climate change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aChina has announced domestic measures to demonstrate its responsiveness to climate change. Last week, China took a significant step towards lower emissions by saying it would set a carbon intensity target, that is the rate at which fossil fuels are used compared with GDP. China is also expected to unveil a law that would set domestic targets for GHG emissions.\u000a\u000a
