aVMake hay while the suns shines could well be the mantra for most people serious about renewables and energy conversation. The capital will witness yet another event on renewable energy tomorrow and day after.\u000a\u000aRenewables: helping rural development, is a two-day international congress on renewable energy (ICORE) being organised by the Solar Energy Society of India (SESI) and supported by the ministry of new and renewable energy, ministry of science and technology, ministry of power, ministry of rural development and the government of NCT.\u000a\u000aThe congress promises to have important sessions on helping rural development, distributed generation, photovoltaic technologies, solar thermal application, biomass ultilisation, small hydro power, hybrid systems, economics, policies and planning for integrated action.\u000a\u000aThe objectives of the SESI, which was established in 1976, are to advance, promote and propagate the use of renewable energy by encouraging basic and applied research in renewable energy by collecting, compiling and disseminating information relating to renewable energy; organising seminars and conferences, by publishing books, memoirs, journals and proceedings in the field of renewable energy. They also work to establish formal education curriculum in collaboration with other institutions. Establishing renewable energy centres in collaboration with corporates, NGOs, foundations, individuals and government bodies is another area they focus on.\u000a\u000aThough Ajay Prakash Shrivastava, president, SESI, is bullish about all renewables, he says solar energy is the kind of renewable energy best suited for the Indian scenario because India gets a lot of sun. While solar energy has been getting its share of attention, Shrivastava says, the kind of boost it has got with the announcement of the National Solar Mission is something that could give the renewable sector the much-needed push. Whether we achieve the target of 20 gigawatts or not is not the point, but the fact that we have a goal to look up to is very encouraging, he says.\u000a\u000aThe congress, says Srivastava, will be a platform for ideas to come together and then be disseminated successfully. The annual conference hopes to come out with a white paper for submission to the government.\u000a\u000aThe challenge when it comes to renewables, feels the SESI president, is the lack of awareness. While events do their bit, if the government has strict policies the scenario could look very different.\u000a\u000aThe current installed power generation capacity in India is more than 1,48,000 mw. However, there is gap between demand and supply. Though 82.3% villages in India have been officially supplied electricity, about 50% of the households have yet to get electricity. Though cities have electricity, the gap between demand and supply makes the situation sticky. The answer therefore lies in effective change, which renewables only can bring in, he says.
