aVNEW DELHI: It would appear that India need not worry about being the \ufffd\ufffd\ufffddeal breaker\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd at Copenhagen summit on climate change. At the last major negotiating session prior to the December conference, which is underway in Bangkok, developed countries continue to resist demands for tougher and broader emission cuts. The effort to ensure that funding for developing countries to pursue mitigation measures has also been considerably slow. Lack of progress on these two fronts, which form the core of the demands of the developing countries, could endanger an outcome at Copenhagen.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAt the same time, the developed countries are demanding that emerging economies like India and China take on emission reduction commitments. The impasse between the developed and developing countries shows no signs of being resolved. Experts say this could mean that the December summit in Copenhagen would yield at best a \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdpolitical declaration\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAt the Bangkok meeting, which is on till October 9, negotiators from 180 countries are trying to work out ways to reduce differences and broaden and deepen efforts to combat climate change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aYvo de Boer, head of the UN Climate Change Secretariat said, \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdprogress toward high industrialised world emissions cuts remains disappointing during these talks. We're not seeing real advances there. Movement on the ways and means and institutions to raise, manage and deploy financing support for the developing world climate action also remains slow.\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe developed countries have to cut emissions by 25-40% by 2020 from the 1990 levels to avoid dangerous climate change. However, the aggregate cut pledged by these countries is well below this level. Recently, japan has pledged to cut emissions by 25% by 2020 from the 1990 levels. However, even Japan\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds commitment is contingent on pledges made by other developed countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAt Bangkok, Australia and EU have proposed that \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdeconomically more advanced developing countries\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd contribute to the global emission reduction effort. While the reference is unmistakably to India and China, no clear criteria has been set out in defining this category of countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aFor their part, the developing countries have demanded that \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdother developed countries\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd take on comparable emission reduction. The reference is to the United States, which is not a signatory to the Kyoto Protocol. Emission reduction efforts by the US, laid out in the legislation introduced by Senators John Kerry and Barbara boxer, have not met with much appreciation by the developing countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe legislation introduced in the Senate last week set out a target of 20% reduction in emissions by 2020 at 2005 levels. The minister of state for environment Jairam Ramesh, who was in Washington DC, described the efforts by the US as \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdmeasly\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd, as the reduction would work out to a mere 5% at the 1990 levels.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aExperts say a key reason why developed countries have not been able to arrive at emission targets is on account of the US. This situation is exacerbated with US President Barack Obama\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds top energy advisor Carol Browner making clear that the there was no way the US Congress would be able to pass a climate change bill in time for Copenhagen.
