aVThe \u2018shared vision\u2019, as developed in the draft text for the Copenhagen meet, seeks to impose a quantitative obligation on developing countries, such as India, which are committed to self-imposed monitoring of adaptation programmes..\u000a\u000aHit by the \u2018ecocide\u2019 perpetrated by the North, the South has to take up large-scale adaptation measures in the coming decades. While the North does accept its historic responsibility and promises to fund adaptation initiatives, several unresolved issues make any consensus at Copenhagen seem doubtful, says N.R. KRISHNAN.\u000a\u000aFailure to reach broad agreement in Copenhagen would be morally inexcusable, economically short-sighted and politically unwise.\u000a\u000aBan Ki-Moon, UN Secretary-General\u000a\u000aWith just over two months remaining for the curtains to go up on the Copenhagen climate talks, the global mood on their outcome is alternating between hope of success and fear of failure. Recent gatherings of the G-8, the MEF (Major Economies Forum), the G-20 and the United Nations had succeeded in establishing a consensus among the major players of the North and the South over the imperative need to contain global temperature rise within 2 Celsius of what it was in the pre-industrial days.\u000a\u000aIndividually, and as members of a group, the former appreciated the compelling development needs of the latter and lauded their efforts to move along a path of sustainable development. That gave rise to the hope that the North was keen to go to great lengths to make Copenhagen a success with the developing nations playing a complementary role.\u000a\u000aNorth\u2019s diktats\u000a\u000aBut hope has given way to despair, following the North\u2019s insistence that newly industrialising countries such as China and India be treated no differently from it; that is, they should accept some form of quantitative restrictions on their Greenhouse Gas (GHG) emissions from which they have remained exempted so far.\u000a\u000aFurther, issues of funding adaptation measures to be taken up by developing countries and transfer of green technologies to them are far from being resolved. Threats of trade sanctions against the supposedly errant (read China and India) have not helped matters either.\u000a\u000aCompounding the urgency for action is the prediction of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change that the limit of 2 Celsius rise associated with a GHG level of 450 parts per million by volume (ppmv) of carbon-dioxide equivalent in the atmosphere, which was considered tolerable hitherto, would now need to be scaled down to 1.5 with the GHG level to be kept below 350 ppmv to prevent the possibility of runaway climate change with all its irreversible adverse consequences.\u000a\u000aThe UK\u2019s Hadley Centre has pitched in with its own assessment that if emissions continue as usual, the average global temperature rise may reach 4 Celsius by 2050 with regions like Africa and the Mediterranean experiencing much higher increases of close to 15.\u000a\u000aDespite all the warnings, urgency does not seem to mark the actual negotiations to arrive at an agreed text for presentation at Copenhagen.\u000a\u000aReflecting the wide divergence of views on almost every issue, the 181-page draft negotiating text for consideration at the Working Group meetings in Bangkok (September 28-October 9) and Barcelona (November 2-6) released by the Climate Secretariat on September 15 bristles with a rash of alternative formulations for each paragraph, differing from each other not only in verbiage but in content too.\u000a\u000aThis bodes ill for any meaningful outcome as the differences, many of which are deep and fundamental, cannot possibly be resolved in the time available. In fairness to the Secretariat, it must be said that the text is only a collation and reordering of suggestions made by the negotiating parties at Bonn in June.\u000a\u000a\u2018Shared vision\u2019\u000a\u000aThe first item on the text is the concept of \u2018Shared Vision\u2019, with specific proposals for mitigation efforts. This concept did not figure either in the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) of 1992 or in its adjunct, the Kyoto Protocol of 1998. It was introduced in the Bali Action Plan, 2007 as \u201ca shared vision for long-term cooperative action...\u201d\u000a\u000aIn the negotiating text, the portion on \u2018Shared Vision\u2019 has 18 short preamble statements conveying the aims of long-term co-operative action with 38 paragraphs going into details of the actions called for. Each of these paragraphs has a plethora of amendments.\u000a\u000aQuantitative obligation\u000a\u000aWhile supposedly adhering to the Bali Action Plan which, recognising the needs of developing countries, conceded that their GHG mitigation actions need only be \u201cnationally appropriate\u201d without having quantified objectives, the \u2018shared vision\u2019, as it is being developed in the text, seeks to impose a quantitative obligation on them.\u000a\u000aConsider the proposition in the text which runs thus: \u201cAll parties should aim at a long-term goal of achieving at least 50 per cent reduction in global emissions of greenhouse gases from their current level by 2050\u2026 In order to achieve this goal, peaking out of the global emissions of greenhouse gases in the next 10-20 years, 2015 for developed countries and 2025 for developing countries..\u201d is considered necessary.\u000a\u000aProvisions of this nature which seek to rewrite the UNFCCC have naturally sparked the ire of the developing countries from the very beginning of the Bangkok meet.\u000a\u000aEurope versus US\u000a\u000aAmong the developed countries themselves, there are basic differences on the goal of global efforts. Whether the level of GHGs is to be stabilised at 400 ppm or 450 or 350 and whether the temperature rise has to be below 2 Celsius or 1.5 are still open to debate.\u000a\u000aAssociated with these limits is the level of ambition called for, whether emissions need to be reduced by 71-81 per cent or by more than 85 per cent from 1990 levels by 2050.\u000a\u000aMany other alternatives have been put on the negotiating table such as the mention of only a 2 rise as the long-term goal without any reference to GHG levels or bringing the average annual global per capita emissions to two tonnes or simply leave the developed countries to bring down their emissions on the basis of their historical responsibility or emissions debt or allocate global atmospheric space equitably among all the countries. The negotiating text has thus turned out to be a veritable tower of Babel.\u000a\u000aNorth-centric\u000a\u000aSuch has been the North-centricity of the text that it gives ample scope to developing countries to complain about practically everything. To cite one example, there is a curious assertion that financial and technological support would be available to them from developed countries only if they deviate from their baseline (emissions) by an order of 15-30 per cent or 25 per cent by 2050.\u000a\u000aIf mitigation is contentious, equally so is adaptation. Hit by the ecocide perpetrated by the North, the South has to take up large-scale adaptation measures in the coming decades. While the North does accept its historic responsibilities and professes to fund adaptation measures, knotty issues like the regime to govern such measures have cropped up.\u000a\u000aMonitoring\u000a\u000aDeveloped countries would like to have the adaptation programmes governed by legally binding principles and subjected to monitoring. Monitoring the progress of these programmes could be made a part of a compliance mechanism or a reporting system. The task could also be entrusted to international funding agencies.\u000a\u000aOn this issue, India has already made its views known. A statement was made recently by India that it would not subject itself to a reporting, monitoring, compliance regime in the case of programmes undertaken by it out of its own resources but may be willing to do so in the case of programmes funded by other sources. This principled concession has been pounced upon in Bangkok by India\u2019s detractors in an attempt to coerce India into accepting outside monitoring of all its mitigation efforts.\u000a\u000aWith so many unresolved issues on the table and with so little time available, how 2,500 delegates can arrive at a consensus, either in Bangkok or in Barcelona for consideration by their political masters in Copenhagen just two months hence remains a riddle. At the same time, adopting any text tilted in favour of the developed countries in Copenhagen would be \u201cmorally inexcusable\u201d.\u000a\u000a(The author is a former Secretary to the Government of India, Ministry of Environment and Forests. blfeedback@thehindu.co.in)\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated October 8, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
