aVBANGKOK: The industrialised countries may be unwilling to commit to reducing emissions under the Kyoto Protocol but they still want the `juicy bits' of it retained under a new deal.In a move that India along with other G77 countries has tried to prevent for the previous two days, the rich nations attempted to "smuggle" the provisions of Clean Development Mechanism (CDM) out of the Kyoto Protocol to discussions on the long-term deal.CDM is an offsetting tool that the signatories to Kyoto Protocol can use. It permits industrialised countries that have taken emission reduction targets under the protocol to instead claim credit for cheaper emission reduction projects in poor and developing countries.With the economies of industrialised countries at higher technological levels, it has become a lucrative option for the entities in these nations to instead buy cheap credits from projects in countries like India. Most industrialised countries allow a share of their targets to be achieved through such cheap credits.At the Bangkok talks which end on Friday, the rich countries have got together -- US, EU, Australia, Japan, Canada and several others -- to demand that Kyoto Protocol, which imposes strict penalties for failure to comply with targets, be scrapped.At the same time, they have moved to demand that the benefits of offsetting their targets against credits, just as it is at present done in CDM, be allowed into whatever new "legal instrument" they forge.India has strongly opposed the move to kill Kyoto as well as the attempt to gain cheap credits outside Kyoto.Presently, two parallel discussions are going on under the UN process. One track of negotiations is to determine what enhanced targets the annex 1 or rich nations will take under the second phase of Kyoto Protocol to which the US is not a signatory and doesn't want to be in future either. The other track is to agree to a long-term deal which decides actions and commitments for all countries running into 2050.Finding US against Kyoto Protocol, despite Barack Obama's bold proclamations earlier on climate, EU too has decided to shift its position demanding an end to Kyoto, though diplomatically it calls it moving the "good parts of Kyoto to a new instrument".
