aVBANGKOK: While the surprise news of the Nobel Peace Prize to the US President Barack Obama for his extraordinary effort spread across the world, developing countries, one after the other, stood up at the concluding session of the Bangkok climate talks to blame the US, along with other developed countries, for attempting to derail the negotiations.With the news of the Nobel prize sweeping across the corridors, the irony of the day was not lost on the delegates. Developing world representatives, indirectly but obviously, accused the US of doing little on an issue \u2014 climate change \u2014 the advocacy of which had got the previous US presidential candidate the 2008 Nobel Peace Prize.US and other developed countries, including EU, Canada, Japan and Australia, became the targets of accusations as they demanded the dissolution of the Kyoto Protocol \u2014 the only tool the world has at present to reduce its emissions and address climate change under the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change.As the final session of the Bangkok round concluded, it became obvious that the move by industrialized countries, led by the US and followed by the EU, to ask for a new `single legal instrument' under the UN convention was seen, across the board, as a ploy to renege from their commitments."The key issue here is the reluctance we perceive on part of the developed countries to come to an agreed outcome on the basis of the mandate that was decided upon by consensus. We are in the final phase of the negotiations but we are confronting the possibility of the goal posts themselves being changed. So instead of enhancing actions under the convention we are being asked to accept a new legal instrument," said Shyam Saran, Indian PM's special envoy on climate change.Saran was referring to the decision taken by all countries, including US, to follow a two-track negotiation process. The tracks are meant to one, increase the cuts that rich countries take under Kyoto Protocol and seal a deal for actions by all countries on a long term basis.But finding US, even after more than a decade and bold promises by US president Obama, not ready to join the Kyoto Protocol, the other rich nations have also found a convenient ruse to reduce their share of responsibility in coming years."The proposals (from the rich countries)...will in reality end up diluting the commitments of Annex-I countries, unilaterally imposing new commitments and burdens on developing countries, and undermine the existing Framework Convention and its Kyoto Protocol," Saran told to the gathering of 192 countries."The industrialized countries are running in a race to the bottom and are indulging in divide and rule," Sudan's representative had said earlier. Sudan holds the chair of the G77+China grouping and speaks on behalf of the more than 100 developing countries at the climate talks.The negotiations were meant to decide the targets rich countries would take in the second phase of Kyoto Protocol, starting 2012, and also build a comparable and ambitious provision for US to join in the process. But now with all the rich countries dumping Kyoto to move towards a legal regime that shifts the onus for GHG mitigation on developing countries, the Bangkok talks hit a gridlock on substantial issues."The trust between the developed and developing world on climate change actions, which has always been at a low level, has been almost completely broken," said an Indian negotiator on condition of anonymity. India and other developing countries want a deal but there are only five days of negotiations remaining before the final Copenhagen round in December. The developed world will now have to do a lot to rebuild this fragile relation or the talks are headed into failure, he added.
