aVOur Bureau\u000a\u000aNew Delhi, Oct.13 The National Council on Climate Change met here on Tuesday to deliberate on the setting up of a network of institutions for mutual exchange of knowledge on climate change.\u000a\u000aThe Prime Minister, Dr Manmohan Singh, chaired the meeting, aimed at giving shape to the National Mission on Strategic Knowledge for Climate Change (NMSKCC).\u000a\u000aDr Singh underlined the importance of developing indigenous skills, knowledge and capacities in the science of climate change, an official release said. He said in the wake of engagements with the global community on climate change, it was necessary to have the ability to prepare and read scientific data related to climate change.\u000a\u000aHe cautioned against compartmentalised thinking in various Ministries concerned and suggested an integrated approach to capacity building.\u000a\u000aAction plan\u000a\u000aStress was laid on building a dynamic knowledge system to promote ecologically sustainable development, with the NMSKCC working as a service mission of the National Action Plan on Climate Change.\u000a\u000aThe mission, serviced by the Science and Technology Ministry, will seek to build synergy with the national communication process of the Ministry of Environment and Forests.\u000a\u000aThose who attended the meeting included the Finance Minister, Mr Pranab Mukherjee, the Deputy Chairman of the Planning Commission, Mr Montek Singh Ahluwalia, and the Minister of State for Environment and Forests, Mr Jairam Ramesh.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated October 14, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
