aVNEW DELHI: Efforts are on to break the logjam ahead of the Copenhagen summit in December. With an agreement at Copenhagen in peril, the activity now has shifted to a political effort to arrive at some kind of an outcome at the December meet. The focus is on arriving at mutual agreeable understanding on issues like financing , and technology.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aClimate change experts accept that a political understanding may be the only way to get the negotiations back on track. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdAt Bangkok, there was progress in nine of the thirteen groups. However, on the four main architecture issues there was an impasse. With the developed countries now wanting to abandon the Kyoto Protocol, the possible agreement on the technical issues may have little meaning. Unless some kind of a political deal can be hammered out,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd a senior climate change expert said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe meeting of the Major Economies Forum, which began on Sunday in London and is being attended by representatives of 17 major economies, seeks to arrive at an understanding on the issue of financing and reduction of greenhouse gas emissions. The pressure is also on the United States to finalise its position.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe American envoy Todd Stern has made it clear that there was a need to bring countries like India, China, Brazil and South Africa under the umbrella of an internationally binding agreements. The demand has been consistently rejected by these developing countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aLater in the month, the EU will be meeting to find a solution to the issue of finance. But the prognosis for agreement on how to bankroll climate change action in developing countries appears to be poor.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdIndia has shown flexibility, we have taken steps that we are not bound to by agreement in response to concerns of the developed countries. We are talking of more detailed and frequent reporting, and set outcomes for mitigation efforts to be undertaken domestically.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aOther developing nations too have made similar efforts, but instead of showing flexibility, the developed world has been rigid in its position. The more flexibility we show the more they demand. Beyond a point, it becomes a case of attrition,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd a senior member of the Indian negotiating team said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn all this India doesn\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdt want to be seen as a deal breaker. As a key member of the G-77 and China, India will continue to make efforts to ensure an outcome in Copenhagen. A series of meetings in New Delhi over the week can be viewed as part of this endeavour.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aOn the technology front, India is all set to provide the stage for a political statement at the end of a high level conference on Climate Change: Technology Development and Transfer. The conference expects to come up with a Delhi Declaration on technology and climate change to be taken forward at Copenhagen. Environment ministers of most countries will be attending the conference, which will be inaugurated by Prime minister Manmohan Singh.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAnother effort to put forward the developing world perspective will be the meeting of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation Environment Ministers. This week\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds meeting is expected to end with some kind of a regional agreement. India and China are also holding a bilateral dialogue on their respective national action plan on climate change. The key sectors that will be discussed are agriculture, industry , transport, power and forestry. China will be represented by Xie Zhenhua, vice-chairman , National development and Reforms Commission.
