aVResearch initiative: The Union Minister of State for Environment and Forests, Mr Jairam Ramesh, and the ISRO Chairman, Dr G. Madhavan Nair, addressing a press conference in Bangalore on Sunday. ISRO and the Ministry are joining hands to study climate change.\u000a\u000aOur Bureau\u000a\u000aBangalore Oct. 18\u000a\u000aThe Union Ministry of Environment and Forests (MoEF) has partnered with the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) to set up a national institute of climate and environment (NICE) in Bangalore to study climate change issues.\u000a\u000aNICE, expected to get the Government approval shortly, would be set up in the current fiscal with an initial investment of Rs 40 crore and would be partially funded by the Ministry.\u000a\u000aIt would take up long-term projects to study the impact of climate change on aspects such as agriculture and water.\u000a\u000a\u201cOur aim is to build a world class institution which will be a data hub on all issue relating to climate change,\u201d Mr Jairam Ramesh, Union Minister of State for Environment and Forests, said. \u201cNICE is a huge step forward in creating the nucleus for long term research,\u201d he added.\u000a\u000aNeed to set up initiative\u000a\u000aStressing upon the need to set up India\u2019s own research initiatives to measure and monitor climate change, Mr Ramesh said \u201cmuch of the data derived from Western sources was found to be biased. There\u2019s no primary monitoring done in India\u201d. Quoting an example, Mr Ramesh said \u201cIn 1990, the US estimated that methane gas emission from paddy cultivation in India at 38 million tonnes a year.\u000a\u000aHowever, an Indian scientist later proved that emission from such cultivation varied from two to six million tonnes, with the median being four million tonnes, which is an accepted measure now\u201d.\u000a\u000aHimalayan glaciers\u000a\u000aFurther, Mr Ramesh said that MoEF would also launch a joint initiative with ISRO to monitor the health of Himalayan glaciers. \u201cWe do not have a programme of our own. The three-year programme would monitor the health of Himalayan glaciers which is of great importance to the country\u2019s water security,\u201d he added.\u000a\u000aMr Ramesh also said that the recently launched Indian Network for Climate Change Assessment (INCCA), involving 127 research bodies, would collaborate with NICE and ISRO to build the country\u2019s \u201cmonitoring, measuring and modelling\u201d capabilities and to respond innovatively and creative to climate change.\u000a\u000aINCAA is the network of scientists from the country\u2019s premier research institutes to study effects of the climate change on the economy and suggest ways to combat it. He also said that a representative of ISRO would be part of the Indian team to the climate summit in Copenhagen in December.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated October 19, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
