aVIrrespective of how the global climate change talks play out, Indian businesses should become climate friendly sooner than later. Climate change is a challenge for businesses because it influences their bottomline.\u000a\u000aBusinesses need to be prepared for a new life where energy and water cost more. We need to develop and use clean technologies to tackle the menace of global warming. Technology flow is vital for reducing CO2 emissions. Clean energy technologies are essential and should be available to developing countries. We need energy conservation in all spheres.\u000a\u000aWater could pose a larger threat than energy. Solutions lie in better management of existing water and other resources. Companies must move on to a path for sustainable development. Our policies should include efficient water usage and reduction of water wastage in transmission.\u000a\u000aSimilarly, water harvesting should be compulsory for green areas and buildings. We must promote energy efficiency using regulatory measures to reduce energy use in buildings.\u000a\u000aMake the Energy Conservation Building Code mandatory for buildings of more than 500 m2 and have all such buildings to be certified green by IGBC or TERI Griha. Outlaw conventional lamps and set up a central CFL recycling unit to extract mercury, use only 4-5 star air conditioners, refrigerators, electric motors, transformers etc. Charge a high excise duty on energy inefficient products and zero duty on energy efficient ones. Use solar heating in all the buildings as far as possible.\u000a\u000aGet labs to concentrate on solar energy research and development to improve efficiency and reduce costs.\u000a\u000aEncourage lifestyle change, keep temperature in offices between 24-25 degrees C, and do away with wearing neck-ties in offices in summer.\u000a\u000aLet the colour of green be white: Encourage the use of white colour roofs and facades and white colour vehicles, as they reflect light and heat.\u000a\u000aMore importantly, businesses also need to be in sync with the National Action Plan on Climate Change, which provides a framework for industry to shape its active response along with the creation of business opportunities.\u000a\u000aBy working with the government, the business community will not only play its role as a partner for development, but will also be able to demonstrate its own competitive edge, ultimately enabling the desired pace of economic growth.\u000a\u000aWhile countries and companies grapple with re-thinking strategies, it will be an imperative to connect loose points and understand the relation between issues, interests and institutions in order to catalyse solutions in the long term.\u000a\u000aThe need, therefore, is to give impetus to timely, measurable and verifiable business responses to risks and opportunities posed by climate change.\u000a\u000aAs responsible people we should take insurance and do what we need to do now and not any later. In a democracy, we must make people aware of our own national threats such as resulting from the Himalayan glaciers disappearing by 2035 and demand that there be policies for water and energy conservation to begin with.\u000a\u000aThe writer is CEO, Paharpur Business Centre & Software Technology Incubator Park
