aVNEW DELHI: "There should be no uncompensated commitments on greenhouse gas (GHG) mitigations by the developing countries," was the brief given to the negotiators at Bangkok, which has been contradicted by the environment minister Jairam Ramesh's new proposal to the Prime Minister.TOI accessed the brief provided by the government to the negotiators leaving for Bangkok which clearly shows the deviation the minister has now proposed, which the Prime Minister's office was quick to call "just one of the proposals"."The commitments and emission reduction targets of developed countries shall be inscribed in the Kyoto Protocol. The continuation of Kyoto Protocol and adoption of deep and ambitious cuts by Annex 1 (industrialized countries) is, therefore, of critical importance and will be non-negotiable for an agreement at Copenhagen," the government had approved.Contrary to the environment minister proposing a weakening of link between India's actions and the technology and finance it deserves as compensation for from the rich nations, the negotiators had been instructed that the voluntary actions of the country would be put on any kind of international reporting system only after the "financial mechanism under the convention enables them with the required support in terms of finance, capacity building and technology."They were also told that India shall not agree to any scrutiny of its unilateral and unsupported mitigation actions. The Australian proposal that the minister has mooted, delinks financial and technological support for developing country actions and also requires a strong review regime of their mitigation steps.The negotiators at Bangkok had in fact reaffirmed the government's position midway through the two-week meeting and were informed that there had been no shift in the period they were at their task in the Thai capital. The affirmation was required as the minister's statements to the contrary had been reported both by the media and the chief US negotiator at Bangkok."The developed countries are...committed to provide agreed fill additional costs of mitigation and adaptation, including costs of technology transfer, incurred by developing countries," it was clearly mentioned.India stood firm on the G77 plus China position that the developed world needs to pay 0.5-1% of the GDP at least to compensate for the costs developing countries would end up bearing.Reacting to the letter from the minister, that TOI had reported on Monday, a key negotiator warned that "the minister's proposal suggesting that you could have Annex 1 and non-Annex differentiation within the Australian proposal is a hoax. The fact is that the proposal regardless of how you call it, puts obligations on developing countries as well as the industrialized countries, only of varying degrees at the moment and to be scaled up in due time. At the moment the UNFCCC imposes no uncompensated obligations for India."With several negotiators upset at the sudden U-turn of the minister keeping the rest of the involved government officials and representatives in the dark, speculation was rife that a senior negotiator had expressed the desire to retire from all government positions involving climate change. By the end of the day, the clarification from the PMO, sources said, could avoid the embarrassing situation, they said.Yet another negotiator pointed out that the suggestion of the minister to legislate targets for emission reductions was explicitly aligning with the US formula for a Copenhagen deal. "India does not have the constitutional set up like US has to embed targets in a law. Targets are made part of subsidiary legal forms. What would happen if India fails to meet its targets? Who does the government wish to hold responsible if say India fails to meet its renewable energy targets or will it reduce its coal production to get to the right percentage?"Several negotiators showed, while talking to TOI, that consensus within the government had still not been built on a single domestic legislation for mitigation, as the minister has proposed.
