aVNEW DELHI: Faced with resistance from within and outside to his advocacy for a dramatic change of stand on climate change negotiations, environment minister Jairam Ramesh was in a damage control mode on Tuesday.As opponents like CPM kept up the attack on him and the country's climate negotiators expressed serious reservations about Ramesh's stand, the environment minister denied that he had strayed from the stance India had so far taken, backtracking on many of his controversial propositions.The minister retraced his steps against the backdrop of clear signs that the country's climate negotiators, including Prime Minister's special envoy Shyam Saran and C Dasgupta, were unhappy with his controversial proposition. Dasgupta, a veteran of many battles with the developed countries -- the leading polluters -- had considered quitting in protest against the attempt to shift gears. The senior negotiator was reassured only after the PMO clarified that Ramesh had, in his letter to the PM, merely reflected his personal views.Dasgupta, who is also on the PM's Council on Climate Change, told TOI he was happy with the clarification the PMO had given. He said, "In my view, the PMO has clarified the position in a timely and welcome manner. It is now clear that the document in question is only a note for discussion, not official policy. It has also been clarified that there will be no shift except on the basis of consensus and with the sanction of Parliament. This is most appropriate since our climate change policy has always been based on national consensus."As the PMO was engaged in firefighting, Ramesh came out with a detailed explanation for his controversial letter to the PM. He denied seeking to change the course, saying the country's position remained the same since 2004. While seeking to blame the row on "distortions" and "editorial interpretations", he stressed that India's position remained anchored in the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change and Bali Action Plan, and that it would not take emission reduction targets or commitments.The about-turn was striking. The minister had in his October 13 letter to the PM -- first reported by TOI -- suggested that India must not stick to G77 alone and must realise that it was now embedded in G20. He had also indirectly hit out at the negotiators, saying India should not be "argumentative and polemical". On Tuesday, he sang a different tune, stating that "India is working, and will continue to work, closely with our partners in the G77 and China... while also engaging with other countries to our benefit".Ramesh also went back on his position, taken in an earlier letter to PM, that India should allow IMF and WTO style scrutiny, review and surveillance of even those mitigation measures that were self-financed. On Tuesday, however, the minister made a somersault to assert that India would agree to "consider international measurement, reporting and verification of its mitigation actions only if such actions were enabled and supported by international finance and technology".The explanation went further than the minister's early response and pointed to the deep scepticism about his protestation that he had made no pitch for a radical change in the country's negotiating stance.His view that Kyoto Protocol could be reconciled with the Australian proposal failed to convince many in the government. Sources confirmed to TOI that Shyam Saran had already replied with a robust critique to the proposals made by the minister in his letter to the PM.Sources said while Saran, India's chief climate negotiator, had agreed with the minister's contention that India should do more to help the Small Island Developing States, he said the acceptance of the Australian Proposal would throw the `differentiation' under the Kyoto Protocol and UNFCCC between developed and developing countries for a toss. Ramesh, in his letter to the PM on October 13, had suggested that India accept the `Australian Proposal' as long as it maintained differential obligations.Several negotiators told TOI that India had no absolute obligations under the Kyoto Protocol and the UNFCCC.The Australian Proposal requires all countries, including India, to be listed on the same page with varying degrees of commitments without any reference to technological or financial support. Under the Convention, India and other non-industrialised countries are only expected to take actions they deem possible under national circumstances and then too only if these are `enabled' by finance and technology.Significantly, Ramesh on Tuesday denied that he was for dissolving the distinction between the developed and developing countries.Saran was also emphatic in his note that weakening of Kyoto would not accomplish anything favourable for India, and opposed Ramesh's views on IMF-style scrutiny of mitigation measures.Saran was only reiterating what he had, as chief negotiator, presented as India's position at the recently-concluded Bangkok talks. Sources told TOI he also argued in his note that a shift in India's position, as Ramesh suggested, would not aid India in its aspirations for a UN Security Council seat and there was merit in sticking to its stand even if it meant relative isolation.The credibility problem was far more serious outside the government. CPM remained unconvinced of the minister's version. "The minister's letter is a complete move away from country's basic positions and seems only to focus on strategically aligning India with the US on climate policy and breaking ranks with the entire bloc of developing countries", said CPM's politburo in what marked a hard-hitting rebuttal of the minister's claim that he did not pitch for a policy overhaul.In his letter to the PM, Ramesh had also recommended a more `nuanced' negotiating position when it came to linking `mitigation commitments' with finance and technology.With the Congress party having washed its hands of Ramesh's position, and the Opposition gunning for him from both left and right, the minister's volte-face has helped put up a semblance of a unified position of the government again ahead of crucial talks on Wednesday with China and a technology meet hosted by India followed up with several meetings on climate within and outside the UNFCCC.
