aVNEW DELHI: Disapproval by Congress and threat of resignation by a key negotiator on Tuesday forced environment minister Jairam Ramesh to take a U-turn on his statement suggesting radical changes in the country\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds stated position on climate change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn a written clarification, the minister reiterated India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds commitment to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change, the Kyoto Protocol and the Bali Action Plan. He stated that there is no change in India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds position on not accepting monitoring, verification and review of mitigation actions which are domestically driven and its objection to accept an internationally binding emission targets.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn essence, Mr Ramesh\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds clarification was silent on the contentious issues raised in his letter to the prime minister.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aLate on Monday evening, lead members of the negotiating team conveyed to the Prime Minister\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds Office their inability to continue to be part of India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds official team as they and the minister were not on the same page. The missive from key negotiators led to a late night clarification from the Prime Minister\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds Office, which dismissed Mr Ramesh\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds suggestions as merely a proposal.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdIn my view, the PMO has clarified the position in a more timely and welcome manner. It is now clear that the document in question is only a note for discussion, not official policy. It is also been clarified that there will be no shift except on the basis of consensus and with the sanction of Parliament. This is most appropriate since our climate change policy has always been based on a national consensus,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd Chandrasekhar Dasgupta, a key negotiator said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThough negotiators have expressed satisfaction that India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds official position hasn\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdt changed, there is a sense of distrust that appears to linger on. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdIt is anybody\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds privilege to suggest radical or fundamental change but people should avoid airing these views outside till it becomes official policy,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd a negotiator said on condition of anonymity.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aDamage appears to have been done in terms of the elbow room that negotiators will have at Barcelona and Copenhagen. The apprehension is not misplaced as at the recent Bangkok round of negotiations, Mr Ramesh\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds offer in New York of regular and detailed reports to the UNFCCC was cited by the US as an indication of India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds intent to blur the difference between developed and developing countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt is not beyond the realm of the possibility that the contents of Mr Ramesh\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds October 13 letter to the prime minister won\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdt be cited again by the developed countries to force India to accept terms that it has resisted for the last two decades.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAlready, there is the glimmer of this possibility \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd Britain\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds environment minister Ed Miliband and US envoy for Climate Change Todd Stern have commended the efforts by Mr Ramesh and Mr Shyam Saran. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdI do commend them for making, from our point of view, some forward progress,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd Mr Stern said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aMr Miliband also spoke on similar lines. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdI think what we see from India is a clear sense that a deal and an agreement on the right terms is in India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds interests and that India needs to engage in what Jairam Ramesh calls \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd per capita plus \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd so it has a per capita approach, but also needs to take domestic action,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd he said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aMr Ramesh\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds clarification on Tuesday interestingly is silent on the Australian proposal, which he had suggested that India \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdshould have no great theological objections\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd to. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdMy note suggested the possibility of some flexibility in India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds stance, keeping the above non-negotiable firmly intact and keeping India irrevocably anchored in the UNFCCC of 1992 and the Bali Action Plan of 2007.\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThere is silence on an earlier suggestion made by the minister on mitigation actions undertaken by India unilaterally. In a letter to the prime minister written following his US trip, Mr Ramesh wrote: \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdFor those mitigation actions that we undertake unilaterally and on our own, we could certainly consider a mechanism to ensure that the international community be kept fully abreast of what we are doing along the lines of the Trade Policy review of the WTO and the Article IV Consultations with the IMF.\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aHe had even in this letter reiterated India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds stand that it would submit to international monitoring, review and verification only those measures that were funded internationally. In Tuesday\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds clarification, Mr Ramesh stresses on the latter but maintains silence on WTO like proposal. It is these silences that could continue to haunt negotiators and reduce their manoeuvring space in subsequent negotiations.
