aVMr Jairam Ramesh, Minister of State for Environment and Forests, and Dr Sheel Kant Sharma, Secretary-General, SAARC, at a press conference in the Capital on Tuesday. \u2014\u000a\u000aOur Bureau\u000a\u000aNew Delhi, Oct. 20 India and other South Asian nations are of the view that the upcoming climate change negotiations in Copenhagen should adhere to the Kyoto Protocol that imposes binding emission cuts on developed countries.\u000a\u000aThe Minister of State for Environment, Mr Jairam Ramesh, told reporters after the eighth meeting of SAARC Environment Ministers that all the members of the regional grouping would also adhere to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) and the Bali Action Plan.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe SAARC speaks in one voice that we should not move away from UNFCCC, Kyoto Protocol and the Bali Action Plan on climate change,\u201d Mr Ramesh said in his briefing to the press after the meeting.\u000a\u000aMr Ramesh, however, declined to take any questions at the event on the controversy surrounding his letter to the Prime Minister, Dr Manmohan Singh, earlier this month, in which he had reportedly suggested a dilution on India\u2019s negotiating stance and accept emission cuts at the upcoming Copenhagen summit.\u000a\u000aUnder fire on the issue from all quarters, Mr Ramesh issued a statement later in the day to clear the air on the contents of his letter. In the statement, Mr Ramesh said he had suggested \u201csome flexibility\u201d in India\u2019s stand on climate change issues but ruled out any dilution the stance on Kyoto Protocol that imposes emission cuts on developed countries.\u000a\u000aFlexibility suggested\u000a\u000a\u201cMy note suggested the possibility of some flexibility in India\u2019s stance... I have never at any stage considered or advocated abandoning the fundamental tenets of the Kyoto Protocol,\u201d he said in the statement.\u000a\u000aMaintaining that India\u2019s stand was \u201cirrevocably anchored\u201d in the UNFCCC and the Bali Action Plan and it was non-negotiable, Mr Ramesh said the basic point was that \u201cIndia\u2019s interests and India\u2019s interests alone shall dictate at our negotiating stance.\u201d\u000a\u000aClarification\u000a\u000aMr Ramesh\u2019s written clarification comes amid strong disapproval voiced by the Congress Party to the contents of the letter written by him and the threat of resignation by key negotiators. Late Monday evening, members of the Indian negotiating team conveyed to Dr Manmohan Singh, their inability to continue to be part of India\u2019s official team following reports of the contents of the letter written by the Minister.\u000a\u000aThe missive from key negotiators led to a late night clarification from the Prime Minister\u2019s Office, which dismissed Mr Ramesh\u2019s suggestions as merely a proposal.\u000a\u000aMr Ramesh\u2019s clarification on Tuesday is, however, silent on the controversial Australian Proposal, which he had suggested that India \u201cshould have no great theological objections\u201d to.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated October 21, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
