aVNEW DELHI: Diplomatic skirmishes between Beijing and New Delhi notwithstanding, India and China on Wednesday signed an agreement to co-operate on ways to fight climate change. They will also continue to work together in international climate deal negotiations.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe agreement emphasised that the \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdUnited Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change and its Kyoto Protocol are the most appropriate framework for addressing climate change\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aConcerns have been expressed in some quarters about the recent moves made by China on the issue of climate change. Some of this concern also found reflection in Mr Ramesh\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds letter to the prime minister. However, on Wednesday, Mr Ramesh stressed that even though China\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds emission rate is five times that of India and even in terms of development China is ahead, the two countries are on the same page when it comes to climate change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdThe differences are not important for China and India when it comes to climate change. Both are collaborating for a fair and equitable outcome at Copenhagen. An outcome in keeping with Rio Declaration of 1992, Kyoto Protocol of 1997 and the Bali Action Plan. An outcome that fully protects and promotes interests of developing countries,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd Mr Ramesh said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aXie Zhenhua, vice-chairman and minister for national development and reform commission of China, reiterated environment minister\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds statement, which served to put at rest speculation that India was considering moving out of the G-77 and China group. India and China have been negotiating on climate change as part of the bloc of 131 developing countries, commonly known as the G-77.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBoth Mr Ramesh and Mr Xie said that there would be more discussion to see \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdwhat India and China should do to ensure a successful outcome at Copenhagen\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd. Describing the road to Copenhagen as \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdnot easy\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd, Mr Xie said at the negotiations the two countries would stick to the Kyoto Protocol and Bali Action Plan, and that they would co-ordinate negotiations.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a
