aVIndia and China on Tuesday signed a key agreement to cooperate on measures to arrest climate change and develop a common position on the global dialogue on these issues.\u000a\u000aThe common position comes just few weeks ahead of the global climate meet in Copenhagen. The common position reiterates that developed countries should take the lead to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and provide financial resources, technology transfer and capacity building support to developing countries including India and China.\u000a\u000aThe position was made clear in the Memorandum of Agreement (MoA) signed by the two countries for cooperation on climate change issues. It was signed by Indian environment minister Jairam Ramesh and visiting China's vice-chairman of National Development and Reform Commission Xie Zhenhua. To develop its global negotiation position, India has now signed climate related agreement with Japan and plans to sign such deals with USA and Brazil. Finance minister Pranab Mukherjee called for a fair and equitable outcome during the Copenhagen negotiations. He said the costs for climate mitigation costs are in the range of $160-200 billion and adaptation costs another $60 billion annually. The funds for that should come from reliable, predictable and sustainable sources basically the developed world.
