aVNEW DELHI: Is no price too high to pay for a deal at Copenhagen? This is a question that the government has jostled with at various levels and the dramatic proposals of environment minister Jairam Ramesh this week have been a symptom of such ruminations. The shuffle of opinions within the government has raised the question: Is the government clear on what will remain non-negotiable till the last night of the Copenhagen Climate Change talks?The clarity must come early, as even before Copenhagen, there are several important meetings like the one of PM Manmohan Singh with US President Barack Obama where the opposition is surely going to use a political disconnect in India on the policy to its advantage."Of course the government cannot disclose its negotiating stance or `tradables' ahead of the talks. Timing is of essence in trade-offs, but we must know who are the people making this policy, which requires the government to know so to begin with," says an observer outside the government who has been tracking Indian climate negotiations for long.The climate negotiations are complicated as they impact global economy like few other multilateral agreements so far. They are built on four basic and parallel channels. Who should mitigate and how much? How climate-friendly technologies should be diffused to the parts of the world that need it and need it quick? How the burden of adapting to inevitable climate change should be shared? And finally, how should the finances needed to do all that it takes to adapt and prevent catastrophic climate change be generated and shared?India and other emerging countries have so far tried to ensure that the talks on all four fronts are carried out simultaneously. The rich countries prefer to first bind emerging economies on to a road that leads to emission reduction targets in coming years and then talk of transferring technology and funds. It's been in the developing world's advantage to let the industrialized countries, which are primarily to blame for driving the planet to the tipping point, first disclose how much reductions they are willing to undertake in the next decade and put figures of funds and technologies they want to share. As per the Bali Action Plan that all countries signed on to in December 2007, the developing countries are expected to reduce emissions, if they are paid the full costs of their actions. They want to know how much funds are on the table before they decide what they can do with it.Right now there is pretty much nothing on the table. The US has blocked talks of fund transfers and sharing of existing technology and the EU is still fighting within on whether it can at all provide any funds. To divert attention from the meat of the issues, at the Bangkok negotiations recently, the industrialized countries instead spent time building a skeletal architecture for delivering the funds, technologies and emission reductions. As one G77 delegate said, rather tongue in cheek, "They now want to lay down the pipelines but they don't yet know where they are to get the oil from. You know what happens to unused pipes. They rust."At the same time, India among other emerging economies has been painted by the lobbyists in the West of being obstructionist. Recent pronouncements from Ramesh seem to indicate that the highest echelons of the government have taken it to heart and wants to now gain the tag of a `deal-maker' and act `flexibly'.But as one Indian negotiator points out, "The negotiations exist because all countries are flexible. It is a process of give and take. Nobody wins all. We cooperate to do what's best and to which all shall agree. But why should India, which has taken several bold and concrete steps since the PM took charge of climate change with his council, be called `obstructionist'."In the next two rounds, the negotiators will require a clear brief from the political masters. As much as the government will need to repose its faith in their skills, they would want the political leadership to be sure that when the minister enters the green rooms of negotiations (where only the ministers are allowed in with their `sherpas' for thrashing out a deal), he has in hand an unambiguous picture of what is non-negotiable. It would not work then if the minister's personal views are at cross purposes with the government policy.
