aVClean technologies\u000a\u000aFinancing for climate change must not be seen as another form of overseas development assistance\u000a\u000aThe cost of intellectual property rights cannot be recovered from the developing countries\u000a\u000aOur Bureau\u000a\u000aNew Delhi, Oct. 21 The Finance Minister, Mr Pranab Mukherjee, reiterated the country\u2019s commitment to multilateral negotiations under the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC).\u000a\u000aIn a clear message that India had not shifted its negotiating position on the issue, Mr Mukherjee said that the financing estimates for countering climate change meant \u201cinvestments of an unprecedented scale far beyond the means of developing countries.\u201d\u000a\u000aStressing the importance of recognising the principle of \u201ccommon but differentiated responsibility\u201d, Mr Mukherjee said the developing nations desperately needed funds to shift to cleaner technologies and cut emissions.\u000a\u000aPayments for entitlements\u000a\u000aThe Finance Minister, who was speaking at the inauguration of an exhibition on climate change and technology here on Wednesday, stressed the need for the developed world to ensure funding on a \u201cpredictable and sustainable basis\u201d to the developing countries to undertake adaptation and mitigation action. He also said the funding should not be seen as assistance but as \u201cpayments for entitlements. Financing for climate change must also not be seen as another form of overseas development assistance (ODA) but rather payments for entitlements of developing countries under an equitable regime,\u201d he added.\u000a\u000aMr Mukherjee said the G-20 meeting in Scotland next month is likely to discuss such financing. He also spoke of the responsibility and obligation of the developed nations to ensure the disbursement and proliferation of clean technology to the developing world.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe cost of intellectual property rights cannot be recovered from the developing countries. The developed countries should make available technology in the public domain.\u201d\u000a\u000aGlobal emissions\u000a\u000aAsserting that India will ensure its per capita emission is lower than advanced economies, Mr Mukherjee said: \u201cThe US and China account for over 16 per cent each of the total global emissions, while India trails with just four per cent of the emissions\u2026 We are a distant third in terms of total volume of emissions, and the gap is very large.\u201d\u000a\u000aEarlier in the day, India and China signed a broad agreement to cooperate in the fight against climate change and working out a common position on the multilateral talks for a tougher global climate deal. The sweeping agreement covers cooperation for action to reduce greenhouse gases, transfer of technology and in areas of energy efficiency and renewables, among others.\u000a\u000aRelated Stories:\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated October 22, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
