aVPrime Minister Manmohan Singh on Thursday said climate-friendly and environmentally sound technologies should be viewed as global public goods. Suitable mechanisms need to be formulated to develop and deploy new technologies in developing countries at affordable costs, he said.\u000a\u000aPointing out that such an approach has been adopted successfully in the case of HIV/AIDS medicines, the PM said the moral case of a similar approach for fighting the climate change is equally compelling. He was speaking at the inauguration of a seminar, High-Level Conference on Climate Change: Technology Development & Transfer, here.\u000a\u000aHe underlined that the key issue is to develop appropriate technologies and leapfrog their commercialisation on a large scale for adoption in developing countries. We need technology solutions that are appropriate, affordable and truly effective.\u000a\u000aSince technology and financing go together, Singh called for the establishment of appropriate financial arrangements to transfer technology. While industrialised countries can afford to shift to energy efficient processes even at additional costs, developing countries need adequate financial support, he said.\u000a\u000aSingh said that providing incentives for adoption of climate friendly technologies in developing countries in the second commitment period of the Kyoto Protocol should be a global concern. Quoting the example of the Clean Development Mechanism under the Kyoto Protocol, he said that it has become an effective vehicle for clean technology deployment in developing countries and is reducing greenhouse gas emissions at lower costs.\u000a\u000aTransfer and deployment of clean technology need to be accompanied by strengthening the limited innovation capabilities in developing countries to increase their capacity of absorption, he said. In fact, India has already proposed setting up of regional climate innovation centres to enhance technology innovation and capacity building in developing countries.\u000a\u000aSingh reiterated that India is committed to keeping per capita carbon emissions below the level recorded in developed countries. While Indias per capita consumption of primary energy is less than one-fourth of the world average, its per capita emission of CO2 is among the lowest.
