aVAt the Copenhagen meet developing countries should take the lead in implementing energy efficiency and south-south technology transfer mechanisms.\u000a\u000aSuparna Karmakar\u000a\u000aThe significance of the upheaval in India in the past week over the proposed change in India\u2019s stance in the climate change negotiations goes far beyond the huge uproar and political opportunism it has spawned.\u000a\u000aThe letter written to the Prime Minister by the Environment Minister, Mr Jairam Ramesh, as reported by leading newspapers, apparently suggests that India delink finance and technology negotiations under the Kyoto Protocol from taking on national mitigation (greenhouse gas emission reduction) commitments under the new deal, which will distance it from G77 \u2014 the 131-member bloc of developing nations \u2014 and bring it closer to the G20.\u000a\u000aThe upheaval generated, however, has the potential to create an epochal change in industrial production systems worldwide.\u000a\u000aThis article tries to outline the challenges and opportunities for India and the developing world, especially in view of the recent Sino-Indian cooperation agreement to fight climate change which includes action to reduce planet-warming greenhouse gases, transfer of technology, and areas of energy efficiency and renewables, among others.\u000a\u000aThe Kyoto Protocol is connected to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) and aimed at combating global warming. It was first adopted in December 1997, came into force in February 2005, and 184 States have signed and ratified it so far.\u000a\u000aThere are several controversies vis--vis the Kyoto Protocol.\u000a\u000aFirst, its most notable non-member is the US, which is a signatory to the UNFCCC and responsible for 36.1 per cent of the 1990 emission levels. Furthermore, there are controversies surrounding the use of 1990 as a base year, as well as not using per capita emissions as a basis; countries had different achievements in energy efficiency in 1990.\u000a\u000aLastly, neither the UNFCCC nor the Kyoto Protocol (which includes most of the binding commitments to reduce greenhouse gases) specifies a binding compliance mechanism. The Kyoto Protocol defines a mechanism of \u201ccompliance\u201d as a \u201cmonitoring compliance with the commitments and penalties for non-compliance\u201d.\u000a\u000aHowever, under Article 18 of the protocol, the need for legal amendments of the procedures and mechanisms for enforcing compliance adds to the confusion vis--vis the binding nature of the compliance mechanism.\u000a\u000aOver to Copenhagen\u000a\u000aIn the non-binding \u201cWashington Declaration\u201d of February 2007, an outline of a successor to the Kyoto Protocol was agreed in principle. It was hoped that the new agreement will be in place by 2009; hence the significance of the Copenhagen meeting of the UNFCCC, scheduled for December. According to the Bali roadmap, a framework for climate change mitigation beyond 2012 is to be agreed on there.\u000a\u000aWhat needs to be remembered is that the Kyoto Protocol is an indefinite agreement; it doesn\u2019t expire after 2012. However, without an agreement in Copenhagen on the status of emissions reduction commitments in the post-2012 scenario (as the protocol doesn\u2019t even contain a standstill provision), there is a fear that the erstwhile signatories may also slide back from commitments.\u000a\u000aTaking the lead\u000a\u000aWith less than six weeks to go, it appears that the Copenhagen meet is unlikely to bridge the longstanding disconnect between the developed and developing country expectations.\u000a\u000aThe talks in Bangkok revealed the considerable progress already made in some key areas of a global agreement, such as adaptation, technology and capacity-building in developing countries.\u000a\u000aHowever, there is no clarity on two issues that are key to success in Copenhagen: rich nation emission reduction targets; and financial support for climate change action in developing countries.\u000a\u000aCan developing countries break the deadlock? It is true that while developing countries can do little to garner the much-needed emission reduction and financing commitments, they can and should take the lead in unilaterally implementing energy efficiency and south-south technology transfer mechanisms which could yield significant cuts in emissions at low cost.\u000a\u000aPerhaps Mr Ramesh\u2019s comments should be interpreted in that light, rather than as an indication of India\u2019s future climate change negotiation strategy.\u000a\u000aDomestic mitigation policy should be based on national imperatives and need not wait for commitments from the rest of the world. But more significantly, India should be at the forefront of the low-carbon industrial revolution.\u000a\u000a(The author is a Visiting Research Fellow with the Institute of South Asian Studies, National University of Singapore. The views are personal. blfeedback@thehindu.co.in)\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated October 23, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated
