aVNEW DELHI: A camera strung on a kite a few hundred metres above the ground clicked pictures of about 600 students and volunteers from across the world as they formed the digit `5' in front of the historic Red Fort on Saturday afternoon October 24 was the global day for climate action.The `5' was the second of the three-part initiative to display the number 350 symbolic of the 350 parts per million of carbon dioxide which is the maximum that can be permitted in the atmosphere. A similar human chain had formed the `3' in Sydney while the `0' will be formed at Copenhagen in December.This was the second day of a joint initiative by Universal Peace Federation, Indian Youth Climate Network and the Archaeological Survey of India during which the Adopt a Heritage campaign was also launched. Volunteers swept the Qutub Minar complex on Friday and the Red Fort complex on Saturday.Roselin Dey, South Asia campaign co-ordinator for 350.org said several such actions had been planned across the world on Saturday to raise awareness on climate change and compel world leaders to take positive steps at the upcoming Copenhagen meet. "In Delhi, too, several cleaning campaigns, walks, etc, were planned over the two days. We were joined by several DU students and volunteers from other countries,'' she said.In fact, several onlookers also joined in the human chain to express solidarity. "Our monuments are in a terrible mess. It is an embarrassment. Whether or not the countries come to any conclusion, we need to cut down on carbon emissions,'' said R Luthra, who stood with the volunteers.
