aVNEW DELHI: Should rich countries pay only vulnerable countries the cost of adapting to inevitable climate change or should they compensate vulnerable people of all countries which would not be able to cope with the unforeseen disasters? This question has got international diplomacy working overtime with key countries being lobbied assiduously. This is going to be one of the key issues countries will battle in the upcoming Barcelona talks in November.While much attention has been spent on targets, or the lack of them, by industrialised countries to reduce their greenhouse gases, the vexed issue of who should be compensated for adapting to climate change that would happen regardless of how ambitious a set of targets the rich countries can come up with has gone unnoticed.But the debates about adaptation have got as heated with the Copenhagen round of talks 30 days away.The UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, the international pact between more than 190 countries, demands that rich nations assist countries that are vulnerable to calamities that climate change will trigger.But in a move that has been opposed strongly by the G77 plus China bloc, the industrialised countries have begun putting offers to only help the `most vulnerable countries'. The carving out of a new bloc, which does not exist in the UNFCCC, has riled the G77 as an attempt to divide the 131 country-strong G77 block which holds the defence up for the developing world.The convention says, "The developed country parties and other developed parties included in Annex II shall also assist the developing country parties that are particularly vulnerable to the adverse effects of climate change in meeting costs of adaptation to those adverse effects."But with rich countries wanting to merely fund the extremely vulnerable countries, the poor and vulnerable of other larger developing countries could get left out, G77 leaders fear."While we must prioritise the requirements of small island states and other vulnerable small countries, one cannot let the industrialised countries use them to renege on their obligations to help the poor of other larger nations," a senior negotiator from the G77 bloc visiting Delhi told TOI. "That is a simple divide and rule game," he added.India too has pointed out that it has a vast coastline with millions of people who would stand exposed to increased vagaries of nature. While India spends a lot on its own to adapt to natural calamities and build resilience in communities, developed countries are obliged to pay the costs for wreaking greater damage on such communities.In the diplomatic battles on adaptation, countries like Maldives and Bangladesh are being increasingly feted by the industrialised nations though for now, the G77 group has held on strong presenting a unified voice on key issues at the negotiations.
