aVThe government has approved the National Mission for Sustaining the Himalayan Ecosystem in principle. One of the eight missions under the National Action Plan on Climate Change, the mission was approved by the Prime Ministers Council on Climate Change, in New Delhi on Monday.\u000a\u000aDelivering his introductory remarks, Prime Minister Manmohan Singh said there is a need to prepare the country and people to anticipate and respond to the consequences of climate change, which is one of the most serious ecological challenges faced not only India, but the entire subcontinent.\u000a\u000aSingh called it one of the most critical of the various missions because it impacts directly water and food security, affecting livelihood of hundreds of millions of people.\u000a\u000aThe National Mission for Sustaining the Himalayan Ecosystem is the fourth mission to be discussed in detail by the council.\u000a\u000aSaying that the entire Himalayan area, which constitutes an extremely fragile ecological zone, is getting degraded as a result of deforestation, demographic pressures, uncontrolled urbanisation and construction, he added that environmental stresses are getting accentuated by adverse consequences of climate change.\u000a\u000aExpressing satisfaction that the mission document has come out with both short-term and a long-term plans to monitor key indicators of climate change in the Himalayan zone, he added that there is need for reliable data through satellite imaging and ground surveys to validate anecdotal evidence that glaciers are receding.\u000a\u000aHe said he was pleased to see the mission document address socio-economic challenges and offer concrete measures because the involvement of local communities and drawing upon their traditional knowledge is indispensable to ensure successful implementation of the mission.\u000a\u000aSaying that the state governments have been sensitised to the need for such measures, he called upon the chief ministers of the Himalayan states to join in a national effort to safeguard the Himalayan ecosystem.\u000a\u000aTaking note of the fact that Nepal, Bhutan, China and Pakistan share the Himalayan ranges with India, he added that any comprehensive climate change action plan will require coordinated action among all stakeholder countries. Though some bilateral initiatives are already being taken, yet there is need to recognise the need for much greater engagement with all the neighbours, he said.
