aVBEIJING: Mahatma Gandhi was a great visionary who taught the world many lessons. But his thoughts provide no answer to certain issues like international trade and global environment problems, Nobel laureate Amartya Sen told a conference here on Wednesday."Mahatma raised a different set of issues," he said while replying to a question asked at a conference on environment in Beijing about whether Gandhian thoughts hold the key to solving problems concerning environment degradation and climate change."Gandhi was even against railways," he said while pointing out that the transportation industry was a crucial aspect of the development and progress the world has seen.Sen said he had high respect for the Mahatma and Gautam Buddha. But it is not possible to find answers to all problems from any one of the great people one admired.He was a great admirer of Buddha but did not accept some of his views on the status of man and woman. Buddha's views on women were brought to light by his disciple, Ananda, he said.The real issue concerning climate change and environment related negotiations are one of justice and fairness. Developing countries have a case when they seek justice from the western world in the process of designing global environmental standards, Nobel laureate Amartya Sen said on Wednesday, but countries like India and China should now make sure that non-polluting countries in Africa are dealt with the same standards of fairness and justice that they seek from the western world in any environment related settlement, he told a conference on "Trade, Urbanization and the Environment" organized by the Peking University and the Veolia Environment Institute.It would be a mistake to divide the world into old polluters and new polluters. If that was so, non-polluting in Africa will blame India and China one day for not doing enough to protect the environment when they could do so. He said Africa must be taken into account and allowed more room in any future arrangement on environment.Sen said developed nations must bear a larger share of the burden for cleaning up the world because they have the means to do so. He was also opposed to placing mechanical limits on different countries on the extent of emissions without taking into consideration their economic conditions and need for development.But he rejected the argument of some developing countries that western countries should contribute more because they have committed historical injustice. There was no need to create new hostility on this count, he said.The western world caused much of the pollution for industrial development at a time when there was no much awareness on environment. Besides, the present generation of people in the West should not be penalized for what has been done in the past.His views were somewhat at odds with those of Peng Sen, vice minister of China's National Reforms and Development Commission, who said the western world should bear a higher burden because they generated 80% of the global pollution.But China was seriously engaged in reducing emission and use of energy at home instead of merely blaming other countries. Peng said China has already achieved its 11th five-year plan on reducing emissions and enlarging the use of renewal energy one and half years ahead of schedule despite the pressures caused by the financial crisis.The 1998 Nobel prize winner said it is possible to tackle the challenge of environment by formulating a series of contracts that would be both equitable and fair to countries in different stages of development, he said.
