aVNEW DELHI: As officials from 192 countries converge in Barcelona for the last round of negotiations ahead of the December summit, expectations that the Copenhagen meet will result in an agreement appear to be reduced.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aGiven the increased call for some kind of agreement at Copenhagen, it could mean a greater pressure on countries like India to make concessions during the Barcelona meet. Some of the pressure could be on account of the much-publicised difference of opinion within the government over India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds position.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aDespite two years of negotiations following the Bali Action Plan, the differences between the developed and developing countries are yet to be bridged.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe developed or Annexe I countries have failed to commit to deep emission cuts, which they are required to undertake under the United nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC). The Kyoto Protocol requires industrialised countries to reduce greenhouse gas emissions that cause global warming to 5% below 1990 levels by 2012.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe developed countries have also failed to commit finances for the developing countries to undertake necessary action to mitigate and adapt to climate change. There is also no agreement on ensuring technology transfer to the developing world.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aDeveloped countries are demanding that advanced developing countries like India and China take on binding emission cuts, in view of the projections suggesting an increase in greenhouse gas emissions by these countries. Developing countries are not required by the convention framework, which is based on the principle of common but differentiated responsibilities arising from the historical emissions of the developed countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIndia and China have made some concessions in a bid to bridge the divide. However, none of the offers have been reciprocated by commitments by the developed countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aTwo other areas of impasse include technology and finance. Last month\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds UN conference on technology cooperation and climate technology in Delhi only served to highlight the difference between the developed and developing countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe Delhi declaration, that was agreed upon at the conference, was silent on a sharing regime of intellectual property rights. The absence of consensus on sharing of intellectual property rights is viewed as a threat to the success of the crucial Copenhagen meet in December. India has argued that climate change technology should be viewed as \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdpublic common goods\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aFinance is another area where differences could cripple an outcome at Copenhagen. However there has been no headway on finance. On Friday, EU leaders failed to arrive at an agreement over how much money they would set aside. The issue of finance will figure at the meeting of G-20 finance ministers in St Andrews, Scotland, on November 6 and 7.
