aVNEW DELHI: NDPL's ambitious rooftop solar power project has hit a hurdle with the Delhi government expressing its inability to meet the immediate demand of Rs 700 crore required as subsidy. Chief secretary Rakesh Mehta said that while the project is highly important in view of the city's climate change plan, lack of funds has seen its progress slow down considerably.Under the project, NDPL is looking to generate 100MW solar power on roofs of the houses of its consumers. While the consumers will use the power generated, the extra will be sold back to NDPL. Officials said power would be generated through photovoltaic panels. These would be fed into the main grid for personal use or if desired, be sold back to the discom. One meter would monitor the energy fed into the grid while another will assess the amount consumed by the user so that bills could be generated on actual consumption.Officials explained that to generate 10kW power suitable for homes with a built up area of 200 sq yards the cost for installation would be roughly Rs 14-15 lakh. "With this expenditure, the tariff would fall to about Rs 15-16/unit with a 20-25 year cost recovery period. However, we requested the government to bear up to 40-50% of the cost so that the tariff would be halved. The project aims at generating 100MW and if the government bears 50% of the cost, it would need to shell out Rs 700 crore that would go directly to the consumer,'' said an official.And while the government is unable to shell out the amount immediately, NDPL officials said there was no need for the same since they did not have the requisite number of interested consumers at present. "Even with those who have come forward till now, it will take us at least a year before the infrastructure can be put in place. We are sure the government would be able to assist us in this scenario,'' said an official.NDPL has already set up two solar plants a 4kW plant in its office premises in Hudson Lines and a 15kW plant at a training centre in Rohini. It is also proposing to set up a 25MkW solar plant at the DERC office.
