aVMUMBAI: As the world takes cautious steps towards the Copenhagen climate summit, a debate on what the post-2012 scenario could possibly look like for the Indian carbon industry has started to rage.What would be the prospective market and pricing of carbon credits post-2012 if India and China were to put caps on industrial emissions? Some industry experts believe that this would open up a new domestic market for carbon credits or certified emission reductions (CERs) currently exported, leading to better price realisation as demand would outstrip supply.The demand for carbon offsets is directly proportional to increase in expansion of a compliance market and their adoption of a cap-and-trade mechanism to achieve emission reduction targets. Providing a perspective on the likely scenario that could unfold, Avneesh Singh, senior consultant (carbon advisory business), Emergent Ventures, said: "International carbon prices should go up as any emission reduction in these countries would then be used to count towards the national cap, thereby severely limiting supply.""Internal offset measures centred around reduction in carbon emissions through abatement measures such as energy efficiency certificate trading and renewable energy certificate trading could give rise to alternative commodities, effecting supply to carbon credits," Singh said.However, there is a possibility that the current offset mechanism would come to an end with the development of regional and national trading schemes if developing nations were to commit to emission reduction. Pointing towards another scenario that the Indian industry could count on, an official from a leading corporate said, "clean development mechanism (CDM) projects could be allowed to be developed alongside a national trading scheme. This would enable CERs to be traded in the international markets as is the case today.""This way, there will be a healthy market for CERs in the domestic as well as international markets. Here, the impact on prices would depend on the quantum of CERs allowed to be generated," the official added.This may also give rise to fungibility of carbon offsets from participating countries. Although acceptance of carbon credits generated from countries could see a differentiation. For instance, emission reductions generated from least developed countries like Cambodia may get a new terminology and could command a different price.The third scenario would be that developing countries take emission reduction commitments without any financial penalty and try and contain emissions. In this case, the supply of CERs would not change much.The fourth, of course, is voluntary mitigations by developing countries and continuation of the existing protocol post-2012.If this be the case, the objective would be to channelise availability of carbon finance to fund mitigation efforts and invest in renewable energy to take care of the energy security of developing nations like India.Many agree that the more likely scenario would be that developing countries would stick to their stand of no commitments for emission reductions but at the same time go in for some non-committal voluntary steps to curb emissions. India could continue to invest in renewable energy and CDM would continue in some form of post-Kyoto protocol as a means to adopt clean technologies.Singh, who expects global negotiations to throw up a new system to improve the supply of international offsets from countries in Africa and SE Asia post-2012, said: "In all likelihood, any targets taken by India would be semiconditional. These countries would not risk losing out on forex inflows through CERs. They would rather negotiate to have a system where they can still sell CERs outside, and not have them swallowed up by the local caps. This would be in the form of technology transfers to developing countries."India has some 461 projects registered so far with the CDM executive board at the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change with total issued CERs at about 72 million units.
