aVNEW DELHI: After a 24-hour boycott by African delegates, talks resumed in Barcelona on Wednesday. And developing countries kept up the pressure, demanding that the developed countries should cut greenhouse gas emissions by at least 40% below 1990 levels by 2020. This is far more than what is on offer. UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds hopes of rescuing the Copenhagen summit continued to be dashed.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aFollowing his meeting with US president Barack Obama, Swedish prime minister Fredrik Reinfeldt said \ufffd\ufffd\ufffda legally binding agreement, like we have advocated in Europe, is simply not possible to deliver\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd. He laid the blame for this at Washington\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds doorstep, saying that it was due to the US\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd current inability to commit to a specific reduction in greenhouse gas emissions. Sweden holds the EU presidency.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aOn Tuesday, giving voice to the demands of the developing countries, the group of African nations said they would return to talks only if the industrialised developed countries were willing to discuss far deeper cuts in emissions of greenhouse gases as the core of a successor to the Kyoto Protocol, which is to be agreed upon in Copenhagen\u000a\u000a\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdPeople in Africa are suffering now, people are dying now, when the developed countries are not willing to express...ambitious reductions,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd Kemal Djemouai, chair of the African group, said of the protest in Barcelona.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aMeanwhile in London, the UN secretary-general played down hopes for the key Copenhagen summit on climate change, suggesting that detail on an agreement may be lacking. Keeping hopes alive, the UN chief said that a binding agreement could be concluded if there was political will.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe EU appears to have given up on the idea of a positive outcome at Copenhagen. In Washington, European Commission president Jose Manuel Barroso said, \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdof course, we are not going to have a full-fledged binding treaty \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd Kyoto type \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd at Copenhagen. There is no time for that\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aFollowing the boycott by the African nations on Tuesday, informal meetings were held on commitments by all nations, including the US and developing states, to fight global warming. There has been a push by developed countries to replace the Kyoto Protocol with a new treaty. Taking up from where they left off in Bangkok, the US has made it clear that it will not accept a treaty that doesn\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdt have any GHG emission limitation measures for countries like China and India.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWhile developed countries would be asked to undertake binding reduction targets to limit GHG emissions, developing countries would be urged to adopt measures to limit emission. At the heart of the effort is an attempt to push developing nations such as China and India to restrict emissions. The US, EU and Australia have been pushing the idea of an \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdinternational registry\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd.
