aVWriting a few words on a complex subject is a challenge. I prefer a common sense review of the issues as Bhola, a plain Joe, might see thingsbecause climate change threatens communities everywhere and it requires Bholas to adjust and adapt.\u000a\u000aThe subject of climate change attracts three kinds of players: the evangelist who makes dire predictions about a catastrophic future; second, the rationalist for whom the facts are too unclear to get worked up. He prefers a considered and rational approach to the evangelistic approach. The third is Bhola, who relies on his instinct.\u000a\u000aAnyway, the experts are divided and they confuse him.\u000a\u000aBhola has five questions.\u000a\u000aFirst, is warming occurring Second, if it is, why Third, what are its consequences Fourth, what should be done about it Fifth, what is the cost\u000a\u000aOn whether warming is occurring, more and more scientists are emphatic that global warming is real and increasing. However, their increasing dogma bothers Bhola. There are seemingly equally distinguished scientists, who are circumspect and are less rigid. For example, some quote Britains Hadley Centre for Climate Prediction to aver that there has been no warming for the last 11 years! Some others quote the same institution to say that there has definitely been warming during the last ten years! Both may be right, but then it does produce uncertainty in Bholas mind.\u000a\u000aTo Bhola, it is not clear whether the problem is rapidly escalating. Still, using his common sense, Bhola feels that there must be a problem. After all, the planet supports 6 billion people today compared to 1 billion just 200 years ago; this must have consequences!\u000a\u000aOn the second question of why there is warming, the evangelists argue that carbon dioxide is the principal enemy; they advocate a frontal attack on emissions of carbon dioxide. But the rationalists point out that there are other gases involvedthe biggest warmer being water vapour, according to them! Bhola understands that climate science is uncertain, but he is perplexed for sure! As a responsible community member and out of abundant caution, Bhola feels that everyone should implement reasonable measures.\u000a\u000aOn the question of the consequences, evangelists are shrill. The snow on Mount Kilimanjaro has declined 26% since 2000. The Himalayas are melting rapidly and mosquitoes are expected at those heights. Greenland is warming up. The Arctic Circle is melting, and sea levels will rise and submerge whole nations. Unfortunately, rationalists do not connect as cause and effect the factual observations and carbon dioxide!\u000a\u000aBy now Bhola is wondering about the fourth question about the remedies. So far as he is concerned, the diagnosis is inconclusive, and so it seems inappropriate to panic and implement drastic measures. Some action is needed, so he chooses measures that do not bring too much angst and make common sense to himbut provided others in the world community also do their bit.\u000a\u000aThe West wants countries like India and China to accept an absolute reduction in emission targets. This will mean that each Indian will be permitted less emission than each American. Bhola wonders why he should be allowed fewer emissions than each of the 800 million Americans and Europeans. It is like suggesting that rich people will have 5 votes per person compared to poor peoplethat is no democracy! He heard that some people blame India for having too many people and Bhola feels angry about such a view. He farms, and agriculture emits carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide and to the extent of 30% of the total greenhouse gases.\u000a\u000aBhola wonders whether India will next be advised to produce less food!\u000a\u000aHe learns that if the whole world turned vegetarian and meat eating stopped completely, it could be a significant positive step in reducing the climate change problem. Bhola dismisses this idea as impracticalto him, it is as impractical as the suggestion that each Indian should have fewer emissions than each American.\u000a\u000aThen is the fifth question about how much it costs. It is such a humongous number that Bhola cant even get his mind around it. His pragmatic doubt is why spend such an enormous sum when the problem is not so clear.\u000a\u000aHe stumbles on research by the Copenhagen Consensus Centre that states that with the money it takes to save one life through carbon cuts, the world can save 78,000 lives from a disease like malaria!\u000a\u000aBhola is staggered. He wonders for a fleeting moment whether this may be the Wests way to prevent his country from lifting the poor out of their wretched and long-standing poverty. He tries to dismiss the thought, but the idea does not go away from his mind.\u000a\u000aHe then hears about a global conference to be held in Copenhagen. Top guns from all over the world will be meeting and spending a lot of money to hammer out an agreement. On what On reducing greenhouse gases, he is told. But did they not meet in Rio 20 years ago and again in Kyoto ten years ago to do something like that Yes, but they are going to try again. It did not work in the past because the big emitters did not implement their commitments after those expensive conferences!\u000a\u000aIn his community, the big leaders set an example to the plain folks by voluntarily doing difficult things first. That is how they stayed as leaders, by acting as leaders. Why do the big countries not do the same with regard to climate change when his little community practices this simple truth\u000a\u000aHe has no clear answer. Bhola feels that it is easier for the rich to give speeches and hold conferences than to be the first to take the pain. What a world!\u000a\u000aThe author is executive director, Tata Sons Ltd
