aVNEW DELHI: Australia\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds proposal for a climate change agreement for Copenhagen is expected to come up for discussion between Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe post-2012 successor agreement to the Kyoto Protocol, suggested by Australia, is based on national schedules. It would bring all countries \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd developed and developing \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd into the same document in the form of national schedules in which each country puts down what they would do.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIndia has two fundamental concerns about the Australian proposal \ufffd\ufffd\ufffd the first being the differentiation between developed (Annexe I) and developing (non-Annexe I) countries and the second, on developing countries not accepting legally binding commitments. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdIndia has two basic non-negotiable positions. One, the basic distinction between Annexe I and non-Annexe I countries enshrined in the Kyoto Protocol must be maintained. Two, legally binding emission targets are for developed (Annexe I) countries. The obligation for developing countries is to identify and make public nationally appropriate mitigation actions as mentioned in the Bali Action Plan,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd minister of state for environment Jairam Ramesh said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAustralia maintains that the difference between Annexe I and non-Annexe I countries is upheld in the proposal and that only developed (Annexe I) countries will be legally bound to reach the emission reduction outcomes recorded in the national schedule. Australia has argued that its proposal is an effort at \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdconsensus building\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe Australians maintain that their proposal \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdretains the headway\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd made by the Kyoto Protocol. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdAustralia\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds proposal does not affect the distinction between Annex I and non-Annex I parties under the convention. National schedules provide a mechanism for enhancing the implementation of the convention and is consistent with the convention,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd Australia\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds ambassador for climate change Louise Hands said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aFor India, the problem with this formulation is that it obfuscates the difference between developed and developing countries. While the agreement would make the legal differentiation, the glossing over would be for the domestic constituencies in the developed countries. India\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds objection is political and on principle. \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdIt is the first step towards doing away with Kyoto Protocol,\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd a senior government official said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe national schedule proposal would allow developed countries such as the US and Australia to show to their domestic constituencies that all countries, particularly advanced developing countries like China, India and Brazil, have been brought on board and are mentioned in the document. Given its domestic considerations, the US, in particular, has been adamant about getting China and India to commit to emission reduction targets.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a
