aVNEW DELHI: Hopes of sealing a new climate change protocol at the Copenhagen Summit in December were dashed with the US secretary of energy Steven Chu indicating that his government would not be signatory to a climate change protocol without the Senate\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds approval. US commitment is seen as crucial for the success of the Copenhagen Summit. Even as the US is emerging as the deal breaker, there is an effort by the US and other developed countries to shift the onus of a successful outcome on to the developing countries like India and China.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aExplaining Washington\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds unwillingness to make a commitment at Copenhagen without Senate approval, Mr Chu said: \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdWe do not want to repeat the historical mistake.\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd Then US vice-president Al Gore was instrumental in final negotiations on Kyoto Protocol in 1997, and the US signed the protocol in November 1998. However, the US Senate\ufffd\ufffd\ufffds unwillingness to ratify the Kyoto Protocol and, in 2001, the then US President George W Bush renouncing the accord made the US a non-signatory. It is unlikely that the US law on reducing emissions will be passed in time for Copenhagen.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe US and the other developed countries have been putting pressure on advanced developing countries such as China, India and Brazil to take on legally binding emission reduction targets. A suggestion that is understood by developing countries as the \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdjunking of the Kyoto Protocol\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd. Addressing an audience at IIT Delhi, Mr Chu made the case yet again. The visiting US secretary of energy said given that the developing countries will have more emissions \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdin the future\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd, they also have to take on \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdresponsibilities\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aTaking recourse to the principle of collective responsibility, Mr Chu said \ufffd\ufffd\ufffddeveloping countries can\ufffd\ufffd\ufffdt say that climate change is not our problem. It has to be a collaborative effort. We have to find ways how we can help each other in the future\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd. India and the other developing countries have reiterated that they have not abdicated their responsibility to ensuring the health of the planet. Instead, in keeping with the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change, developing nations have stressed on the principle of \ufffd\ufffd\ufffdcommon but differentiated responsibilities\ufffd\ufffd\ufffd. Placing the historical responsibility of global warming at the doorstep of the industrialised nations, countries like India have argued that it is these countries which will have to undertake legally binding emission cuts while the obligation of developing countries is to identify and make public nationally appropriate mitigation actions.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aKeeping its domestic constituency in mind, Washington needs to present a deal to its Senate that brings developing countries like India, China, Brazil within the ambit of legally binding emission targets. Mr Chu, who will be meeting with environment minister Jairam Ramesh on Saturday, is likely to make a case for some kind of binding commitments for India.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a
