aVNEW DELHI: The death knell for the Copenhagen climate change summit has been rung. With the US, the biggest emitter of greenhouse gases, throwing its weight behind the proposal to postpone a legally-binding climate deal till 2010 or later, the best that can be expected at Copenhagen is a political or vision statement.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aUS president Barack Obama's acknowledgement that time had run out to seal a deal at Copenhagen should come as no surprise. The call for a political statement had been building up since the middle of the year, before the Bangkok and Barcelona round of negotiations. For developing countries like India, the task is to ensure that the Copenhagen declaration does not become the gateway for jettisoning the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) and Kyoto Protocol.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWith a deal no longer forthcoming in Copenhagen, the big question before India is how it will manage negotiations over the next one year. There is concern that while India may have shrugged off the tag of a 'deal breaker', it has simultaneously given up its negotiating space by placing all its cards on the table.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aOver the past few months, India has announced its intention for bringing a domestic legislation to limit future emissions and offered to give biennial reports to UNFCCC on its domestic actions.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBy making concessions so early in the game, India appeared to have alienated the less-developed countries and small island states for whom climate change is a clear and present danger. Given that negotiations for the post-Kyoto second commitment period will now carry on for another year, India has given up all its bargaining power without extracting any reciprocal concessions from developed countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aLabelling India as a 'deal breaker' has been a negotiating tactic by the developed world to force it to show its hand. Industrialised countries may have succeeded in this move. A senior negotiator said: "We should take proactive measures to deal with climate change as long as it promotes development. We should undertake mitigation and adaptation actions as long as it does not take away resources from our other development goals. There is no harm in putting on the table all the actions that India undertakes provided that there is reciprocal action from developed countries."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe US president's support for the Danish plan to convert the Copenhagen meet into a first-stage series of commitments rather than an all-encompassing protocol did not find takers among leaders from developing countries. Grenada's environment minister Michael Church said: "We believe that an internationally legally binding agreement is still possible." Mr Church was speaking on behalf of more than 40 nations in the Alliance of Small Island States. A sentiment that was echoed by Sudan's UN ambassador Lumumba Stanislaus Di-Aping: "We are not moving away from a belief that a full treaty is possible in Copenhagen." Mr Di-Aping represents developing nations in the Group of 77 and China.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBut the move away from a internationally binding agreement at Copenhagen is not a bolt from the blue. Developed nations have been pushing this line for a while and Denmark's Prime Minister Lars Lokke Rasmussen has been pitching Plan B, that is Copenhagen talks should set political targets and outline commitments. The real apprehension is that a political statement could mean that developed countries will push for a replacement of the Kyoto Protocol. Former negotiator Surya Sethi said: "To succumb to a political statement would be detrimental to our interests. It is better that there be no agreement at all than a bad agreement. A political statement will necessarily vague and may not conform to UNFCCC, like the L'Aquila declaration. Given that political statement will be necessarily vague, it will be open to all kinds of interpretations. A bad agreement will queer the pitch for future negotiations."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIndia needs to ensure that the Copenhagen declaration does not lead to the junking of Kyoto Protocol. The US and EU have been arguing for a 'new agreement', one that 'takes everyone on board'. To this end, India along with other developing countries must make sure that the political declaration doesn't allow for this to happen.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aSenior Indian negotiator Ajay Mathur said: "We need to make sure that our negotiating partners remain at the table. We must ensure that an agreement limiting future emissions from Annexe I countries is reached." In the absence of this agreement on emissions by developed countries an agreement outside of the Kyoto Protocol, the Bali Action Plan and the UNFCCC becomes a possibility. "At the very least, all countries have to agree that the process of negotiations has to go on. We have to ensure that we get people back on the Kyoto Protocol track," Mr Mathur said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a"While there is no agreement on the architecture, substantial progress has been made on details, including vexatious ones like finance and technology. There is no final agreement but progress has been made. At Copenhagen, all countries should agree to preserve the progress that has been made," a senior negotiator said. The Danish proposal would buy time for the US. Over the past week, through statements by various high-ranking officials, Washington has made it clear that it will not sign on to a deal till the US Senate passes the domestic carbon-capping legislation. The Kerry-Lugar Bill will allowing the Obama administration to bring a 2020 target and financing pledges to the table at a UN climate meeting in mid-2010. The bill proposes an emission reduction target, which works out to 4% from the 1990 levels. The target has been described inadequate by the developing world which is pushing for a 25% to 40% reduction in emissions by the Annexe I or developed countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBut it will also mean increasing pressure on developing countries such as India, China, Brazil and South Africa to accept internationally binding emission reduction targets.
