aVNEW DELHI: Over the last few months, India's negotiating position on climate change has been marked by sufficient 'confusion'. Over the past few months in the run up to Copenhagen, different versions of India's negotiating position were presented, with all parties claiming that there has been no shift in stance. Much of the confusion appears to have emanated from what seems like a power struggle between environment minister Jairam Ramesh and the prime minister's special envoy for climate change Shyam Saran. It is not clear what Prime Minister Manmohan Singh's position in this internecine rivalry is.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn July, Mr Saran defended the L'Aquila declaration, which saw India accepting for the first time the 2 degrees Centigrade temperature cap. He was the lead negotiator at the Major Economies Forum meeting. India had thus far not accepted this temperature cap, arguing that "the setting of any such goal must be decided in tandem with the establishment of a basis for equitable burden sharing". India had argued that the temperature cap was a backdoor imposition of legally binding emission cuts for developing countries like India. The prime minister clarified his position on the issue in Parliament. He argued that a there had not been a shift in the Indian position. Instead, the L'Aquila declaration represented a shared view among 17 developed and developing countries, explaining the wording which reflects "different approaches and positions of a fairly diverse group of countries."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn early September, Mr Ramesh announced the idea of a law that would embody India's mitigation efforts with broadly indicative targets. The idea of law that would translate India's domestic actions in terms of a emission targets was viewed as a first step towards accepting legally binding caps. The minister subsequently clarified that there would be no explicit emission reduction targets, but there would be implicit performance targets.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBut that was not the only point of confusion. In September, during his visit to the US, Mr Ramesh made an unilateral offer to submit a detailed communication to the UNFCC once every two years. India, as with all non-Annexe I countries, is required to submit a report only once every six years. He reiterated that only those measures that are funded internationally and supported through international technology transfer will be subject to international monitoring, verification and reporting.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn what appeared to be a departure, Mr Ramesh suggested, in a letter to the prime minister, dated September 24, that "for those mitigation actions that we undertake unilaterally and on our own, we could certainly consider a mechanism to ensure that the international community is kept abreast of what we are doing \u2014 somewhat along the lines of the Trade policy Review of the WTO and the Article IV consultations with the IMF". In a letter to members of Parliament written just four days after his letter to PM, the environment minister dropped the suggestion. He did however mention the idea of a more detailed and frequent report to the UNFCCC. The flash point between the minister and the special envoy came when in a note to PM, Mr Ramesh made a series of suggestions, including a greater flexibility on India's part to safeguard its interests. This was viewed by many in the negotiating team, including Mr Saran and senior negotiator Chandrasekhar Dasgupta, as a "sell out to the US".\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aMr Ramesh had to issue a clarification which reiterated India's position. He stressed that while India was prepared to discuss and make public periodically the implementation of its National Action Plan on climate change, India will never accept internationally legally binding emission reduction targets or commitments as part of any agreement or deal or outcome. Neither would India ever accept any dilution or renegotiation of the provisions and principles of the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC). "In particular. we will never agree to the elimination of the distinction between developed ("Annex I") countries and developing ("non-Annex I") countries as far as internationally legally binding emission reduction obligations are concerned. Internationally legally binding emission reduction targets are for developed countries and developed countries alone, as globally agreed under the Bail Action Plan."
