aVNEW DELHI: In keeping with India's national effort to move to path of low carbon intensity development, the Union Cabinet is expected to approve a proposal to incentivise generation of wind energy through a generation-based incentive.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aA sustainable energy mix with a larger contribution from renewables is part of India's national effort of dealing with climate change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe proposal is an effort to move away from the current practice of a manufacturer driven approach towards one focused on the generator.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn the current system, adopted in the mid-1990s, the government provides accelerated depreciation for installation of wind energy projects. This incentive will be phased out by the end of the Eleventh Plan or till the direct tax code comes into effect, whichever is earlier.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aGeared to increasing generation from wind, the proposal suggests an incentive of Rs 0.50 per unit of wind energy produced. The government has set a target of 4,000 MW of power from wind in the next two years.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe scheme of accelerated depreciation brought in to ensure new players into the sector has served its purpose, with India becoming a manufacturing hub. The government's focus is now on increasing efficiency, bringing down costs and expanding the sector by encouraging core players , such as independent power producers and foreign investment.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBy linking incentives to generation, the government hopes that the cost of power from wind will be substantially reduced thereby ensuring its place as a source for distribution companies.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe Cabinet is also likely to consider the national solar mission document, which requires India to generate 1,000 mw of solar power every year by 2013. The proposal could lead to annual production of 20,000 mw by 2020.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn the first phase, between 2010 and 2013, the government is also proposing to generate 200 mw of off-grid solar power and cover 7 million sq metres with solar collectors. The mission is in three phases, with the ambitious targets and financial mechanisms for the latter two phases being reviewed on the basis of performance in the first three-year phase.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBy the end of the final phase in 2022, the government hopes to produce 20,000 mw of gridbased solar power, 2,000 mw of offgrid solar power and cover 20 million sq metres with collectors.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAs part of the India's commitment to undertake domestic actions to tackle climate change, the government on Wednesday tightened air quality rules and said it will enforce a single standard for industrial and residential pollution. The Revised National Ambient Air Quality Standards rule would lead to the use of "clean fuel" to lower emissions, Minister of State for Environment and Forests Jairam Ramesh said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe new guidelines match those set out by the European Union in 2008. "We have removed the distinction between industrial and residential areas. This is very important. Now standards will be uniform irrespective of whether it is classified as industrial or residential area. The consequences of the new standards will be clean fuel and this will have a major implication on greenhouse gas emissions as well," Mr Ramesh said.
