aVNEW DELHI: The Centre on Thursday confirmed that there was no possibility of reaching a climate change treaty at the Copenhagen summit "You should not have too much expectations from Copenhagen summit. The mandate to negotiate will get renewed. It seems there is a long haul before we arrive at a meaningful international commitment," Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh said.The government, which reiterated its unequivocal rejection of legally binding emission limits, said it was "prepared to be alone" in its rejection. But with more negotiations in the offing, the pressure on developing countries like India to accept legally binding emission caps is certain to increase.Mr Ramesh also said that there was a need to "distinguish international commitments from the domestic action".Suggesting the need to recognise that "climate change was essentially a domestic issue", the minister said that there is need to be "aggressive, progressive and ruthless" in undertaking domestic measures to limit emissions."India's position would be strengthened internationally if we are aggressive at home. While we must be proactive in our domestic measures, India will never agree to targets," Mr Ramesh said.Arguing for aggressive domestic action, the minister said that India was most vulnerable to climate change. India is impacted by climate change on multiple fronts. A rise in sea level would impact 300 million people of peninsular India, and the uncertain impact on the Himalayan glacier will affect the river systems of the north, and the fact that India is still shaped by the monsoon makes climate change a major issue for the country. The vagaries of monsoon have resulted in a 45 per cent variation in GDP.Treating climate change as a development issue, Mr Ramesh challenged the western notion of linking population with climate change."There is a move to brand population as a culprit. There now is abundant empirical evidence to show that there is no link between population and greenhouse gas emissions.Between 1985 and 2005, China had a negative growth rate, yet its emissions rose by 43 per cent. It is more an issue of lifestyle and consumption," the minster said.
