aVCautious stand\u000a\u000aEven as the possibilities of a consensus remain elusive at the Copenhagen meet next month, India hopes to take a cautious stand.\u000a\u000aIndia has been singled out by the negotiators from developed countries as a \u201cdeal-breaker\u201d and a \u201crejectionist\u201d country on multilateral negotiations.\u000a\u000aArun S.\u000a\u000aAnil Sasi\u000a\u000aNew Delhi, Nov. 21 India\u2019s negotiating stance at the forthcoming Copenhagen summit could emphasise that its services-led growth model is less Greenhouse Gas (GHG)-intensive than other manufacturing-dominated economies including China.\u000a\u000aA report by the Department of Economic Affairs (DEA) on the major issues and policy implications on climate change says that the issue of lower GHG emissions on account of a service-dominated GDP needs to be considered while making internal reforms relating to climate change and as an argument on GHG emissions.\u000a\u000a\u201cThere is a need to see how the calculations are done on future emissions. Services-led growth is also environment-friendly growth\u2026This can be used as a powerful argument in our negotiations regarding GHG emissions,\u201d the report, authored by Mr H.A.C. Prasad and Mr J.S. Kochher, said. The report is being considered by policy makers including the Thirteenth Finance Commission, sources said.\u000a\u000aWhile the merits of buttressing the \u201crelatively more clean service sector\u201d argument with the per capita emissions is being debated in the policy circles, experts however have cautioned against the pitfalls of using this strategy.\u000a\u000aDiffering on the strength of this argument, they feel it is a myth that services sectors are less energy-intensive as a whole.\u000a\u000aDr Prodipto Ghosh, member of the Prime Minister\u2019s Council on Climate Change and Distinguished Fellow at The Energy and Resources Institute (TERI), told Business Line, \u201cYou cannot generalise that services sector is energy saving. Service sectors use computers, air-conditioned buildings and polluting vehicles to ferry their workers. These are all energy consuming.\u201d\u000a\u000aMany services sectors could be broadly comparable to certain manufacturing sectors such as engineering goods and textiles on energy usage, he said. However, he added that services may be less energy intensive than sectors such as steel and cement.\u000a\u000a\u2018Unfavourable comparisons\u2019\u000a\u000aDr Ghosh said, \u201cIndia will be shooting itself in the foot by making unfavourable comparisons with China. We may be on the same side on several issues. Also, why should we put unnecessary constraints on ourselves saying we will always be a services-oriented country? We have huge infrastructure needs and lot of investments are flowing into energy-intensive sectors like steel and cement to cater to our demands.\u201d\u000a\u000aDr Arpita Mukherjee, Professor, Indian Council for Research on International Economic Relations, said, \u201cJust because the size of the manufacturing in a country is more does not mean that it will pollute more. They could be using energy-efficient technologies. Even in a services economy, it is important to invest in energy-saving mass transport services like the Metro and promote environment-friendly measures like green buildings, using CNG in vehicles and banning plastic.\u201d\u000a\u000aCautious stand\u000a\u000aEven as the possibilities of a consensus remain elusive at the Copenhagen meet next month, India hopes to take a cautious stand. India has been singled out by the negotiators from developed countries as a \u201cdeal-breaker\u201d and a \u201crejectionist\u201d country on multilateral negotiations.\u000a\u000aThe Government, which has reiterated its unequivocal rejection of legally binding emission limits, has said it is \u201cprepared to be alone\u201d in its rejection. But with more negotiations in the offing, the pressure on developing countries like India to accept legally binding emission caps is certain to increase.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated November 22, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated
