aVThe not-so-public spat between the Minister of State for Environment and Forests, Jairam Ramesh mad the Prime Minister's Special Envoy on climate change Shyam Saran might have compelled the PM to step into the breach and may (?) have embarrassed its main protagonists. It may also have weakened our position internationally by showing up the differences within the Indian establishment.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBut there is a silver lining. The fracas between the Ramesh and Shyam Saran has finally shifted climate change from the inside pages of most dailies to page one. With a little bit of luck, not only will it stay on page one, but in course of time, will become part of a much wider mainstream debate.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThat is a change we sorely need to see. For one, quite unlike either the World Trade Organisation (WTO) talks on multilateral trade or the G-20 talks on fixing the global financial architecture, climate change affects each one of us and the poor even more, intimately.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIf the UNFCC (United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change) is to be believed, 'climate change is one of the most fundamental challenges ever to confront humanity'. There is overwhelming scientific evidence, says the UNFCC, that 'climate change will threaten economic growth and long-term prosperity, as well as the very survival of the most vulnerable populations.'\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe projections of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change indicate that if emissions continue to rise at their current pace the world will face an average temperature rise of around 3C this century. This will result in a rise in the sea-level, shifts in growing seasons with serious implications for food security and an increasing frequency and intensity of extreme weather events such as storms, floods and droughts.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aOne may disagree with the precise numbers, given that it is still a very inexact science. But if, as many fear, inaction will prove more costly than action and economic development needs to be moved onto a low-emissions-climate-resilient path, the world will have to co-operate far more than it has done in the context of either the G-20 or WTO talks.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt also means countries will have to reorient their economic growth patterns, advanced countries embracing life-style changes and developing ones adopting development strategies that could slowdown their pace of growth. To put it in a nutshell, any commitment on climate change will necessarily involve trade-offs, trade-offs that involve future generations much more than the present one.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt is imperative, therefore, that we widen the debate to beyond M/s Ramesh and Saran and few intellectuals. Today, if climate change seems far removed from the aam admi/aurat's radar, it is not because she is not concerned. It is simply that is much lower down in her list of priorities. For her it is roti, kapda aur makaan and everything else a poor second.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBut the problem, as environmentalists tell us, is that it is not an either-or choice. We need to work on both in parallel. If we don't, we could not only paint ourselves into a corner and be branded spoilers as with the WTO negotiations. But, worse, could do incalculable harm to ourselves as India is one of the countries likely to be severely affected by climate change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAt the very least, therefore, the government must widen the debate and be more transparent about any commitments it agrees to. In advanced countries contentious issues are often decided by referendum. In the Indian context that might be difficult, in view of the complexity of the issues and the ground reality of an uneducated population (though much the same arguments were made against universal franchise while drafting the Constitution!).\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a
