aVThe climate deal to be sealed in Copenhagen will be based on a shared vision for long-term cooperation. The preparatory meeting at Barcelona has concluded without any agreement on the global goal. Divergence is over what is to be shared across countries: global emission reduction objectives or global atmospheric resources. The peaking of global emissions is among the proposals being considered, and it has implications for sharing a scarce natural resource.\u000a\u000aThe national consensus in India, that its per capita emissions will not exceed the average per capita emissions of developed countries, presupposes that we have the carbon space for sustainable development. As policy space is increasingly going to be defined by the availability of carbon space, we need to redefine our climate policy and define the global goal accordingly.\u000a\u000aHowever, we have not developed a coherent framework to drive the negotiations, and are merely responding to the agenda set by developed countries. We continue to rely on the position developed in 1992, with its focus on historical responsibility of developed countries in causing the problem. In forums like the G5 and G8, we have emphasised the importance of ensuring equal sustainable development potential, but have not followed up in the climate negotiations with a new paradigm.\u000a\u000aDeveloped countries have a clear vision for retaining their share of the carbon space by modifying burden-sharing. They favour global pricing of carbon and the use of market-based instrumentssuch as emissions tradingas crucial to keeping the costs of their actions low, and are pushing for setting national, or even sectoral, intensity targets for developing countries as a way of encouraging developing countries to reduce emissions. They also believe that boosting international deployment of low-carbon technologies is best achieved by developing countries removing barriers to trade and foreign direct investment. In this framework, approaches to support energy efficiency and adoption of low-carbon technologies have only a complementary role. We cannot adopt this framework, and must come forward with our own framework because of at least three reasons.\u000a\u000aFirst, recent analysis by the International Energy Agency shows that sectoral resource use and final energy mix varies significantly between developed and developing countries, requiring very different solutions at the national level. In developed countries, transport, residential and services sectors account for two-thirds of final energy use. Transport emissions are the fastest growing emissions. As oil products account for nearly half of total energy use, developed country policy focus is on measures for decarbonising energy. In developing countries, transportation accounts for only one-third of total energy use. In India, just 10% of emissions are from the transport and residential sectors. As our energy use per capita is less than one-tenth of developed country levels, this situation is going to change very rapidly. For example, between 1990-2005, passenger travel tripled in China, while freight haulage more than doubled, and per capita energy use increased nearly 50%.\u000a\u000aIn India, the main driver of energy demand up to the year 2050 will be the movement of some 300 million people into towns. The strategic policy issue for decoupling energy use from economic growth will be modifying the nature of the urbanisation process. In the climate negotiations we must propose a framework centered on equitable access to carbon space. Developed countries must immediately reduce their emissions from the services, household and transportation sectors down to the global average, as these sectors are projected to account for more than half of all global emissions in 2050. Second, offsets are a central part of the framework put forward by developed countries. Costs for them can be reduced by 40% by offsets from forest conservation measures. The UK Low Carbon Transition Plan states that the entire required mitigation in the energy industry will come from offsets. Offsets really allow developed countries to continue to occupy carbon space, and present us with a dilemma because of the financial transfers in the purchase of credits. India should insist that monitoring modification of longer-term trends would be a necessary part of any deal.\u000a\u000aThird, it is usually ignored that, at the climate change negotiations in Bali, in December 2007, developing countries agreed to take mitigation actions in the context of sustainable development. This distinction was made to secure carbon space. That objective will be achieved only if we are able to ensure that the actions shift from considering the environmental impact of carbon dioxide to analysing linkages with energy and ecological services for human wellbeing. Multilateral cooperation should be state-led and devoted to long-term opportunities for deep reduction of carbon emissions defined as technology-oriented strategies for the production sectors.\u000a\u000aWe must take the leadership in developing a new paradigm that defines the global goal in terms of modifying consumption patterns and development of new technologies, so that patterns of resource use are common for all countries. It is only within such a framework that we will secure the carbon space needed for sustainable development.\u000a\u000aThe author has worked at the policy level in the government of India and in the UN Climate Change secretariat
