aVNEW DELHI: China has invited key developing country partners on November 27 for talks on climate change ahead of the UN negotiations that commence in Copenhagen on December 7.Union environment minister Jairam Ramesh along with other officials will attend the China meeting.Coming after both China and India signed MoUs with the US on climate and energy related issues, the meeting could see a reaffirming of the stance of the major players in the G77 block, sources said. Brazil and South Africa besides other key smaller countries are also expected to be part of the one-day deliberations.Doubts had been raised about both China and India breaking ranks from the developing country block and aligning with the US. Apprehensions about being left isolated at the crucial talks by other key developing world partners in December had been voiced at high levels within the Indian government as well. At the same time, smaller but as influential G77 partners had over the past two months watched the controversial divergence in the Indian camp with as much consternation.Brazil, one of the four key big economies in the G77 block, had recently put a proposal to reduce its emissions primarily through externally supported reduction in deforestation but this too had been misinterpreted in some circles as stepping away from the classic G77 positions.Some G77 country representatives had gone public voicing concerns about the attempts by developed countries to `divide and rule' over the G77.The funding and forging of a group called the vulnerable countries -- including Mauritius and Bangladesh -- as a separate voice at the UN meet had also caught the attention of negotiators in the block. The UK Department of International Department funded and helped organise a meeting of the `vulnerable countries' in Mauritius, which was seen in many quarters as an attempt along the lines.Coming in the wake of such concerns being raised in different quarters of the G77 block, the China meet, sources said, could help reduce apprehensions among those who have so far been partner countries at the climate negotiations.
