aVNEW DELHI: Faced with manoeuvring of US and China, India on Friday upped its Copenhagen offer by promising to bring down emissions by 20% to 25% between 2020 and 2030. Environment minister Jairam Ramesh, who announced the re-worked Indian position, maintained that it would be voluntary and that the country would not take any internationally legally binding commitments.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn the past one week, there have been hectic activities on climate change in the US, China and Brazil with all three countries announcing their respective positions for the summit. The latest move by India is expected to buffer it against a possible charge that it's the main hurdle to a solution. At the pre-COP meeting in Copenhagan, India had not quantified the emission target. It has also moved beyond the pre-COP meeting to promise performance targets across the economy.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe development comes in the wake of the announcement by China that it would cut carbon intensity by 40-45% by 2020 from 2005 levels. This was cited as a move forward by the developed countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe announcement on reducing future levels of greenhouse gas emissions by Beijing has been in the works, and president Hu Jintao had indicated Beijing's plans during is address to the UN General Assembly in September.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThere was comforting news for India from Bejing on Friday when it reiterated that it has not broken away from G-77 and that Thursday's announcement was a voluntary, domestically binding policy goal, and not internationally legally binding commitment. This is in line with New Delhi's position.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIndia has been undertaking domestic measures to deal with climate change through the National Action Plan on Climate Change. The most recent of this was the unveiling of the national solar mission, a policy decision to increase the renewable energy component in India's energy basket.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn Port of Spain, prime minister's special envoy on climate change Shyam Saran said that China's decision to cut carbon intensity by 40-45% by 2020 did not amount to cutting down emissions. Mr Saran said that India need not follow what China has decided as he noted that India already has ambitious action plans to shift dependability from carbon-based fuels to renewable energy sources, like nuclear, solar and wind energy.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aMr Saran stressed that India is the voice of developing nations on the issue of climate change. Reminding that there must be equitable burden-sharing among member nations, the special envoy said: "We are not negotiating a new agreement in Copenhagen. It's on the Bali and UN round. All countries should share burden. CHOGM is basically developing nations, so, it is here that they will express the voice explicitly."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aSenior Indian negotiator Chandrasekhar Dasgupta, too, reacted on similar lines. "China should be congratulated on its voluntary national action plan."
