aVChina's announcement that it would cut its carbon dioxide emissions per unit of gross domestic product between 40% and 45% from 2005 has suddenly added spice to the Copenhagen summit, which had begun to look like a bland dish.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe fact that the Chinese announcement followed close on the heels of a conditional US commitment to 17% reduction during the same time frame, has fuelled rumours of a Kyoto successor emerging in Copenhagen next month. A close reading of media reports about the latest Chinese position makes one feel that any over-optimism on this score may be misplaced.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aScroll back to China's situation two years ago to get the flavour:\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aFor China, 2007 may have been the most eventful year of the decade. The economic powerhouse finally achieved its 'actual great leap forward' as the largest CO2 emission source of the world. Its automobiles, machine tools and steel exports were meeting with increased tariff and non tariff resistance from importing countries including the US. Internally the country witnessed simmering discontent in its energy sector as coal mines groaned under the pressure of low-administered prices and falling operating margins aggravated by mine accidents and serious bottlenecks in freight movements.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aSometime in March that year, prime minister Wen Jiabo confessed that China's economic growth 'is unsteady, unbalanced, uncoordinated and unsustainable'. Two months later, the National Development and Reform Commission (NDRC) released China's National Climate Change Programme (NCCP), a document that talked about China's approach to address climate change, based on national action to reduce energy and carbon intensity through energy efficiency and hybrid fuel mixes.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aFor China, a low carbon path is a national priority and a sure way to keep up its economic tempo. In reality, NCCP is a sub-set of the country's energy and economic security policies. (It is NDRC and not the Chinese ministry of environmental protection that is in charge of the Chinese NCCP). China can ill-afford to let 'invisible' carbon denominated process and production methods (PPMs) standards, shackle its export offensive.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aMore than India, it is China that should be worried about the current efforts to re-interpret Article XX (e) of GATT to keep out 'goods based on carbon intensive processes'. In reality, China has been under greater pressure to stave off the 'climate related threat' from the WTO window. By sending a 'concrete' signal of commitment to emission intensity reduction, the People's Republic is doing its best to keep the trade dragon from getting into the FCCC fold.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIf media reports are to be believed, China's latest commitment on emission intensity reduction is voluntary. Energy efficiency will be the strategy to achieve the targets. Now this is something that is eminently achievable by the emerging economic superpower. China's carbon intensity has been declining for over a decade. Its power and cement sectors have experienced substantial gains by way of enhanced energy efficiency.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThere is nothing that the Chinese cabinet has now announced that goes against the spirit of its National Climate Change Programme of 2007. Similar is India's record on the energy efficiency front. A commitment for reducing intensity of carbon emissions through the energy efficiency track is not the same as mandatory mitigation cuts on aggregate emissions that developed countries would like the Asian giants to undertake.\u000a\u000a
