aV\u201cIndia and China are on the same page as far as the negotiations are concerned but not on the emissions front.\u201d \u2013 Mr Jairam Ramesh\u000a\u000aAnil Sasi\u000a\u000aNew Delhi, Nov. 27\u000a\u000aChina's pledge for voluntary cuts in \u2018carbon intensity' could turn the heat on India at the Copenhagen Summit, feel Indian experts.\u000a\u000aChina has announced cuts in carbon intensity as against direct emission reduction targets. The Chinese announcements follow a declaration by the US on emission cuts earlier in the week.\u000a\u000aChina will reduce its carbon intensity to 40-45 per cent of 2005 levels by 2020, a meeting of the State Council, China's Cabinet, declared on Thursday.\u000a\u000aIt was also announced that the Chinese Premier, Mr Wen Jiabao, will attend next month's climate talks. The announcement came a day after the US proposed a 17 per cent reduction in emissions below 2005 levels by 2020, and 83 per cent by 2050.\u000a\u000a\u201cThe term carbon intensity essentially means the amount of greenhouse gases emitted per yuan of economic activity. This is very different from an upfront cut in emissions. Reducing carbon intensity does not mean China's net emissions will fall,\u201d said a climate change expert.\u000a\u000a\u201cWith the first concrete numbers put on the table by the world's largest and second biggest polluters, India is certain to be targeted at the (Copenhagen) meet. Following the US and Chinese pledges, India now is the only remaining major emitter that has not yet announced any cuts,\u201d a member of the Indian negotiating team said.\u000a\u000aA key goal of the UN-sponsored talks in Copenhagen is to clinch a successor Treaty to the Kyoto Protocol before it expires in 2012. This seems unlikely, say officials.\u000a\u000aIndia continues to maintain that it will not submit to any legally binding cuts on carbon emissions but it has announced a National Action Plan on Climate Change.\u000a\u000aThe Minister of State for Environment and Forests, Mr Jairam Ramesh, left for China on Friday for talks with his Chinese counterpart.\u000a\u000a\u201cIndia and China are on the same page as far as the negotiations are concerned but not on the emissions front,\u201d Mr Ramesh said at the sidelines of an event here on Thursday.\u000a\u000aIndia could face immense pressure from the US and the European Union at the negotiations, especially with China now announcing its carbon intensity curbs.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated November 28, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
