aVNEW DELHI: Prime Minister Manmohan Singh on Saturday formally said that India was willing to sign on to an global target for emission reduction or limiting temperature increase. The Prime Minister's statement comes a day after the minister of state for environment Jairan Ramesh announced that India would consider voluntarily reducing its carbon intensity by 20 to 25 per cent on purely domestic basis. In an attempt to tackle domestic opposition to what is being perceived as a shift in India's known position, Mr Singh said that India's offer must be accompanied by an "equitable burden-sharing paradigm."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aStressing that India was committed to the principle of equity and common but differentiated responsibilities enshrined in the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, Mr Singh said, "We acknowledge the imperative of science but science must not trump equity. Climate Change action based on the perpetuation of poverty will simply not be sustainable."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aRefering to India's appreciation of its responsibilities to deal with this global problem, Mr Singh spoke of the National Action Plan on Climate Change with 8 National Mission covering both mitigation and adaptation. "We have not made their implementation conditional upon obtaining international support. However, we can certainly do more if there is a supportive global regime. Each of the National Missions, including those on renewable energy, enhancing energy efficiency and expanding forest cover, are platforms on which we would be happy to pursue cooperative partnership with sister Commonwealth countries."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aPrime Minister Singh said that if the consensus at Copenhagen is a "political document", then it was incumbent to ensure that the post Copenhagen process does not violate the mandate of the Convention. "If the consensus is that only a political document is feasible then we must make certain that the post-Copenhagen process continues to work on the Bali mandate and the UNFCCC continues to be the international template for global climate action. We must avoid any lowering of sights," Mr Singh said in his address to the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meet.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn his address, Mr Singh reiterated time and again India's adherence to the principles enshrined in the UNFCCC, Kyoto Protocol and Bali Action Plan. He said that abandoning its commitment to the principles of equity and common but differentiated responsibilities was not acceptable.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aMr Singh said, "if the outcome at Copenhagen diminishes rather than enhances the implementation of the UNFCCC in respect of the specific components of mitigation, adaptation, finance and technology, it would represent a serious setback, no matter how we seek to characterise this result."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aExplaining the urgency to reach a decision, the prime minister pointed out that several small island developing nations, which are the least responsible for climate change, are the most vulnerable to its impact and their "very survival is at stake."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn a strongly worded intervention, Mr Singh said that it was unfortunate that some developed nations were attempting to junk the Kyoto Protocol. Climate change, the prime minister said, "is becoming the pretext for pursuing protectionist policies under a green label. This would be contrary to the UNFCCC and a violation of the WTO as well". A move that will be rejected by India and other developing nations.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a
