aVNEW DELHI: Prime Minister Manmohan Singh could be veering close to accepting the Danish invitation to attend the Copenhagen Climate meet on December 18, sources told TOI. While the inclination to attend the meet had increased in recent days, a final decision was yet to be taken.The pressure on PM to mark his presence on the final day of the two-week long UN climate talks has been mounting in the past month.French President Nicholas Sarkozy had earlier requested him to attend the heads of state meeting. The PM's Chinese counterpart, Wen Jiabao, has already announced his participation and so has Brazilian president Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva. The confirmation of heads of the two emerging economy governments is bound to weigh in favour of Manmohan Singh's visit.US president Barack Obama's visit on the last day could have sealed the Indian decision but the fact that Obama would instead be attending in the middle of the first week has left some ambiguity in the Indian camp.While the first week of the UN talks will be held at the bureaucratic level of negotiators, the week starting December 14 would be a ministerial round culminating at the end on December 18 with the heads of state meet.With expectations being lowered for the Copenhagen meet and a demand for a politically binding agreement instead of a comprehensive pact, weight is being added to the participation at Copenhagen `at the highest level' from all key countries.As significant as the PM's visit would be that the government would need to take a call soon if it would volunteer a domestic target to reduce carbon intensity, following along the footsteps of its neighbour, China.With experts in the government aware of both the pressure to announce a similar measure but also conscious of the differing economic and energy scenarios of the two Asian giants, the top heads in the Indian team would have to weigh the pros and cons of such a move.Added to the matrix would be the heightened focus on climate change within the domestic political arena with Parliament still in session. The Lower House is to have a discussion on the issue on December 3 and Rajya Sabha has already recorded a heated debate on policy shift of the UPA government on climate change.
