aVThe statement by Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, in a way, assures that India is willing to work for ambitious global emission cuts and, perhaps, sign on to some sort of binding commitments, provided there is sharing of the technological and fiscal burdens. However, along with this, there is also the news that India is even considering the drastic step of walking out of the conference along with Brazil, South Africa and China (BASIC block).\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aApparently, according to the minister for environment and forests, China will play the lead in developing a BASIC 'draft', which 'fully meets India's goals and aspirations'. The walkout, however, may not happen given the prime minister's optimistic reminder that the Bali Action Plan adopted in December 2007 had, indeed, laid out the goal of an 'agreed outcome' for Copenhagen.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAll this seems to present a certain lack of coherence and clear sense of purpose in India's approach. It will be a welcome change if the country is to play a bold and assertive role in pushing for deep emission cuts while keeping options open for appropriate mechanisms to achieve this. India's position, perhaps, has veered around to accepting deep cuts in the emission intensity, which does mark a welcome departure from the traditional adherence to the per-capita emission (PCE, tonnes CO2) entitlements approach.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn the absence of a nuanced and more substantive rendering, the approach based on PCE has tended to become something of a dogma and has lost its capacity to push for substantive forward steps to cut emissions. Its application has tended to become more as a negative instrument to oppose certain positions than advance any positive proposals. Irrespective of the approach used, negotiations must lead to imposing serious obligations domestically and multilaterally on the nations to address the twin challenges of poverty and global climate change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe global financial crisis has definitely dimmed the possibilities of a 'strong' treaty emerging from climate talks in Copenhagen. Yet, it underscores and brings to the fore the need to move beyond the tall talks of voluntary commitments. In fact, experience clearly point to the limits of excessive reliance on self-regulation and underscores the need for strong binding mechanisms. It is clearly time to put an end to voluntary commitments and the dreams of self-regulation. There are two sides to this.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe first is the fundamental nature of the global climate change crisis with deep roots in market failure. There is no mechanism that appears to allow the effects of economic activity to be transferred into the realm of markets within sufficiently-reasonable time to make a self-regulating effect. The time lags over which that could happen, if it ever does, is too long and uncertain to work as a self-correcting feedback on the market economy.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBesides this, there is also the near-complete impossibility of arriving at any reasonable causal connection between climate change effects in one geographical location with the economic activities in another. The only way open at this stage is to put in place a sufficiently-dynamic regulatory regime that can bring accountability in the response to global climate change concerns.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a
