aVIndia forest and tree cover has grown to 23.84% of its geographical area, as per the latest report issued by the government on Monday. Environment minister Jairam Ramesh released India State of the Forest Report 2009 just a week before the Copenhagen global summit on climate change. He said the expansion of the countrys forest cover neutralises more than 11% of greenhouse gas emissions from the worlds fourth largest polluter.\u000a\u000aThe data will add strength to Indias demand for special financial incentive from the international community during the Copenhegen summit for its effort in regenerating and protecting forest resources, which have emerged as major carbon sinks. The report, only the second one issued by the ministry of environment and forest since 1987 notes that the countrys forest cover has increased to 69.09 million hectare from 65.96 million hectare as per the latest 1997 assessment, an increase of 4.75% in area.\u000a\u000aThis means 21.02% of the total land area is under forest. Including tree cover and excluding the high reaches of mountains, the total green cover is 25.25% of the land area.\u000a\u000aThere is little scope to increase the area under forest, Ramesh said. The main focus would be on improving the quality of the tree cover in the existing forest area. The report, prepared by Forest Survey of India shows the country has added 0.3 million hectare of forest cover annually during 1997-2007. However high-density forests covered only 2.54% of land mass and moderately dense forests covered 9.71% while 8.77% was scrub.\u000a\u000aThe report said that seven northeastern states have close to one fourth of the countrys forest cover and the region has gained 59,800 hectare of forest cover as compared to the previous assessment of 2005. On the inter state variations in the forest cover, Ramesh said states such as Uttarkhand, Himachal Pradesh, Jammu and Kashmir, Sikkim, Arunchal Pradesh, Chhattisgarh, Jharkhand and Orissa have significantly added forest cover during last one decade.\u000a\u000aWe have asked the 13th finance commission to reward those states who have maintained and protected their green cover, he said. While Brazil and Indonesia have been asking for financial support for halting deforestation, we have in fact added significant forest cover during last one decade, Ramesh said.\u000a\u000aRecently, Brazil and Indonesia had submitted Reducing Emissions From Deforestation and Degradation (REDD) plan for consideration in Copenhagen summit, India has asked for REDD plus which seeks to financial incentives for afforestation programme.\u000a\u000aRamesh said Brazil and Indonesia have lost 2.1 million hectare of forest annually due to its exploitation for economic benefits. Deforestation contribute 20% of the total GHG emission. On the Chinas decision to increase forest cover by 40 million hectare by 2020, he said that there is a need to launch a massive programme for stepping up afforestation in degraded land.
