aVIndia should be able to lay its national action plan on climate change at the Copenhagen summit if a global emission reduction target is set, financial support is given to developing countries and clean technology transfer is facilitated, said IPCC chief Rajendra K Pachauri on Tuesday.\u000a\u000aHe said India cannot take on legally binding emission reduction targets. It is totally unacceptable because 400 million people in India don't have access to electricity even now.\u000a\u000aBut India would be under pressure because the US President Barack Obama has announced a provisional target of reducing emissions 17% by 2020 and China has committed that it would cut its emission intensity by at least 40% till 2020.\u000a\u000aReferring to Prime Minister Manmohan Singh's declaration that India would not exceed per capita emission of industrialised countries, he said India must at the same time work towards ensuring its energy security because fossil fuels won't last forever. The preferred choice for India, he said, is to harness solar energy.\u000a\u000aHe also called upon the Prime Minister to attend the climate change meet of government representatives, including the heads of state, from more than 190 countries. The 15th Conference of Parties is being organised by the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) in Copenhagen from December 7-18. The meet is to discuss the emission reduction of industrialised countries in the second phase of Kyoto Protocol after 2012.
