aVNEW DELHI: Mr Barack Obama, who is scheduled to make the most momentous event of his presidency \u2014 an increase in US troops to the country and an exit strategy \u2014 on Tuesday briefed Prime Minister Manmohan Singh about his Af-Pak policy. The US president also used the occasion to gauge New Delhi's mind on the Copenhagen climate deal.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt is understood that Mr Obama gave Mr Singh a preview of what he is going to announce in his Af Pak strategy. The telephonic conversation between the two leaders comes in the backdrop of a recent meeting between the two, where they covered most of the ground on Afghanistan.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a``The two leaders discussed the situation in Afghanistan and steps that could be taken to bring peace and stability in the country,'' said the prime minister's office in a statement.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aOfficials maintained that there was greater appreciation for India's role in Afghanistan and the call to Mr Singh is being seen as significant. India has been telling the US that it is important for regional and international players to put their weight behind the Afghan government. India is also looking at extending training and capacity building for Afghans.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAt present over 100,000 US and Nato troops are in Afghanistan and Mr Obama, according to reports, is expected to announce a surge of around 30,000 troops. A large part of Mr Obama's announcement is also expected to focus on the US relationship with Pakistan and the promise of a new renewed engagement in exchange for action on terror.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aEven though the conversation between Mr Singh and Mr Obama centred largely on Afghanistan, the reference to climate change in the telephonic conversation indicates the kind of pressure India is under ahead of Copenhagen. Mr Singh assured the US president that India would ``play a constructive role in the negotiations and looked forward to a successful outcome.''\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe Obama administration has put forward a target of reducing greenhouse gases by about 17% below 2005 levels in 2020 with the promise of further cuts. But in the wake of these announcements, the pressure has been increasing on India to take a deal making role.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe US is also expected to have a strong presence in Copenhagen to show its commitment to climate change and emission cuts. Mr Obama has already announced that he will attend the Copenhagen summit on December 9, a day before he accepts his Nobel Peace Prize in Norway.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aApart from Mr Obama, his administration will be present in batches for the duration of the conference. The White House had announced that a host of top administration officials would travel to Copenhagen. Interior secretary Ken Salazar, agriculture secretary Tom Vilsack commerce secretary Gary Locke and energy secretary Steven Chu, are just some of the heavyweights who are expected to attend the conference.
