aVIndia is likely to offer to slash its carbon intensity by 24% by 2020 and 37% by 2030 on a baseline of 2005, said environment ministry officials on Wednesday. Carbon intensity is defines as carbon dioxide emitted per unit of energy consumption.\u000a\u000aThe Indian offer follows China that last week announced plans to reduce carbon intensity by 40-45% on a baseline of 2005. The new offer will put India in a strong bargaining position at the Copenhagen climate meet that begins on Monday, as Indias carbon intensity is already low and on the same page as that of the least energy intensive developed countries.\u000a\u000aThe targets are, however, provisional and are not expected to be a part of internationally binding commitments. Indias new offer is likely to be tabled in Parliament during a special discussion on Indias position on climate change on Thursday, by environment and forests minister Jairam Ramesh.\u000a\u000aThe figures are based on the impact of implementing various missions under the National Action Plan on Climate Change. While the solar mission aims to generate 20,000 mw by 2022, the energy efficiency mission aims to cut 5% of the countrys annual energy consumption.\u000a\u000aIndia has been under increased pressure to make emission reduction commitments, particularly ever since the worlds biggest emitter China announced that it would reduce its carbon intensity and the second biggest emitter, the United States, announced that it would reduce its emissions by 17% by 2020 on a baseline of 2005.
