aVNEW DELHI: India on Thursday acquired the tag of a ''responsible'' global power in climate mitigation when it announced that it would reduce its carbon intensity levels by 20-25% on its 2005 levels over the next 11 years. But in the process, it has possibly taken a step that could restrict its economic options in the future.The announcement was made, as anticipated, by Union environment and forest minister Jairam Ramesh in the Lok Sabha before a gathering of large number of MPs who, cutting across party lines, not only recognised that global warming was a serious threat to the planet, but also armed the government with flexibility in the climate negotiations that kick off in Copenhagen on December 7, which will climax with a global summit on December 18.Ramesh, who gave credit to the Planning Commission for undertaking the homework to come up with the number, said that the 20-25% reduction in carbon intensity was not legally binding but was within the realm of possibility. He pointed out that the country had already achieved 17.6% reduction in carbon intensity between 1990-2005. He said the Commission was confident that the target could be met and it would be part of the Low Carbon Growth plan being embedded in the 12th Five-Year Plan.An announcement of a unilateral climate mitigation measure was anticipated soon after China announced that it would clip its carbon intensity by 40-45%, but still most experts had expected a similar reduction measure in energy intensity, not carbon intensity.While ''energy intensity'' connotes the amount of energy used to generate every rupee of national income, ''carbon intensity'' measures the amount of carbon emitted for every rupee generated. While the two normally track a similar graph, the rub lies in that there are certain changes in the economy that would save energy costs but emit more carbon \u2014 like shifting from burning wood or grass for domesticfuel to kerosene or cooking gas.
