aVDoing its bit to force a successful and meaningful outcome at the Copenhagen climate change summit beginning next week, India today offered to effect at least a 20 per cent cut in its carbon intensity by 2020 over 2005 levels, hoping this would satisfy demands from developed countries for some sort of quantified commitments.\u000a\u000aUnion Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh told Parliament today that India would reduce its carbon intensity by a minimum of 20 per cent and "most likely 25 per cent" by the year 2020, a target that is quite conservative considering the trend observed in carbon intensity over the last two decades.\u000a\u000aRamesh added that India would do "more," if there was a "satisfactory and equitable" agreement in Copenhagen.\u000a\u000aCarbon intensity is the amount of carbon dioxide emitted per unit of GDP. A reduction in carbon intensity means a country is able to achieve higher levels of GDP without a corresponding increase in carbon dioxide emissions, therefore saving on some carbon emissions.\u000a\u000aWith today's decision, India has followed in the footsteps of China which had, a few days earlier, announced its decision to make 40-45 per cent cuts in its carbon intensity by the year 2020 compared to 2005 levels.\u000a\u000aChina and India are the world's biggest and fifth largest emitters of greenhouse gases respectively and the only developing countries in the top five. Neither of them is obliged to make reductions in its absolute emissions under the Kyoto Protocol. Only developed countries are obligated to do so.\u000a\u000aNew Delhi's announcement means that now the world's top five emitters have all announced some sort of quantitative targets for 2020  absolute emission cuts in the case of the United States, European Union and Russia, and carbon intensity reductions in case of India and China  raising the hopes for a comprehensive agreement at Copenhagen.\u000a\u000aRamesh said New Delhi's decision to make targeted reductions in carbon intensity was essential for India to stake claim for global leadership on climate change and take a moral high ground.\u000a\u000a"We could, of course, have chosen not to do anything and remained like the proverbial frog in the well. But the world would have laughed at us," he said.\u000a\u000a"More than the international community, we have to show action to our own people  to those living in the Sunderbans, in the northeast, in the Himalayas  that the government was serious about tackling climate change," he said.\u000a\u000aRamesh said the figure of 20-25 per cent was arrived at after consultations with the Planning Commission which has been making mid-term appraisal of the Eleventh Five Year plan. He said the Planning Commission was already preparing a low-carbon growth path for India for the next Plan period.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Two officials stoned, axed, Andhra forest department waits for arms\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
