aV\u201cThere is no question of India accepting a legally binding emission reduction cut.''\u000a\u000aOur Bureau\u000a\u000aNew Delhi, Dec. 3\u000a\u000aIndia has announced its willingness to cut its carbon intensity, or the amount of carbon dioxide emitted for every unit of GDP, by between 20 and 25 per cent by 2020 compared with 2005 levels, the Environment Minister, Mr Jairam Ramesh, said on Thursday.\u000a\u000a\u201cThis we will do regardless of what emerges in Copenhagen\u2026 If we have a successful, equitable agreement (at Copenhagen), we are prepared to do more,\u201d Mr Ramesh said in the Lok Sabha, laying out India's position ahead of the Copenhagen global climate talks later this month.\u000a\u000aLegally Binding\u000a\u000aThe proposed cuts would not be legally binding, he said in his reply to a four-hour debate on the issue of climate change and the position India will take at the December 8-18 global summit.\u000a\u000aMr Ramesh reiterated that India will not accept a legally binding emission cut, or a peak year of carbon emissions at the global climate talks in Copenhagen. \u201cThere is no question of India accepting a legally binding emission reduction cut,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aHe said while India could accept international verification of reductions if supported by international financing and technology transfers, \u201cwhen mitigation action is unsupported, we will not want it to be subject to the same kind of scrutiny.\u201d\u000a\u000aHe said: \u201cThere are attempts by some countries that developing countries should announce when their emissions will peak\u2026 We will not sign a peaking year agreement. This is not acceptable.\u201d\u000a\u000aAlternative Model\u000a\u000aThe Minister, however, added that the time has come for India to negotiate from a position of strength and to demonstrate an alternative model of growth.\u000a\u000aTo ensure generational representation, the Minister said he would be taking two school and two college students to Copenhagen as part of the official Indian delegation. \u201cThis will convey India's seriousness in doing something for the future generations,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 4, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
