aVThe debate over climate change in the Lok Sabha on Thursday enlisted enthusiastic participation from younger MPs with most of them supporting the government's stand on the issue while a few, like Jayant Chaudhary and Jyoti Mirdha, struck a slightly discordant note by suggesting that the country wasn't doing enough.\u000a\u000aCongress's Mirdha expressed the opinion that India should also take emission cuts like the developed countries, something that is completely against conventional wisdom in the country. Her argument was that India cannot be entering into a competition with developed countries over who emits more. "If the United States has emitted large amounts of greenhouse gases in the past, that is no reason for us also to emit more," she said.\u000a\u000aShe said India's growing GDP might make it a developed country one day, but if nothing is done to rein in global emissions, there would be very little left to eat or drink. Objecting to large dams, especially in Himalayan states, Mirdha said it was a mistake to consider water a renewable source of energy. She said it was common knowledge that large dams upstream lead to floods midstream and droughts in the plains.\u000a\u000aChaudhary of RLD said the argument that since India had not contributed to global warming in a significant way and therefore we should not be reducing emissions was "moronic". "I feel we are still in the denial mode while climate change is fast becoming the most serious problem that the world faces. We are already losing a lot. It is about how much we will lose if we don't act now," he said.\u000a\u000aEarlier, initiating the debate, veteran BJP leader Murli Manohar Joshi said India should take the leadership role of the developing and deprived world and not stoop down before the dictates of the rich countries. He said the western model of development and excessive consumerism was destructive and urged the government to look for an alternative sustainable development pathway. "India must not compromise on poverty reduction goals by succumbing to take forced and internationally binding emission cuts," he said, adding that India needed to be flexible but "firm".\u000a\u000aSandeep Dikshit of the Congress said the western model was not totally flawed. "If they are the biggest culprits on climate change, they also have developed technologies to tackle its effects," he said, adding that India needed to work in close cooperation with them to access those technologies.\u000a\u000aSupriya Sule of the NCP wanted to know about the role of the states in government's action plan to deal with climate change. She also sought to know as to how the government planned to drive a low-carbon economy.\u000a\u000aCPM's M B Rajesh advocated a tough approach by the government and said there was no need for flexibility. He held developed countries completely responsible for the climate mess.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Narendra Modi a monster, Trinamool has pact with him: Buddha\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
