aVIndia is the world's fourth largest market for wind power and estimates are its green spending could touch $150 billion by 2017.\u000a\u000aLondon is a global hub for finance and capital raising, and international investors are ready to use their funds to help India build a global low-carbon economy.\u000a\u000aNick Anstee\u000a\u000aNext week the world will be watching the European city of Copenhagen as policy-makers from across the globe gather for the United Nations Climate Change Conference. They are faced with a huge challenge \u2014 to reach agreement on the successor to the Kyoto treaty and ultimately a consensus on how the world should tackle global warming.\u000a\u000aIf the Copenhagen summit is to be a worthy successor to Kyoto it is essential that there is a clear and strong signal from policy-makers that they commit to deeper cuts in greenhouse gas emissions targets and that these will be enforced robustly.\u000a\u000aHowever, the necessary commitment of policy-makers is only half the story. I believe that is it only by leveraging private sector capital and unleashing the power of the markets to boost investment in green technology and pollution reducing projects that the challenges of climate change can be met.\u000a\u000aPost-carbon economy\u000a\u000aIndia is very well placed to be at the forefront of this drive to harness private sector expertise and build the world's post-carbon economy. It has great potential for technological developments which will enable your citizens to leap-frog the wasteful development model of the West. There are a wide range of choices for the future and these choices could bring huge opportunities for businesses. But we are not there yet \u2014 in order for these opportunities to be realised, a number of steps must be taken and agreed internationally.\u000a\u000aFirst, global policy-makers must establish a clear and consistent regulatory environment around all aspects of climate change mitigation and in areas such as the carbon market. Before investors part with their cash for clean technologies such as renewable energy they must be confident they are basing investment decisions within a secure regulatory framework. The cost of capital is related to risk and politicians must make it a priority to minimise risk for investors by creating policy stability.\u000a\u000aSecond, as well as developing exciting new technological solutions to tackle climate change, we must also examine how we can use expertise in the financial markets to create new opportunities. Innovation must be encouraged not just in terms of technology, but also in the field of financing techniques.\u000a\u000aI know that in the post credit crunch world policy-makers view innovation with suspicion, but in the field of climate change financing, it should be encouraged within the secure framework I described above. Indeed I believe the financial sector needs to be just as innovative as the scientists and engineers that are seeking a physical solution to global warming.\u000a\u000aThis is an area where I believe the City of London can work closely in partnership with India by linking your drive and entrepreneurial flair with our expertise as a financial innovator and as a centre for carbon financing: London is a global hub for finance and capital raising, and international investors are ready and waiting to use their funds to help India build a global low-carbon economy.\u000a\u000aOff to a good start\u000a\u000aThird, reform of the Clean Development Mechanism should also be addressed so that bottlenecks, long waits, uncertainty for certified emission reduction credits can be minimised while maintaining transparency and rigorous scientific standards.\u000a\u000aOf course, there is much work to be done, but India in particular is off to a good start. For investors seeking out growth opportunities the investment landscape is promising \u2014 it is the world's fourth largest market for wind power and estimates suggest that green spending in India could reach up to $150 billion by 2017. Bio-fuels, clean coal and wind are likely to present significant investment opportunities in the future.\u000a\u000aI truly hope that agreements are reached in Copenhagen which will promote our shared values of fair-play and innovation. I also hope that these agreements will encourage companies to play their vitally important role in tackling these issues. It is clear that a fundamental change to the way we consume and do business is needed to stave off the worst aspects of climate change and this should not be seen as a constraint but an opportunity to build a better, cleaner world.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 4, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
