aVNEW DELHI: The Copenhagen papers submitted by the BASIC countries \u2014 Brazil, South Africa, India and China \u2014 have outlined the redlines and the wishlist. In what could restrict the elbow room for the developed world in the Copenhagen dialogue, the BASIC countries have said the process of negotiations has to be carried on within the parameters of the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC), Kyoto Protocol and the Bali Action Plan. Some developed countries like the US have been pushing for an "alternative" agreement, which for all practical purposes does away with the Kyoto Protocol. On this count, the four-nation draft makes it amply clear that the UNFCCC is the "fundamental legal framework for the global fight against climate change". It has reiterated that all climate-change action would have to conform to the principle of equity and common-but-differentiated responsibilities. The draft also makes it clear that the four countries do not expect a legally binding agreement to be agreed upon in Copenhagen. It sets a date of June 2010 by which an agreement should be arrived at. Complete adherence to the UNFCCC, Kyoto Protocol and Bali Action Plan is also enunciated in the manner in which these countries want the post-Copenhagen negotiations to be carried out. It suggests these negotiations should be in line with the mandate of the Bali Action Plan. It has also reiterated the developing countries' position of allowing monitoring, reporting and verification for climate-change actions only for those supported and enabled by the developed countries. As for measures undertaken domestically, the draft not only rejects verification, but instead suggests that the developing countries will undertake "auditing, supervision and assessment" of these efforts on their own. The results of this exercise will be publicly available.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe wishlist of the BASIC countries includes their opposition to climate change becoming an instrument for creating trade barriers. The draft states no levy or no-tariff measures can be imposed on goods and services as part of measures to combat climate change. The move is a counter to proposals by countries like France and the US to impose a levy on countries that do not take on globally binding emission targets.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt is now becoming clear that an outcome at Copenhagen may not be possible. The BASIC draft calls for recording the progress made in the negotiations. Developing countries like India have argued that while there is no agreement on the architecture issues, substantial progress has been made on details, including vexatious ones like finance and technology. There is no final agreement in these areas, but progress has been made. The paper calls for "capturing the progress" made till now.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn keeping with the submissions made by the G-77, the draft has called for institutional arrangements for technology development and transfer and a Global Climate Fund to oversee and channelise the financing for mitigation, adaptation, technology transfer and capacity building. In a concession, the draft recognises that carbon markets are part of the financing arrangements and, therefore, accepts that private funding will play a role. Developed countries have been pushing for funding under the UNFCCC to include both public and private funds.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt has also suggested setting up of a subsidiary body for adaptation "to administer and promote international cooperation on adaptation and relative relevant activities under the Convention, including the formulation of a comprehensive international programme for adaptation."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt also provides an interesting counter to proposals by developed countries for an alternative agreement to include the US, for whom Kyoto is a dirty word. The Copenhagen Accord has put in a clause to include the US. "For any Annex I Party to the Convention that is not a Party to the Kyoto Protocol, its emission reduction commitments shall be comparable to the target referred to (for Annexe I parties). Such commitment shall be reflected in a national schedule."
