aVOur Bureau\u000a\u000aNew Delhi, Dec. 4\u000a\u000aThe Bharatiya Janata Party has come out strongly against the Government stand on carbon emission intensity cuts, terming the announcement of \u201cunilateral cuts\u201d as a \u201cweakening of India's negotiating position\u201d at the global platform.\u000a\u000a\u201cIt is bad strategy on the eve of any multilateral negotiations to announce unilateral stance without waiting for the approach of the developed countries. It is India's experience in various multilateral negotiations including the World Trade Organisation that unilateral concessions announced before the multilateral dialogue become the starting point in India's negotiations,\u201d Mr Arun Jaitley, Leader of the Opposition in the Rajya Sabha, said on Friday.\u000a\u000aThe statement comes a day after the Minister for Environment, Mr Jairam Ramesh, announced a 20-25 per cent cut in carbon emission intensity as a \u201cvoluntary\u201d measure on India's part in the run-up to the UN climate change summit which begins next week in Copenhagen.\u000a\u000aThe BJP also said that the Minister's announcement was a \u201cserious departure\u201d from the Government's earlier stand that it will not accept any \u201clegally binding commitment to reduce overall emissions as also emission intensity.\u201d\u000a\u000aAccording to the party, the Government has moved away from its stated stance of \u201cequal per capita principle.\u201d\u000a\u000aThe main Opposition party has come down heavily against the Environment Minister for \u201crubbishing\u201d India's earlier approach as `do nothing'. \u201cThe (Minister's) argument\u2026 makes a mockery of the programmes undertaken by successive governments with regard to environment protection. The Minister ought not rubbish a consistent stand taken by various governments.\u000a\u000aThe Minister obviously overlooked the fact that this \u2018do nothing' approach has led to reduction in emission intensity by 17.65 per cent during 1990-2005,\u201d the statement adds.\u000a\u000aSeeking an explanation on what would constitute an \u201cequitable\u201d global agreement, the BJP asked whether the Government was going to resist any attempt to \u201cdilute /undermine/replace\u201d the Kyoto Protocol and insist on continuation of legally binding emission reduction by developed countries under the Kyoto Protocol.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 5, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
