aVHimalayan-Tibetan glaciers is the Earths third largest ice mass. The combo impact of global warming and short-lived pollutants are causing a decrease in ice-cover area. The glaciers are undergoing exceptional retreat, though the response time of glacial retreat differs by locations and governed by major weather systems like south west monsoon in eastern Himalayas and westerly jet streams in the Karakoram and western Himalayas. Scientists have projected a 43% decrease in glacial area on average by the year 2070, and 75% decrease by the end of 21st century at the current exponential warming rate. If that happens, it will have far-reaching effect on the hydrological processes in the Himalayan-Tibetan region. Recently, more and more scientists come to recognise by modelling the satellite data the impact of short-lived black carbon (BC) or soot on glacial melting.\u000a\u000aSouth Asia and southeast Asia is a global hotspot for BC or soot after long-lived green house gases. BC emissions originate from bio-mass burning, diesel engines and coal fired cement plants. Using unmanned aircraft, Professor Ramanathan, University of California, San Diego, measured the amount of sunlight absorbed by black carbon, and found that it contributes as much as 50% of the solar heating of the air. It is the second largest contributor to atmospheric warming in the region, after carbon dioxide, he says. He estimates that the combined effect of BC and GHG may be sufficient to account for a warming trend of 0.250C per decade in the Himalaya-Tibetan region.\u000a\u000aGlaciers in the southern and central part of Himalaya are expected to be sensitive to atmospheric warming, due to their summer-accumulation type. An increase in summer air temperature not only enhances ice melt but also significantly reduces the accumulation by altering snowfall to rain. Under present conditions, the glacier variations south of the Himalayan main ridge are believed to reflect monsoon dynamics. Glacier retreat shows a north-south gradient with larger retreat rates in the south as the influence of the monsoon decreases towards the north. The northbound glacier tongues in Kashmir and Zanskar valleys show speeds of several tens to over 200 m year-1. They are almost debris free as the ice flux drain the large accumulation areas through the north bound valleys, in order to keep the glacier in geometric equilibrium. These glaciers dynamically adjust to climate variations and thus respond by retreat to atmospheric warming than local decay. In contrast the southern flowing glaciers in Sikkim, Nepal and Bhutan have high debris cover and velocity around 40 m y-1 near the tongues, which appear to be nearly stagnant. The response to atmospheric warming for these glacier tongues is downwasting-essentially decoupled from the dynamics of upper glacier parts.\u000a\u000aThe larger warming trend at higher altitudes has two fold impacts on the mass balance of the glaciers. First, warmer temperatures lead to enhanced melting. Second, they are shifting and weakening SW monsoon and westerly jet streams. This abnormality has led to more liquid precipitation on eastern Himalayas and early spring snow dumping on western Himalayas which melt out quickly because of soot presence in the atmosphere of high altitude regions. It is well known that GHG forcing leads to a warming of the atmosphere as well as surface warming. However, the influence of soot on atmospheric warming and reducing the snow and glacier albedo is being recognised by field studies conducted in the glacierised valleys of Himalaya-Tibetan region.\u000a\u000aTERI has established measurements of glacier mass balance, meteorology, surface radiation, and stream flow measurements at four benchmark glaciers in the eastern, central and western Indian Himalayas. The easternmost glaciers are strongly influenced by the summer monsoon season. The western most glaciers are less impacted by the monsoon and depend more on mid-latitude winter jet streams for accumulation and summer radiation inputs for melt. The meteorological and radiation measurements at these glaciers will be used to drive glacier melt calculations, which can be directly validated against the in-situ mass balance measurements also being made at these glaciers.\u000a\u000aIn April and July 2009 TERI has installed Aetholometer at E Rathong Glacier, Sikkim (4,700 m asl), and Kolahoi Glacier, western Himalaya (4,000 m asl) and measured the ambient BC aerosol in the atmosphere. Measured mass concentrations of BC integrated with time. The values obtained ranges between two to three microgram per cubic meter. The likely source of abnormally high concentration of BC or soot in high altitude regions is from the adulterated diesel used by the transport sector and large number of cement plants in the Himalayan states. In the summer of 2010, we will install ultraviolet and visible radiometer to measure spectral radiance to characterise the spectral signal of absorption by dust and soot on snow and ice surfaces. The focus of TERIs studies on glaciers is to understand the processes and drivers of melt-rate. As the policy makers in our country needs to know the regional picture for water resources management and they are not concerned whether some glacier is advancing or stationary or shrinking. There are various reasons that cause these changes, but the issue is too underrated at regional level. This initiative would help in creating credible quantitative database on major climate regions across the Himalayas. The hydrology and mass balance modelling with IPCC scenarios will give future projections on the water resources availability from the Himalayan-Tibetan region.\u000a\u000aThe writer is Head, Glaciology Division, TERI
