aVIndia, the fourth largest global economy has seen tremendous growth in the last decade. The rapid growth in economic activity and population has led to a significant demand in the transport sector particularly in urban India. According to a recent industry estimate, by 2020 Indias population in urban cities is expected to grow five-fold from where it is today and reach a staggering 200 million.\u000a\u000aIn this scenario, the future of fossil fuel technology is becoming progressively bleak with inflation in oil prices, depleting oil reserves, geo-political issues and the rising operating costs of manufacturing conventional vehicles. Increasing pressure is being imposed on the automobile industry by environmental groups to look at alternative non-polluting options.\u000a\u000aThe positive shift from an auto industry perspective is that today one is witness the advent of alternative technologies introduced by auto giants to counteract problems of carbon emissions introduced in the atmosphere via conventional transport and commuting options available. Auto manufacturers are investing significant time and resources in developing alternate technologies that include vehicles, which are powered by CNG and LPG, Hybrids, hydrogen fuel cells and electric vehicles (EV). However, upon evaluating all these technologies the EV ranks on top and is the hottest topic in auto circles as they have zero emission, are easy to handle, and have low maintenance costs when compared with the conventional internal combustion engine models. The EVs today are perceived as a catalyst in mitigating environmental concerns. It is considered green with greater user acceptance and increased consumer demand for electric modes of commute demonstrated in real market time.\u000a\u000aFrom a climate change point of view at a macro level, India is taking positive steps to effectively address the imminent dangers from greenhouse gas emissions via implementation of the National Action Plan on Climate Change (NAPCC) agreement. It is heartening to note India is cognizant to issues of climate change and global warming is considered on a serious note prompting action from the government, consumers and auto manufacturers alike. The major activities which are causing the greenhouse effectthe use of fossil fuels in the generation of energy (37.5%), transport (17.3%), industrial processes (22.2%) and agriculture (7.8%), provide the essential foundation of todays world economy. Such high emitting practices must be replaced by new sustainable sources of energy. Delaying action will only increase economic costs and physical damage from climate change in the long run.\u000a\u000aThus, effective ways of generating, distributing and using energy must be developed and applied at scale. The world must assess the relative merits of different transportable and non-transportable energy sources: cleaner coal, gas, nuclear, wind, solar, wave and tidal and geothermal energy. New ways of fuelling cars and other forms of transport must be developed and applied including the use of hydrogen fuel cells, sustainable biofuels, and electric engines. In this regard, European government has taken action to encourage adoption of EVs by imposing congestion charges on fossil fuel cars, providing free parking and funding EV infrastructure. In the US, Obamas administration has given ample emphasis on promoting EVs. China has the largest population of EVs and the government is taking steps to make EVs easier to adopt locally. India has also reportedly offered to cut energy intensity by 20-25%. However, though the Indian government is encouraging the use of alternate energy sources in pockets only, a greater consistency in policy is required to elicit positive envi- ronmental changes over a period of time.\u000a\u000aIn the said context, the forthcoming Copenhagen Climate Summit is a relevant platform for arriving at a global agreement to stop climate related chaos.\u000a\u000aWhile in the process of debating commitment to legally binding emission cuts internationally, India needs to take proactive steps at a domestic level first to tackle climate change. Talking specifically about the impact on climate change arising from transport sector emissions, the changes that needs to be implemented include:\u000a\u000a1. A rigorous public education programme to be put in place as a first step about methods and solutions to clean the environment and the roles that individual citizens at a domestic level can play.\u000a\u000a2. The government should encourage the auto industry, utilities and renewable energy companies to collaborate in order to fast forward the development of cleaner electricity solutions. As we clean the grid, we create a cleaner environment for all of us to live in and enjoy.\u000a\u000a3. Government should encourage incentivising purchase of electric cars as well as introduce reduced tariffs on energy consumption during off peak times (overnight when EVs can be charged). This will reduce the dependency on our oil imports and fast depleting fossil fuels.\u000a\u000a4. The government should create incentives for the purchase and installation of battery charging points at the workplace, at home and in public places such as shopping malls, parks etc. This coupled with solar energy harvesting will make India the leader in emission free mobility solution.\u000a\u000a5. The government should shift the burden of taxation from non-polluting to polluting vehicles. Levy a revenue neutral regionally collected tax on petrol and diesel in order to create a fund to subsidise the purchase of non-polluting vehicles.\u000a\u000a6. The government should mandate all auto manufacturers to transition to sales of non-polluting cars by setting clear annual incremental goals10% by 2012 and 50% by 2020 etc.\u000a\u000aTo summarise, I would like to say, the world can no longer afford conventional cars. There are 800 million cars in the world today, a number that is growing on a daily basis and is unsustainable. We are now very close to the point of no return, environmentally. It is time we change the way we think about cars and truly understand the threat arising from carbon emitting cars to our every day existence. Todays consumer can still commute every day on the same roads, at the same speed and within the same time. The only choice they have to make is whetherto do so in a polluting way, thereby threatening the future of our childrenor to do it by adopting green autoand spell out a different ending.\u000a\u000aFor, climate change issues needs to be addressed as much at a local level first as it needs to be addressed at a global level.\u000a\u000aThe writer is Deputy Chairman and CTO Reva Electric Car Company
