aVMany people have been introduced to climate change through the concept of carbon markets. A new shift in the liberal economic paradigm towards a novel form of market mechanism, built on the cost of environmental integrity of the planet. Now why would I be so against the entire concept of market mechanism when the entire world wants a bigger carbon market to prevail\u000a\u000aThe concept of using market mechanisms to mitigate climate change was introduced in the climate negotiations at the last moment to provide flexibility in action. This flexibility resulted in the coming up of new concepts such as clean development mechanism or the emission trading scheme in Europe. Currently the entire concept of carbon market is premised on cost effectiveness of mitigation action. An industrialised country, which has an obligation under Kyoto Protocol to reduce its emission in the name of cost effectiveness invests in a developing country for a particular project. The resultant abatement of emissions in the developing country is counted towards the reduction commitments of the industrialised country.\u000a\u000aRather than using market mechanisms to help in much more robust mitigation, carbon markets have contributed in promoting false solutions, which do not really have an effect on the emissions but rather results in a net increase in the emissions of the world. Also these sorts of mechanisms have created perverse incentives in developing countries to not really come up with policies, which can result in substantial reduction in emissions. Rather, the corporate sector in developing countries is using such market mechanisms to hide behind and shirk investments from their own coffers in reducing their emissions.\u000a\u000aNow with the international negotiations looking at amending the Kyoto Protocol for the next phase and also looking at getting more developing country involvement in the mitigation, the future carbon market regime too will change. There is a need for serious regulation of the carbon market in view of the current developments in the negotiations which stem from weak targets from industrialised countries.\u000a\u000aThe current emission cut targets of industrialised countries, range from 10-17% on aggregate, which are extremely low. Added to this is a huge component of offsetting and market mechanisms. The proposed cuts can be undertaken by the developed countries domestically without the need for other mechanisms. The need for offsetting would be too low while developing countries would be able to generate a lot of emissions reductions for industrialised country consumption. This would only result in a saturation of the market, and leading to a very basic problem of the market, which is over supply and low demand, resulting in very low price of carbon. This low price would not only reduce the profit margins in developing countries but would also give away the low cost mitigation options that developing countries currently have, such as efficiency measures. This would lead to a collapse of the carbon market itself.\u000a\u000aThe market mechanism, right now is being viewed as a substitute for providing public finance to developing countries, which is another obligation of the industrialised world. Any market mechanism that comes into play should ensure that carbon markets do not act as a substitute for the financial obligation that industrialised countries have. According to a recent report by Project Catalyst, It is important to note that the role of private sector carbon markets will be significantly smaller than most people expect. The report finds that even with developed country targets of 25% below 1990 levels (which is significantly more stringent than current proposals), private sector carbon markets would contribute only 10-15 billion euros annually in 2010-2020. With current proposals, the carbon market finance would translate only to 3 billion euro annually. This is only a small percentage of the overall finance needed for mitigation. We know for a fact that markets tend to percolate into only the least cost-high profit projects and under the negotiations, public finance from industrialised countries is to be used for high-cost mitigation action in developing countries. If the markets act as a substitute for public finance, developing countries like India would have to take on high-cost mitigation actions on its own where the brunt of the cost would be passed on to the same companies, which right now are investing heavily to come up with the offsetting projects.\u000a\u000aA 2012 market regime should ensure that as countries start to have their very own carbon market, the rules across the board are the same for everyone. Take the example of the legal framework that every country follows. Every country in the world reprimands its citizens on similar crimes, just as a murder in every country amounts to a heinous crime, which is reprimanded regardless of what country one lives in. Or you could take the example of the stock market. Every country has its own national stock market but the larger principle on which the market operates is same. So should be the case for the carbon market too. If basic rules in various markets are different it would only result in isolation of that market. To have interaction between two carbon markets, rules such as, what constitutes a reduction, need to be same otherwise the markets would be unable to interact with each other. Finally, it is in the interest of private sector that carbon markets operate in a way that they are able to compare apples to apples, and that there are no rotten apples entering the system, jeopardising the integrity, and distorting the price signal of the markets.\u000a\u000aNow, what can we do in India and how a new market mechanism would come into play. Currently, a significant portion of the credits generated by the existing Clean Development Mechanism (CDM) are non-additional. In other words, credits are generated for emission reduction activities that would have taken place regardless of CDM being present. These credits are then used to allow higher emissions in industrialised countries. As a result more emissions have been emitted globally than would have been without the CDM. Money that could have been spent on renewable energy investments in developed countries or on truly effective low-carbon projects in developing countries has been wasted.\u000a\u000aProject-based CDM needs to be gradually limited to Least Developed Countries only, while new mechanisms could be phased in for more advanced countries like India. This would mean sectoral crediting mechanisms (SCM)this could also include programmatic CDMand sectoral trading (ST). Under a SCM, countries would receive credits at the end of a trading period for emissions reductions below a pre-established (no-lose) target line. Under ST, countries would receive emissions permits up-front, equivalent to a (unilateral) sectoral target. Beating this sectoral target would allow countries to sell excess emissions permits; failure to meet it would necessitate buying up the shortfall of permits on the international market.\u000a\u000aUnder sectoral mechanisms, establishing a sufficiently ambitious threshold for crediting or trading will not be easy, as business as usual predictions are always more or less arbitrary and baseline data may be of poor quality. Indeed, this was the experience with the EUs cap and trade system, which saw massive over-allocation of emission permits in the first trading period leading to a dramatic crash in the carbon price and little or no reduction in emissions. This points to the need for a cautious approach in any transition towards new sectoral carbon market mechanisms, including a pilot period during which precautionary measures should be implemented to ensure environmental integrity of the system and guard against over-allocation. One such measure could be discounting of emission permits either at the supply or demand sidethis would mean that more emission reduction tons are delivered for each emission credit unit used to offset industrialised country emissions. This would also increase carbon market financing for developing countries.\u000a\u000aIn the end, a carbon market is not your traditional market, which works on the principle of profit making. It is a mechanism to cost-effectively ensure that the world takes up a low or zero carbon emission pathway. The carbon market concept is to create conditions to ensure that carbon as a commodity becomes so expensive that using this commodity would be antagonistic to profits and in the end, carbon as a commodity becomes non-existent. Eventually, a market without a product. This is the principle to remember when we talk carbon markets.\u000a\u000aThe writer is Climate & Energy Policy Adviser, Greenpeace India
