aVFrom the invention of the steam engine that spawned the industrial revolution and initiated the process of climate change, technology has today come to be at the forefront of the race against climate change. Invention, production and use of new green technologies that can wean us off the same fossil-fuel based steam engine from two centuries ago remains our best hope.\u000a\u000aInvention of environmentally-sound technologies by using renewable or non-emitting alternate energy sources alone cannot be the solution. Technologies must also be cheap enough to be accessible to citizens and businesses in poorer countries. Discussion on technology transfer and financing support from rich to poor nations is thus at the centre of the post 2012 international climate framework.\u000a\u000aCurrent estimates suggest that developing countries may require $100$200 billion annually to respond to climate change. Available offers of financing are woefully short: at the Commonwealth Summit in Trinidad earlier this month, for instance, Gordon Brown proposed a $10 billion fund to help developing countries deal with climate change. It is easy to be lulled into believing that the emerging prospects for environmentally sound technologies will provide developing countries the pathway to progress. Many argue that countries like India can take the lead in developing new green technologies. The realities are different and much harsher than what such hopeful rhetoric offers. Developing countries lack the comprehensive technical capability and infrastructure to immediately stimulate the development of new technologies even if appropriate policies or economic incentives are in place. While richer countries are drivers of invention and innovation, poorer nations rely primarily on commercialised technologies developed elsewhere.\u000a\u000aUsing technology transfer and financing support that is likely to become available through an international climate agreement, developing countries must put in place strategies that can deploy commercialised green technologies as an immediate strategy. For developing countries, diffusion of existing technologies represents the best short-term transfer gateways and offers the co-benefit of enhancing technical capacity for innovation in the longer term.\u000a\u000aIndian businesses must rapidly re-orient to position themselves for the emerging opportunities from technology transfer and the transition to a low carbon economy. The Bureau of Energy Efficiency implementing the Nation Mission on Enhanced Energy Efficiency under Indias National Action Plan on Climate Change is in the process of implementing several initiatives that could result in the creation of a domestic energy efficiency market worth $10 - $15 billion annually. Indias recent announcement on its willingness to commit to energy intensityenergy used per unit of GDPreductions of 20-25% over the next decade could further expand the potential market size. The forthcoming Indian energy efficiency market will not only be large but will have something in it for everybody. Domestic energy efficiency initiatives will create numerous gateways for reaching small and medium enterprises, promote innovative financing models, generate new investments and enhance corporate transparency through better reporting and standards.\u000a\u000aMany of the strategic business decisions on clean technology adoption will no doubt be guided by economic incentives and regulatory imperatives. And in making these decisions business must be guided by a value system that allows them to take account of the environmental impact of their economic activities. Whatever their choice and the resulting regulatory framework, businesses that have the organisational and management capa- bilities to understand and manage the environmental impact of their economic activities are the only ones likely to benefit.\u000a\u000aTechnology transfer and financing support are only part of the solutions. Introducing a value system isnt about just greening your businessit is about ensuring that your business survives the future.\u000a\u000aThe writer is MD, ICF International (India)
