aVRising waters and sinking boats produce evocative metaphors for humanitys problems with climate change. Here is one: a boat, sinking at one end, the other end up in the sky. In the water, people are scrambling for life-vests. On the other side, high and dry, two men raise wine glasses saying, Thank God, the hole in the boat is not on our side. However, they would sink too as there are no baffles within the boat to keep the water from them. So it is with the climate change, unlike poverty. The rich can live with poverty on the other side of the world. But climate change knows no national boundaries, it would affect everyone. This, people everywhere have realised. The question is what must they do to save themselves\u000a\u000aPlan A is to get their governments to come up with the solution. When things are going well, we want less of government. But when things are going wrong, we want our government to save us. That is what we have governments for. And since the solution to climate change must involve all people, all our governments must agree. The problem is, as an American environmentalist said at an international conference, that there are too many people on earth now for nature to support if they all lived in the way Americans live. Yet all aspire to live that way-it is the goal of their development. Nature, he pointed out, has a way of reducing the numbers of the species it cannot support. Therefore, populations will be reduced by floods and famines-it is natures way of adjusting. The boat, he calculated, can support only one billion passengers living in the American life-style. The rest will be thrown off. It is the job of every government to ensure that its people have a place on the boat and do not get thrown off as the boat begins to sink with their weight. Therefore negotiations among governments must be about economic interests and complicated issues of equity-much more contentious than those in the spluttering Doha Round of trade negotiations. Thus, from Kyoto to Copenhagen, through Bali and other places, our governments have been meeting to agree and soon disagree.\u000a\u000aPlan B is to ask objective scientists and economists to come up with the solution, rather than politicians who must be sensitive to the demands of their own constituencies, and hence subjective. This is turning out to be very complicated too. Global warming with carbon in the air is only one facet of a much larger environmental problem on the ground that is hurting many people already. At the same international conference, a woman from Ghana watching a video of a polar bear on a dwindling iceberg, shown to all to wake them up to the affects of climate change, said, If our fear is changing patterns of water distribution on earth, my people are suffering it right now! Our farmers do not have water to grow crops. The inter-linkages between the facets of our complex environmental system are not yet completely understood by scientists. Therefore, Michael Spence, Nobel Laureate economist and leader of the UN Commission on Growth and Development, cautions against rushing to set targets, which governments are expected to, in Copenhagen. Targets would compel action by governments and business, and actions would backfire with unintended consequences if the linkages within the system are not understood, as happened in the rush to use bio-fuels in the US that contributed to a global food crisis. People in many countries need food and water today. The affects of temperature rise are expected to become serious after another 30 to 40 years perhaps.\u000a\u000aPlan A and Plan B would not work without Plan C, which is action by citizens. Life-style changes would be required, mostly by those who are consuming more than their fair share of environmental resources, including space in the atmosphere for carbon emissions. They must make space on the boat for others. What are they willing to changeswitch off phone chargers, use public transport, fly less, or as Paul McCartney and Pachauri suggesteat less meat The earth has enough for everyones needs, but not everyones greed, Mahatma Gandhi said. But when does greed convert to need If the job citizens assign their governments is to ensure that all their needs are met, and the job of scientists and industry is to produce what we need, then governments, scientists and industry must deliver what we want.\u000a\u000aWhen the waters rose, God commanded Noah to find space for all species on his ark. Change requires leadership. Leaders do not merely warn us of dangers to avoid. They inspire us, like Gandhi did, with tangible visions of the world we want to live in. A world that well help shape via our actions and support to the leaders who lead us. Those visions then set the agendas for governments and scientists. Copenhagen will not change the world. Leaders will.\u000a\u000aThe author is a member of the Planning Commission
