aVNEW DELHI: A united Opposition on Monday kept up the heat in Rajya Sabha on the government's changing stance on climate change negotiations.Despite environment minister Jairam Ramesh's claim that the core of India's stance has not changed, BJP, Left and Samajwadi Party MPs walked out of the House protesting that their concerns had not been addressed.Raising the issue of conflicting statements on climate change during Zero Hour, leader of Opposition in RS Arun Jaitley alleged that the government had altered the position it held all along by unilaterally announcing 20%-25% cut in carbon intensity on the 2005-level till 2020. He also pointed out that the principle of equality represented by per capita entitlement principle was also altered, leading to unhappiness among official negotiators.Jaitley said, "The original understanding was there would be substantial cuts being made by the developed countries, and today, having really bared our hands completely on the eve of negotiations, we do not know what the developed countries are going to do. It is a bad strategy." Jaitley also pointed out at the lack of reciprocity and apprehension of two key negotiators.Sitaram Yechury (CPM) said change in India's position was due to US pressure and cited a White House press release that said change in the position of India and China was due to bilateral meetings with US president. He demanded that per capita emission standard should not be diluted.Earlier, Yechury said, "Voluntary announcement of emission cut means that by 2020 we will have to reduce carbon intensity by 150% of what we have reduced in the last 15 years." D Raja (CPI) asked what can government do to prevent companies and government agencies to grab forest land to earn carbon credits.Responding to members, Ramesh said non-negotiables will continue to be non-negotiables till December 18, when the Copenhagen meeting ends. He said the country will not accept a legally binding emission reduction cut. Secondly, voluntary declaration of emission was not an internationally legally binding commitment. Thirdly, he said, India rejected the notion of a peak year. "We will not accept any draft which suggests India's emissions should peak by 2025, 2030. This is simply not on our agenda," he said.He said while India supported international scrutiny of supported action, it will not allow international scrutiny of unsupported actions. "What I have stated is that India, once in two years, will submit to the UNFCCC a national communication for consideration," he said, adding voluntary cut in emission enhanced India's negotiating chances.He also said that two negotiators had some doubts that had been cleared.Brinda Karat (CPM) said the minister had done a great disservice to the nation and asked why India will submit national communication for consideration. Jaitley also said none of the concerns have been addressed and walked out along with party MPs. Left and SP also walked out.
