aVA four-nation axis comprising India, China, Brazil and South Africa has clearly emerged and would play a key role in shaping the outcome of the 12-day UN climate change meet that began at Danish capital Copenhagen on Monday, environment and forests minister Jairam Ramesh told FE. The four emerging economies have drawn up a basic draft for negotiating cuts in greenhouse gas emissions on the principle of differentiated responsibility, he said.\u000a\u000aThe minister saw a great degree of convergence among the offers made by the four countries for reducing their carbon footprints but was dismissive of the Danish and EU drafts in circulation. The Danish and EU drafts are clearly unacceptable to us, he said, adding that any attempt by the developed world to force such unrealistic proposals on the rest would be thwarted by the strength of the four-nation axis.\u000a\u000aThe new yardstick of emission intensity of GDP, the minister indicated, is just another pillar of its climate policy foundation. But the per capita argument persists and it is consistent with the notion of carbon intensity of GDP and historical contributions to the greenhouse gas build-up. India would not discard the proposition that mitigation action by each country should be commensurate with its per capita emission level.\u000a\u000aAccording to senior officials at the ministry, India is keenly aware of the developed worlds desire to isolate it at the meet and typecast it as a deal-breaker. Last weeks offer on reducing emission intensity of GDP is a strategic move to preempt such efforts, they said.\u000a\u000aIndia is also planning a domestic law on mitigation action that would help it meet the self-imposed targets. Such a law, sources said, would make the countrys negotiating position more unassailable.\u000a\u000aHost Denmark had put out a draft last week exhorting all countries, irrespective of their levels of economic/social development or relative shares in the cumulative effect of historical CO2 emissions, to adopt 2020 as the year when their emissions would peak. Ramesh said this proposal was shorn of any realistic estimates and blatantly violated the notion of differentiated responsibility. Similarly, the EU draft imposes the onus of unrealistic spending demands on the developing world, thereby, undermining the solemn promise that developed world would predominantly finance the climate management efforts.\u000a\u000aIndia would not commit to any binding emission cuts, the minister reiterated. The country offered to cut its carbon emission intensity of GDPthe quantum of emission per unit of GDPby 20-25% from the 2005 level by 2020. This offer is voluntary and unilateral. China has also adopted the scale of emission intensity of GDP and offered a 40-45% cut.\u000a\u000aSouth Africa said on Sunday it would reduce emissions by 34% from business-as-usual level over the next 10 years. Brazil has committed absolute reduction of it carbon emissions by 30% by 2020.
