aVAs the keenly-awaited climate change conference formally opened this morning, it received a shot in the arm by the encouraging findings of an analysis which showed that if countries deliver on their present commitments for the year 2020, the effort could be almost enough to keep the global rise in temperatures to within 2 degrees Celsius from pre-industrial levels, a goal that is now considered imperative to achieve.\u000a\u000aThe analysis, presented by the famous climate economist Lord Nicholas Stern, says if the countries achieved their ambitious targets, the total global emission in the year 2020 was likely to be 46 billion tonnes, only slightly more than the 44 billion tonne that is believed to be the upper limit for emissions in that year so that a temperature rise beyond 2 degrees can be avoided. The gap can be filled by the developed countries taking a little more ambitious cuts or the developing countries coming forward with plans for further reductions through their domestic policy.\u000a\u000aStern, whose report on the economics of climate change a few years ago is still considered to be the most credible, circulated the results of his new analysis at the conference centre here. The results take into account the most recent commitments made by the countries and include the cuts in carbon intensity announced by China and India. They also include the commitments made by the United States, European Union, Japan, Russia, Australia and Canada to reduce their emissions. The emissions in 2010 are projected to be 47 billion tonne. The analysis is laced with many conditions and it bases its findings on the best case scenario.\u000a\u000aFor India, the report projects that the 20 gw of solar energy under the National Solar Mission can result in savings of about 30 million tonne of carbon dioxide emissions by the year 2020. Similarly, a 15% increase in renewable energy and addition of seven million hectares of land under forest cover would each reduce Indias emissions by 70 million tonne by 2020.\u000a\u000aHowever, despite this, the analysis projects Indias total emissions in 2020 at 3.6 billion tonne, almost two times the current levels.\u000a\u000aThe analysis says the real task would start beyond 2020 when more drastic measures would be required to reduce the global emissions to about 14 billion tonne by the year 2050 to be consistent with the 2 degree objective.\u000a\u000aMeanwhile, the conference formally opened today with the UNFCCC executive secretary urging countries to start acting from the day this conference comes to an end.\u000a\u000aThe time for formal statements is over. The time for restating of old positions is past. The time has now come to act, and to reach out to one another. We have to begin significant and immediate action the day this conference ends, he said, addressing the opening ceremony. Deliver. Reach for success, he said.
