aVAs the climate change conference began in Copenhagen on Monday amidst renewed expectations after more than 100 heads of state confirmed their participation, back home a united Opposition in the Rajya Sabha walked out, accusing the government of giving in to the US pressure and announcing its emission intensity cuts. Refuting the allegations, environment minister Jairam Ramesh emphasised that India would not accept any legally binding emission cuts.\u000a\u000aUnder no circumstances, we will accept any draft which suggests that Indias emissions should peak by 2025, 2030... This is simply not on our agenda, Ramesh said.\u000a\u000aReplying to queries from members in the Rajya Sabha, he said India would not accept the same level of international scrutiny for the countrys unsupported carbon mitigation action though it can do so for the plans supported by global funding and technology.\u000a\u000aWherever the world supports us in terms of finance and technology, they can come and verify what we are doing. But where you (developed world) are not supporting us... we will not support these actions to international scrutiny, he said.\u000a\u000aOn Thursday, environment minister Jairam Ramesh had announced that India would unilaterally cut its emission intensity by 20-25% by 2020 on a baseline of 2005. He had also added that the country would neither take on legally binding emission cuts nor accept a peaking year for emissions.\u000a\u000aAs reported by FE on Saturday, India can continue on its growth trajectory and still cut its carbon intensity by up to 39% by 2020 on a baseline of 2005 as per the Planning Commission.\u000a\u000aIndia has already cut its emission intensity by 17.6% between 1990 and 2005. The country has been able to do so by pursuing a policy to promote energy efficiency, renewable energy, nuclear power, fuel switching, energy pricing reforms, and addressing GHG emissions in the energy sector.\u000a\u000aIts possible for India to cut its emissions further by making it mandatory for vehicles to have fuel efficiency standards by 2011, putting in place a model code for buildings, introducing energy efficiency certificates, and running half of new capacity addition of power plants on clean coal. The 12th Five Year Plan is also expected to pitch for low-carbon economy, Ramesh had added in his statement.\u000a\u000aThese initiatives are important because most consumers in India, like in the rest of the world, believe that the main responsibility of solving climate change rests with the government, according to new research by Nielsen Company and Oxford University Institute of Climate Change.
