aVParliament rejects Rudd's premium on carbon plan.\u000a\u000aAnil Sasi\u000a\u000aMelbourne, Dec.7\u000a\u000aEven as the Indian Government managed to steamroll its view for some \u2018flexibility' in India's stand on climate change, Australia \u2014 one of the largest per-capita emitters of greenhouse gas \u2014 has been forced to go into the Copenhagen talks with a diluted mandate after a bitter political tug-of-war.\u000a\u000aThe Prime Minister, Mr Kevin Rudd's \u2018cap and trade' Bill, which aimed at putting a premium on carbon, was shot down in the Australian Parliament earlier last week. Despite being hailed as the Australian PM who reversed the country's anti-Kyoto position, Mr Rudd was forced to head for the COP15 Summit with a Parliament at home that put its foot down against any pro-climate action.\u000a\u000aIn order to go to Copenhagen as an environmental leader, the Australian Prime Minister had forced an early vote on the proposed \u2018cap and trade' Bill. Australia is dependent almost entirely on coal-fired stations for electricity and has a very high per-cap emission due to its small population.\u000a\u000aWhen Mr Malcolm Turnbull, leader of Australia's opposition Liberal party and someone who was considered too close to Mr Rudd on climate policy, gave his support for the Bill, a high-octane debate began in the country. The dramatic week in Australian politics ended with the Liberal party voting out Mr Turnbull and replacing him with Mr Tony Abbot, a staunch climate sceptic.\u000a\u000aUnable to retract the call for an early vote, Prime Minister Rudd's \u2018cap and trade' Bill was shot down in the Australian Parliament. Although the nation's total carbon footprint is dwarfed by other countries, this move has considerably limited Australia's ability to negotiate for an international treaty from a position of strength.\u000a\u000aThe COP15 summit began on Monday in Copenhagen, where climate negotiators hope to craft a replacement for the Kyoto Protocol.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 8, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated
