aVThe United Nations Climate Change Conference, 2009 received a shot in the arm on its opening morning as an authoritative analysis showed that if countries deliver on their present commitments for the year 2020, they could almost keep the global rise in temperatures to within 2 degrees Celsius of pre-industrial levels, a goal that is now considered a necessity.\u000a\u000aThe analysis, presented by climate economist Lord Nicholas Stern, said that if all countries achieved their targets, total global emissions in 2020 could be 46 billion tonnes, only slightly more than the 44 billion tonnes, which is understood to be the upper limit for emissions in that year so that a temperature rise beyond 2 degrees Celsius is avoided.\u000a\u000aThe minor shortfall can be made up if developed countries are a little more ambitious with cuts, or if developing countries take some extra steps for further reductions through domestic policy.\u000a\u000aStern, whose report on the economics of climate change published a few years ago is still considered to be the most credible, circulated the results of his new analysis at the conference centre here. The results take into account the cuts in carbon intensity announced by China and India, and include commitments made by the US, EU, Japan, Russia, Australia and Canada.\u000a\u000aThe analysis incorporates many conditions, and has based its findings only on the best case scenario.\u000a\u000aFor India, Stern's report projects that the 20 GW of solar energy under the National Solar Mission can result in savings of about 30 million tonnes of carbon dioxide emissions by the year 2020. A 15 per cent increase in renewable energy and addition of seven million hectares of land under forest cover would each reduce India's emissions by 70 million tonnes by 2020, says the report.\u000a\u000aHowever, despite this, the analysis projects India's total emissions in 2020 at 3.6 billion tonnes, almost twice the current levels.\u000a\u000aThe analysis says the real task would start beyond 2020 when more drastic measures would be required to reduce global emissions to about 14 billion tonnes by the year 2050 to be consistent with the 2 degrees Celsius objective.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Narendra Modi a monster, Trinamool has pact with him: Buddha\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
