aVThe auto sector, alternative energy and gas-based fuel companies, and the engineering and capital goods segment are among those who stand to gain from the Indian proposal for a 20%-25% reduction in carbon emission intensity from 2005 levels by 2020. The assurance spells bad news for the cement and steel industry, say stock market experts.\u000a\u000aWhile the replacement of older, less efficient vehicles should benefit auto companies such as Tata Motors, Ashok Leyland and Maruti Suzuki, the shift to cleaner and better fuels should benefit gas-based and alternative energy related companies such as Gail and Suzlon, as well as large complex refiners Reliance Industries, says a note sent by Macquarie Equity Research, a leading overeseas brokerage firm, to its clients. It adds that the so-called dirty fuel-based companies such as Cairn and IOCL may be negatively impacted.\u000a\u000aWhile new emission norms are applicable to new vehicles, there could be an increase in demand for public transport as state transport units run by the government may be asked to improve their fleets. Moreover, very old trucks will also be replaced and old taxis will be phased out to improve on vehicle emission. This will be good news for companies such as Tata Motors, Maruti Suzuki and Ashok Leyland. While there is a cost for manufacturers to upgrade their vehicles to comply with new norms, this is normally passed on to consumers, says the report.\u000a\u000aExperts argue that to meet the new emissions norms proposed, industries across the board will have to incur higher capex, which is positive for the engineering and capital goods segment.\u000a\u000aSince companies across the board will have to incur higher capital expenditure in plant and machinery to meet the proposed emission norms, we believe that large engineering and capital goods industries will be the major beneficiary.\u000a\u000aIn this context, L&T, Bhel and Praj Industries, which focus on green and clean technologies, are in a position to take the maximum advantage, says Deven Choksey, MD, KR Choksey Securities.\u000a\u000aGiven that renewable energy is a policy-driven sector, the Macquarie report notes that this could prompt a Copenhagen rally in renewable energy stocks like Suzlon, the largest wind turbine manufacturer in India, and Moser Baer, a manufacturer of solar panels.\u000a\u000aHowever, material stocks like Tata Steel, Grasim Industries and Ultra Tech cement, among others, will be negatively impacted by the move to meet the emission requirements as they will have to incur additional capex according to Macquarie.\u000a\u000aBut one section of the market feels that since companies have enough time ahead for meeting the required norms and unless these commitments are mandatory, there wont be much impact on the industry.\u000a\u000aThough prima facie it appears that the cement and steel industry will be negatively impacted because of the proposed move Arup Misra, analyst at Elara Capital, said, Unless and until those commitments become mandatory or legally binding on companies in India, I dont see any major downturn in these industries because of the proposed move.
