aV\u201cThe most difficult talks ever embarked upon by humanity\u201d are in progress at Copenhagen, the results of which will be felt \u201cby the rice farmer in Sichuan in China, by Google headquarters . . . or by the oil worker in Norway\u201d. This is what one Minister attending the conference is reported to have said before the event began on Monday.\u000a\u000aAnother view, proffered by a climate expert hailing from Potsdam in Germany, is that \u201cit is unlikely that we will achieve what is necessary so that (carbon) emissions will peak before 2020\u201d, the hope being that there will be a \u201cmagic moment\u201d of concessions which would inject life into the conference which, many apprehend, will be all bluster and promise and no solid, sincere commitment.\u000a\u000aFlow of concessions\u000a\u000aIndeed, the flow of \u201cconcessions\u201d seems to have begun in right earnest with the US President, Mr Obama, saying that his country would reduce greenhouse gas emissions \u201cin the range of\u201d 17 per cent below 2005 levels by 2020 and 83 per cent by 2050; Beijing announcing the very next day that it would reduce the carbon intensity of the Chinese economy by 40-45 per cent below 2005 levels by 2020; and, after a week, New Delhi telling the world that India would reduce its carbon intensity levels by 20-25 per cent on 2005 levels over the next 11 years.\u000a\u000aThese \u201cconcessions\u201d are important because they involve three important global economic players who have adopted a totally different line in climate negotiations till now.\u000a\u000aClearly, the timing of the moves on the part of the three countries is closely linked to the conference which, incidentally, is what makes them suspect in the eyes of those who have been watching the farcical \u201cclimate struggle\u201d unfold ever since the Kyoto Protocol came into being. (The confabulations are \u201cfarcical\u201d because the participants are straining every nerve to get the better of each other knowing full well that failure would lead to the extinction of life as we know it today in the not-too-distant future.)\u000a\u000aTake, for instance, New Delhi's stand. In July 2008, the Prime Minister, Dr Manmohan Singh, laid bare the basics of the Indian position on the subject when he told a meeting of the 16-member major economies group in Hokkaido that the issue of climate-change \u201cshould not be used to add conditionalities to already complex development challenges that we face in developing countries or maintaining economic status quo or attempting to introduce protectionism by another means\u201d.\u000a\u000aHe said that poverty eradication was \u201cthe first and overriding\u201d priority for all developing countries. \u201cMore than 600 million people in India are still without access to modern energy sources, and a quarter of our population lives on less than a dollar a day\u201d. According to Dr Singh, the \u201csustained and accelerated economic growth was critical for developing countries and we cannot for the present even consider quantitative restrictions on our emissions\u201d.\u000a\u000aImportant issues\u000a\u000aTwo things are important here, namely, the \u201cper capita\u201d concept (which the Prime Minister has overtly applied to the carbon emission scenario on a number of occasions) and, of course, the ruling out of the quantitative-restrictions approach. Both these ideas have been pushed into the background at Copenhagen.\u000a\u000aIn fact, one Union Minister has reportedly pontificated that \u201cper capita is an accident of history\u201d and the fact that we have a low figure \u201cis no great credit to us\u201d. Clearly, this line is utter nonsense, but the fact remains that, as an important player, New Delhi has \u2014 at least on the face of it \u2014 altered its stance at the negotiating table. One only hopes that the ploy is ultimately successful, for the stakes are very, very high indeed \u2014 for the future of life on the planet.\u000a\u000aRANABIR RAY CHOUDHURY\u000a\u000aRelated Stories:\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 9, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated
