aVOn the second day of the climate change conference here, the much-reviled Danish draft for the possible agreement was the subject of intense discussions, inviting sharp reactions from the developing countries which rejected the proposals saying it was an attempt to kill the Kyoto Protocol and replace it with an agreement more favourable to the rich countries.\u000a\u000aThe Danish draft, which introduces the concept of a 'peaking year' for the entire world and wants developing countries to share mitigation responsibilities as well, was 'shown' to a number of countries, including India.\u000a\u000aMany countries voiced their objections immediately following which the host country was said to be working to modify some of the contentious clauses and come up with an amended draft over the next couple of days. It was not clear which clauses were sought to be amended.\u000a\u000a"It is clear that such proposals would not be acceptable to the developing countries. It is a question of our survival. The attempt is to make a sweet agreement for the rich countries. It shows a complete lack of sensitivity to the poorer nations," said a negotiator from the G-77 group which had already made it clear on the opening day that it would reject any agreement that did not come through the negotiation process.\u000a\u000aIndia's head of negotiating team Shyam Saran, however, was more restrained in his criticism. "We were shown the draft. It wasn't circulated to us. We understand that there are quite a few contentious issues which are not acceptable to us. But as of now, we don't know in what form this is going to be introduced in the negotiation process," he said.\u000a\u000aThe Danish Draft recognises the need to contain the global rise in temperatures to within 2 degrees Celsius compared to pre-industrial levels and suggests that the global emissions be made to peak in a year not later than 2020, with the understanding that the developed countries have peaked a little earlier so that developing countries get a little more time for peaking. It also talks about reducing the global annual emissions by at least 50 per cent by 2050 on 1990 levels and convergence of per capita emissions of all the countries. However, it wants the developing countries to have their domestic actions also open to international scrutiny, something that is not acceptable to the developing countries.\u000a\u000aIn the evening, representatives from many African countries also staged a short protest march at the conference venue, shouting slogans against the Danish draft.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Narendra Modi a monster, Trinamool has pact with him: Buddha\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
