aVChina and the United States, the world's two biggest emitters of greenhouse gases, sent the temperatures soaring with a heated exchange of words over which developing countries should be considered for money from the rich countries to adapt to climate change.\u000a\u000aResponding to US Special Envoy Todd Stern's comments on Wednesday about China being ineligible for government finance from the rich countries, China's vice minister of foreign affairs He Yafei today said his country was not seeking "donation or charity". He said the rich countries were legally obligated to provide money to the developing countries for putting their survival at stake through their years of emissions.\u000a\u000aHe stressed that China too was a developing country but said it was not asking the money for itself, it was only acting on behalf of other developing countries.\u000a\u000a"I was shocked to read the comments (of Todd Stern). I don't want to say the gentleman is ignorant. He is very well educated but he lacks common sense  or he is extremely irresponsible," Yafei said at a press conference here.\u000a\u000aA couple of hours later, Stern, however, stuck to his guns and said he had only talked about public finance not being available to major developing countries like China or India.\u000a\u000a"There is this whole spectrum of other finance driven by the private sector and there, investments can go in all sorts of directions  China, India or anywhere. I am not saying anything about that," Stern said.\u000a\u000aYafei, however, said that Stern's comments violated the spirit of cooperation between the countries that was seen during President Barack Obama's visit to China last month.\u000a\u000a"I would ask him, or any person who is interested in the climate change issue between China and the US to read the joint statement when Obama visited China three weeks ago. I would ask the gentleman to read it carefully. That joint statement represents the consensus and the two countries have agreed to work together on climate change," he said.\u000a\u000aYafei also said that China would go ahead with its domestic programme on climate change regardless of whether it received money from the rich countries or not.\u000a\u000a"We have done enough (on climate change) without any external support for the last dozen or so years. And our commitment for 2020 is not based on external support. It is a unilateral effort," he said about China's recent decision to cut 40-45 per cent of its emission intensity by 2020.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Narendra Modi a monster, Trinamool has pact with him: Buddha\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
