aVMembers of Parliament from North-Eastern states plan to step up their campaign for a "fair deal" in the discourse on climate change, seeking an incentive to retain the forest cover and bio-diversity reserves in the region.\u000a\u000aAt an MPs' meet organised by a think tank last week, parliamentarians from N-E, cutting across party lines, strongly called for "a fair deal for the region to conserve its ecology".\u000a\u000aThe Sikkim Democratic Front's Prem Das Rai (representing Sikkim), the Congress's Ninong Ering (representing Arunachal East), and the Congress's Ranee Narah (representing Lakhimpur) stressed the need for "Governmental incentive to protect the rich forest cover in the region" while an MP from the region reportedly said that "the N-E states must not be made to pay for the pollution caused by cities like Mumbai and Delhi".\u000a\u000aJD(U) Rajya Sabha MP N K Singh, the BJP's Anurag Singh Thakur and the Rashtriya Lok Dal's Jayant Chaudhary were also present.\u000a\u000aMost MPs of the region felt they had not been given adequate opportunities to "speak about their concerns". Rai, for instance, was the only speaker from the region to take part in the Lok Sabha debate on the subject on December 3.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Narendra Modi a monster, Trinamool has pact with him: Buddha\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
