aVAt a time when global leaders are trying to hammer out a deal for reducing global warming at the UN Summit in Copenhagen, a study conducted by scientists from the Indian Agricultural Research Institute (IARI) has revealed that climate change could cause a significant reduction in wheat production in India.\u000a\u000aThe findings assume significance at a time when declining area under agriculture, depleting resources and obsolete technology have put a big question mark over Indias ability to meet its food requirement in coming years.\u000a\u000aThe assessment noted that adaptation strategies (methods to cope with the adverse impact) will provide only some short-term relief while the existing ones might not be sufficient to meet the rising future wheat demand. Due to climate change, the current technologies alone will not be sufficient to meet future wheat demand even if all necessary support is provided for bridging the yield gap, PK Aggarwal and DN Swaroopa Rani, scientists with the IARI have observed in their paper titled Assessment of Climate Change Impacts on Wheat Production in India.\u000a\u000aThe paper has noted that either new genotypes with higher yield potential will be required or a change in land use pattern is needed which would lead to timely wheat plantation in the main growing regions of northern India. Increased melting of glaciers and consequent reduction in water availability will further limit progress in wheat production unless new genotypes which have higher yield potential, water use efficiency and temperature tolerance are involved, the paper noted.\u000a\u000aThe study has even warned that the governments much-publicised National Food Security Mission (NFSM), which, at present, focuses on bridging yield gap in wheat production, may become weak in future due to climate change.\u000a\u000aIn the absence of effective adaptation, the country would lose 3.9 million tonne of wheat yield due to climate change by 2020 and 11.7 million tonne by 2050 and 23.5 million tonne by 2080. Per hectare wheat yield in India is needed to be increased to 3.8-4 tonne by 2020 and more than 4 tonne by 2050 to feed the growing population , the study showed.\u000a\u000aHowever, the assessment also observed that though adaptation strategies have the potential to nullify these losses completely in the short run, those would be less effective in the long run. The study also analysed that the adjust potential yields have slowly increased from 4.25 tonne per hectare in 1960 to 4.8 tonne in 2000 largely because of expansion of irrigation in wheat producing regions of northern India. On an average, this increase in potential yields was 14 kg per hectare per year.\u000a\u000aIndias wheat production in 2008-09 was at around 80.58 million tonne.
