aVCopenhagen appears to be all about enlightened self-interest of the developed nations and the impatient urge of the developing countries to attain sustainability levels, even at the cost of damaging the planet.\u000a\u000aMohan Murti\u000a\u000aI am writing this column from KaeseStrasse \u2014 CheeseRoad in the gourmet region of Bregenzerwald in Austria, far away from the Danish capital of Copenhagen, where 15,000 delegates and officials, 5,000 journalists and a 100 world leaders, are locking horns. The CheeseRoad farmers in the valley and alpine dairies produce alps cheese, butter and cream-based traditional mountain recipes.\u000a\u000aThe CheeseRoad farmers are a happy contented lot. Why? They have no electricity in their homes (out of choice), they eat and drink what grows and is produced on their farms. They do not own cars or mobile phones. Their carbon footprint is zero. Enjoying my cheese fondue and vin blanc, it seems copiously clear to me that, at the end of Day Six, the climate change summit in Copenhagen is about to collapse in a heap of irritability, peevish blame, reproach and caustic retorts by nations against one another.\u000a\u000aSpeaking with one voice\u000a\u000aOn December 7, the opening day of the Copenhagen climate change summit, 56 newspapers in 45 countries took the unprecedented step of speaking with one voice through a common editorial. Can anything be more boring? The editorial presented an apocalyptic scenario, with global warming ravaging the planet. That is fine.\u000a\u000aBut, while the editorial rightly pointed to the need to reduce CO {-2} emissions as an environmental clean-air objective, it accepted the global warming consensus, out-and-out, sans debate or discussion. The evidence that CO {-2} is the sole cause of global warming is questionable, as revealed by numerous scientific studies.\u000a\u000aIt seems that the global warming consensus is being used to validate a profitable, money-spinning, multi-billion-dollar carbon trading scheme which seeks to enrich corporations and financial institutions to the detriment of the developing countries.\u000a\u000aReducing emissions\u000a\u000aThe implementation of an environmental programme geared overtly towards reducing CO {-2} emissions at the national and international levels requires neither the global warming consensus nor a high-yield-driven carbon trading system. At this instant, banks are preparing to do with carbon what they have done in the past \u2014 craft market derivatives contracts that will rally round punters who hedge their price risk over the long term.\u000a\u000aIt seems clear that we have not many world leaders of sincerity, but more of sheer demagoguery and vainglory. Even a sightless man knows that the problems of global warming and climate change go beyond mouthing platitudes and any government permeated with half a vision would already have a roadmap in place to repair the situation. Instead, leaders in Copenhagen are humbugging each other and the rest of the world into advancing their national aspirations and the commercial interests.\u000a\u000aI was rather amused by the loud protestations coming from the world's two biggest greenhouse contaminators \u2014 China and the US. They have been exchanging spiteful, wounding remarks this week about the sincerity of their pledges to fight climate change. The Chinese Vice-Foreign Minister, Mr He Yafei, said that the US chief negotiator either lacks common sense or is \u201cextremely irresponsible\u201d.\u000a\u000aI was further entertained by the knee-jerk reaction of Mr Lumumba Stanislaus Di-Aiping, who represents the Group of 77 (G-77) at the UN climate change conference. He walked out of a consultation meeting with UN representatives in anger. As the chief negotiator for 130 developing countries, he believes that the UN climate change conference will probably be wrecked by the bad intentions of some people.\u000a\u000aMembers of the US delegation in Copenhagen have already made it clear that they will refuse any deal that looks even remotely like Kyoto. Further, they will oppose any agreement that does not load responsibilities onto developing countries, particularly China and India.\u000a\u000aRight to pollute?\u000a\u000aFrankly, all I see coming out of Copenhagen is about doing as little as possible, not as much as possible. It's all about extraordinary enlightened self-interest of the developed nations and the impatient urge of the developing countries to attain sustainability levels for the large majority of their people, even if it is at the cost of damaging the planet.\u000a\u000aCOP15 is about every country's rights to pollute. Not the right to clean up! The question of \u2018average' does not arise with matters of environment protection and pollution. It is like celibacy. There are no degrees or percentages; there are only \u2018either' and \u2018or'.\u000a\u000aI have tried to restrain my anguish and disgust at the visionless, rudderless, missionless political downward slide at the COP15, which, at best, has been bereft of mission. You don't need a 12-day shopping holiday in Copenhagen to start doing your bit.\u000a\u000aChange life-styles\u000a\u000aAlmost five billion humans have no idea what this COP15 is all about. But most of them will agree that there is no magic wand other than to change our life-styles. Simple changes. For instance, in India, at one stroke, one can stop massive de-forestation by adopting a sanitary way of disposal of the dead.\u000a\u000aRig Veda Book X.VI.IV speaks of \u201c Yea Agnidadhaa, Yea Anagnidadhaa\u201d meaning: \u201cThose who are burned with fire and those not burned with fire\u201d.\u000a\u000aImagine the number of trees that would remain uncut if we choose to have electric crematoriums instead of open funeral pyres and burials. We can easily listen to simple ideas that involve no great rocket science or high technology to be implemented over the next two years.\u000a\u000aAll the way, through India's long history, we have shared a fascination with, and respect for, animals and nature. The Atharva Veda has the magnificent hymn to the Earth (Bhumi-Sukta), redolent with ecological and environmental values.\u000a\u000aEarth, atmosphere, sky, sun, moon, stars, waters, plants and trees, as well as moving, swimming, and creeping creatures are all hailed and offered oblations (Taittiriya Samhita i-8-13).\u000a\u000aFor India, the slogan should be \u201cback to basics\u201d. This means a basic reorientation of our perceptions, accompanied by simple actions that are born out of deep personal commitment.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 14, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated
