aVWhile developing countries held up negotiations through most of Monday demanding quick decision on the emission reduction targets for the rich nations, a bigger chaos prevailed outside the conference venue where thousands of participants, who arrived for the second week of the meetings, queued up in biting cold to get their accreditation cards.\u000a\u000aAmidst heightened security arrangements in view of the arrival of over a hundred heads of states over the next few days, the crowd which had started gathering since early morning was kept waiting for more than eight hours in some cases before being allowed inside the venue to collect their access cards.\u000a\u000aAt least a couple of computers at the registration counter also crashed for some time leading to a long queue outside with many deciding to return and come back on Tuesday. The conference secretariat said more than 42,000 people had registered on the UNFCCC website for the meetings. By midday, about 23,000 delegates were already inside the venue.\u000a\u000aThe NGOs and observer groups form the largest contingent, comprising almost 60 per cent of the total participants registered for the conference. Due to security reasons and also the large number of people joining the conference on Monday, the NGOs were asked to reduce their numbers by about two-thirds. So the slogan-shouting, singing and drama that was the regular feature in the first week was completely absent on Monday. The access of NGO representatives to the meeting rooms has also been curtailed.\u000a\u000aMeanwhile, the big political leaders slowly started arriving for the summit meetings on December 17 and 18. Maldives President Mohammad Nasheed, who is quite a star in the climate change circles, was among the first heads of state to arrive and was immediately thronged by media-persons and television cameras. Many heads of states of the small island countries were stopping over in Germany for a couple of days where German Chancellor Angela Merkel and a few other EU leaders are scheduled to have informal meetings with them.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Narendra Modi a monster, Trinamool has pact with him: Buddha\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
