aVClimate change is a bitter reality that poses to be one of the greatest environmental, social and economic threats to the very existence of our planet. Every generation has a belief that its achievements are the greatest and its challenges insurmountable. But is the present generation doing enough to create a sustainable environment, which we have inherited not from our ancestors but borrowed from the generations to come\u000a\u000aCarbon dioxide and GHG emissions that arise from daily activity have led to an increase in the earths surface temperature having catastrophic effects. In the build up to economic development and superiority, countries across the globe have contributed to this ticking time bomb. The situation is further accentuated, as we witness a reversal in trends of energy consumption patterns between developed and developing countries. While, at present developed countries account for 22% of the world population and 70% of energy consumption, very soon we would see the developing countries comprising of 78% of the population and consuming 70% energy as compared to the earlier 30%.\u000a\u000aWith the growing concern on the outcome of ecological changes as a consequence of these energy consumption patterns, developing countries are faced with immediate concerns relating to forest and land degradation, freshwater shortage, food security and pollution levels. Therefore, there is increasing and mounting pressure on countries like China and India to reduce their carbon footprint and commit to reduced emission targets, given the level of development that these Asian giants are going through.\u000a\u000aIn India, especially climate change and security concerns have converged in a way that attention is drawn to the energy policy. In order to achieve its ambitious target of 8-10% growth in an attempt to alleviate poverty and beef up its infrastructural capabilities, the country needs to overcome its energy constraints. Given the potential that the country has in terms of access to renewable energy sources and energy efficient technologies, we can easily leapfrog over the carbon intensive phase of development and move towards a low or carbon neutral economy.\u000a\u000aIndias commitment to the climate change policy is evident at the national level, with the implementation of the National Action Plan on Climate Change (NAPCC) introduced by the Prime Minister in 2008. This initiative attempts to address not only issues related to climate change but also energy security in the country. The action plan which comprises of eight missions under its purview encompasses the use of renewable sources of energy such as solar, wind and hydro power and concentrates on the creation of an energy efficient sustainable habitat for a Green India.\u000a\u000aEven on the international playing field, Indias commitment has not staggered. While countries across the globe enter into negotiations to arrive at a successor to the Kyoto Protocol at Copenhagen, India has solidified its opinion for the creation of a fair and equitable multilateral framework that would help developing countries, especially India transition into a low-carbon economy, with the new global regime providing sufficient financial and technical support for mitigation and adaptation efforts.\u000a\u000aHowever, Indias stance on the polluter pays principle heading into Copenhagen remains intact. The country has re-emphasised that carbon reduction targets for all emitters be similar rather than having different parametres of measurement and accountability between the developed and developing countries. India will be striking its own path at Copenhagen keeping in mind that they will not be bullied by global pressure on climate change. India has already volunteered to cut its carbon intensity by 20-25% by 2020 over 2005.\u000a\u000aHowever, the overall sentiment is very clear, with India and China having now committed to international measurement and verification for environmental reporting measures; developing countries remain unwilling to let climate change be used as an excuse by developed nations to set up trade barriers and protectionist policies. With time for negotiations now running out, hope is emerging that a substantive pact can be agreed upon to pave the road ahead. There is an urgency to establish a common global goal with each nation contributing to the best of its ability to ensure we do not hit upon another roadblock to saving our planeta failure that is completely unaffordable.\u000a\u000aThe writer is managing director & country head, RICS India
