aVClimate change is the buzz word today. According to reports of the International Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), there is enough scientific evidence to prove that the matter is serious and needs immediate global action. As the Copenhagen Conference has started, every international leader is keen to be in the centre of the talks on climate change. However, one thing remains unclearwho will do what and by when, to save the planet from global warming.\u000a\u000aIndia and China are the most decisive countries, not only because of their size and hence the capacity to contribute to the climate change, but also because of their current growth rate. In the next two decades, these two developing giants are supposed to reach a stage where other developed countries stand today. The large investments flowing into these countries carry huge social and human costs. Projects often involve involuntary resettlement, mostly of poorer groups, with its potentially impoverishing impacts. In the fast-track race for development being currently pursued, it is critical that the interests of people displaced in the process are adequately protected. Development-induced displacement, resettlement and rehabilitation will be a major challenge for both the nations in pursuing their developmental goals.\u000a\u000aPeople displaced by development projects confront a variety of impoverishment risks that include landlessness, joblessness, homelessness, marginalistion, increased morbidity, food insecurity, loss of access to common property, and social disarticulation. If resettlement is not to leave people worse off than before, it must be addressed as a development opportunity.\u000a\u000aHowever, the basic challenge that needs to be addressed is that no country can afford to continue their developmental activities, in the business-as-usual style. All future developmental activities must also be sustainable in nature, including minimising displacement and fulfilling of all the resettlement and rehabilitation commitments.\u000a\u000aEvery year dams, highways, ports, urban improvements, mines, power plants, pipelines and petrochemical plants and other such industrial development projects globally displace about 10 million people. In India alone, involuntary resettlement is estimated to have affected about 50 million people in the last five decades and three-fourths of those displaced still face an uncertain future. While development projects are intended to reduce poverty, in practice, involuntary resettlement has often created new pockets of poverty all over the world.\u000a\u000aGrowing public concern over long-term consequences for project-affected people is resulting in greater scrutiny of the rehabilitation and resettlement process, particularly for large development projects. Economics is essentially, the science of the allocation of a finite resource pool, so an environmental perspective must guide the evaluation of all economic and developmental projects. This recognition must involve a comprehensive understanding of the perceptions and opinions of all stakeholders involved and their roles in the protection and management of the resource base. There is also need at the policy level to establish well-defined and enforceable rights (including customary rights) and security of tenure, and to ensure equal access to land, water and other natural and biological resources.\u000a\u000aSustainable development in the face of climate change makes collective action not an option, but an imperative. Some of the areas of common concern are marine and riparian issues, trans-boundary environmental impacts, management of bio resources and sharing of technology and information. It is time the blame game is stopped and developed countries take their lead as is their historical responsibility. Climate change mitigation has been registered prominently on the agenda of the developed countries but the gap between scientific response and political action remains large.\u000a\u000aWe need policies and guidelines to improve the environment and to ensure sustainable development. In this context, the Copenhagen Summit will be one more important opportunity for all the developed countries and their leaders to take concrete steps in drastically cutting down greenhouse gas emissions within a stipulated time frame. Simultaneously, they should also ensure the supply of technology that will help in mitigating the impact of climate change in developing nations. This is the right occasion for all the nations to jointly address the issues and find out global solutions through peaceful negotiations and in a cordial manner to save humanity.\u000a\u000aThe writer is a senior scinetist, Teri
