aVA deal needs to be made in Copenhagen for sure, but it first needs to be made at home.\u000a\u000aThe process of arriving at a comprehensive national policy takes more work and deliberation in a democratic set-up than what was displayed in the run-up to India's position at Copenhagen.\u000a\u000aAnmol Vanamali\u000a\u000aAt Copenhagen, India wants to be seen as a deal-maker and not a deal-breaker. According to the Environment Minister, Mr Jairam Ramesh, that is precisely the mandate given by the Prime Minister, Dr Manmohan Singh, to him and he seems to be sticking to it with aplomb.\u000a\u000aPrior to Copenhagen, he announced, much to the chagrin of the Opposition in Parliament, that India will aim for a unilateral policy of emissions intensity reduction of 20-25 per cent by 2020.\u000a\u000aAt a press briefing held at Copenhagen, he repeated that stance and added that a further reduction in emissions intensity could also be achieved with international support in terms of technology and finance.\u000a\u000aIndia's policy announcement is commendable and increases the chances of arriving at a framework agreement at Copenhagen. However, whether India has carefully scrutinised its actions to achieve these policy aims is a pertinent question that remains to be answered.\u000a\u000aThe National Action Plan on Climate Change (NAPCC) announced in June 2008 mentions two flagship mitigation missions; the Energy Efficiency (EE) mission and the Solar Mission.\u000a\u000aThe latter has now been rechristened as the Jawaharlal Nehru National Solar Mission (JNNSM).\u000a\u000aThe EE mission was conceptualised by the BEE (Bureau of Energy Efficiency) to reduce the wide spectrum of energy efficiencies seen in India's energy intensive sectors.\u000a\u000aBouquets\u000a\u000aOne of the most striking features of this is mission is called the \u201cPerform Achieve and Trade (PAT)\u201d scheme, which is an innovative market-based mechanism to ensure that in an energy-constrained country like India, wastage and inefficient use of energy is prohibited and penalised while efficiency and conservation are incentivised.\u000a\u000aIn most marginal abatement curve analysis, energy efficiency investments are found to be at the lower end and India would do well in making these investments unilaterally in order to show its contribution to fighting climate change instead of passing them off as offsets to reduce developed countries' burden at a cheap price.\u000a\u000aThe JNNSM aims for a three phase solar installation target with 1 GW in 2012, 10 GW in 2017 and 20 GW in 2022.\u000a\u000aThe targets for 2017 and 2022 are to be supported through international finance and technology. Thus the JNNSM is an effort to leapfrog from a business-as-usual scenario of using conventional and carbon-intensive sources to a solar intensive and carbon-free scenario.\u000a\u000aThis mission will have substantial co-benefits such as increase in domestic manufacturing capacity, R&D and cleaner air. The JNNSM is ripe as a model for the Nationally Appropriate Mitigation Action (NAMA) framework currently being debated at the UNFCCC negotiations, wherein a developing country's mitigation action can be supported partially through international public finance (called a supported NAMA) and could be eligible credits in the international offset market (called a credit-generating NAMA).\u000a\u000aThe explicit announcement of basing its success on international intervention means that it is in India's interest to ensure that domestic \u201cMeasuring, Reporting and Verification (MRV)\u201d policies mirror international standards to ensure that transition between the JNNSM and the future climate change architecture happen smoothly.\u000a\u000aBesides these, India has proactively announced feed-in-tariffs for a range of eligible renewable energy technologies, set up the Indian Renewable Energy Development Authority for specialised financing and passed a host of policies for incentivising better energy usage and penalising inefficiency.\u000a\u000aBrickbats\u000a\u000aHowever, India has also been a bit short of expectations in terms of process and, to an extent, substance. The gaping hole so far has been the lack of demonstration of a coherent pathway to reaching its emissions intensity reduction target. In climate change negotiations, and especially at this juncture in Copenhagen, policies that are not backed up by implementation plans don't carry much weight.\u000a\u000aThe US for all its faults and lack of ambition, has been through an extensive and, at times, excruciating negotiation process through its Congress before putting forth its 17 per cent reduction below 2005 levels by 2020 target.\u000a\u000aThough it remains to be passed by the Senate, the US Government can claim it has seriously engaged its constituents, be it the opposition, civil society, private sector or the general population, before walking up to the negotiating table. We have hardly seen such widespread involvement of various stakeholders in India in analysing the intensity reduction target.\u000a\u000aThe one day that it was discussed in Parliament, there was a walkout, led by the Opposition, as show of disagreement with India's proposal. It is unclear whether State governments were consulted before putting forth this proposal. There has also been no mention of the NAPCC's expected contribution to reaching the announced emission intensity reduction target, thereby reducing confidence in both.\u000a\u000aThere is also a potential stumbling block. India's unrelenting position that MRV for unilateral NAMAs should be separate from MRV for supported NAMAs, that is, MRV for unilateral actions are to be done according to Indian standards while MRV for supported actions are to be according to internationally acceptable standards. It is tough to see how that could be possible given that supported NAMAs will be inextricably linked to unilateral NAMAs and any quality issues with one will affect the legitimacy of the other.\u000a\u000aThe process of arriving at a comprehensive national policy takes more work and deliberation in a democratic state than what was displayed in the run-up to India's position at Copenhagen. It probably is one of the reasons why, in spite of all the good intentions shown by Jairam Ramesh, we have not been able to convince the developed countries that India has assumed a role of responsibility in fighting climate change.\u000a\u000aThe deal needs to be made in Copenhagen for sure, but it first needs to be made at home and then away.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 16, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
