aVClimate change threatens the survival of the planet, just as nuclear weapons did after Hiroshima and Nagasaki. But unlike then, the present world leadership seems unequal to the challenge.\u000a\u000aSharad Joshi\u000a\u000aThe negotiations over climate change at Copenhagen, critical to the survival of the planet itself, are a throwback to the Second World War years. At that time, too, it seemed that the world was on the cusp of disaster. Then, however, the world political leadership was of a different order.\u000a\u000aThis comes out through the memoirs of Dean Acheson, Present at the Creation. He was Secretary of State to President Harry Truman. In that role, he was instrumental in setting the tone and direction of the US foreign policy, especially towards the Communist bloc, at the start of the post-World War II era.\u000a\u000aTHEN AND NOW\u000a\u000aAcheson was one of the architects of the Bretton Woods institutions \u2014 the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD) and the International Monetary Fund (IMF). These structures marked the emergence of a new world order after the devastation of the Second World War.\u000a\u000aThe memoirs cover the years of the \u201cMarshall plan\u201d which was described by Churchill as \u201cthe most un-sordid act in human history\u201d. Understandably, his memoirs were entitled Present at the Creation. They contain a pithy but detailed account of the years he spent in the State Department. Extraordinary people were trying to build a new world piece by piece.\u000a\u000aThe devastation and loss of life in Germany, Italy and Japan, and the destruction caused by the atom bombs in Hiroshima and Nagasaki, gave rise to a fear that the world could be at the end of its days. A generation of statesmen then managed to ensure that the earth did survive the possibility of a nuclear conflagration, and created economic and political institutions to that effect.\u000a\u000aThe work that remained incomplete at that time, such as the General Agreement on Trade and Tariffs (GATT), was picked up much later, only after the fall of the USSR. That task remains far from finished even today. There are serious apprehensions that the Doha Round of the WTO might remain inconclusive.\u000a\u000aWhat is happening today is exactly the reverse of what took place in the immediate post-war period of Acheson. We could witness the dissolution of a civilisation that emerged after the Second World War.\u000a\u000aCLIMATE CHANGE THREAT\u000a\u000aThe earth is now threatened not by nuclear holocaust, but by global warming and climate change. The climate meet at Copenhagen, proclaimed as the last opportunity for human civilisation to save the Earth, is clearly heading for an impass.\u000a\u000aClimate change is coming out to be a far more serious threat than a nuclear attack. After the World War, the superpowers showed enough sagacity to stave off a nuclear confrontation. The present leadership appears to lack the statesmanship of its predecessors.\u000a\u000aThe problem goes beyond the climate issue. Economic and the financial crises are throwing into question the validity of the Bretton Woods institutions. Multilateral trade bodies, such as the World Trade Organisation, have lost their way.\u000a\u000aHad the successors of Truman and Acheson in the US inherited even a fraction of their statesmanship, they would not have insisted on a system of trade based on massive agriculture subsidies, that heaps colossal livelihood losses on the developing world. Nor would they have perversely persisted in demanding further opening up of Third World markets.\u000a\u000aThey would not have demanded that those nations innocent of polluting over centuries be the first to commit to mitigation of greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions.\u000a\u000aThe only way the Third World countries can continue to improve lifestyles without augmenting GHGs is through massive investments and import of technology. Worthy successors of earlier statesmen would have insisted on this transfer as a precondition for any emission reduction.\u000a\u000aIMMATURE AMERICA\u000a\u000aPresident Barack Obama's country is not the US of Truman and Acheson. It is standing on its political prestige, unwilling to adopt attitudes appropriate to a mature superpower. It is entering into fratricidal arguments with the less fortunate poor cousins on per capita emissions and carbon credits.\u000a\u000aThe collapse of the Doha Round or even that of the World Trade Organisation would not necessarily mean the end of the world. Human ingenuity is infinite and an appropriate generation will create structures that will bring together the actual traders rather than their political representatives for discussing trade matters. However, a stalemate at Copenhagen will undoubtedly bring in an era of severe food insecurity. The failure of the Doha talks will usher in a revival of protectionist trade wars.\u000a\u000aThe failure of the Doha Round as also of the climate meet at Copenhagen will only establish the intellectual and moral bankruptcy of the present world leadership.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 16, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated
