aVAmid a logjam over a climate treaty, the Danish Presidency of the conference on Wednesday abruptly announced that it will present two texts prepared by it, stunning several countries, including India, who said the move was against the essence of multilateralism.\u000a\u000aConnie Hedegaard, the Danish President of the UN Climate Change Conference (COP), who stepped down to make way for Prime Minister Lars Loekke Rasmussen, announced that the Presidency had prepared two texts on the Kyoto Protocol and Long Term Cooperative Action (LCA) tracks of negotiation.\u000a\u000aThe announcement left several delegates disgruntled who expressed deep concern about the manner in which the COP proceedings were being conducted, saying they were top down instead of being party-driven.\u000a\u000aWe have been told by the COP chair that a text has been prepared by the COP Presidency. On what basis, asked Vijai Sharma, Indias Environment Secretary, demanding inclusivity, transparency and the essence of multilateralism. Earlier in the day chaos ensued in a plenary meeting of negotiators that had gathered to discuss the Kyoto Protocol before the still heavily-bracketed text (areas still to be resolved) is presented to the ministers for conclusion. During the meeting, Hedegaard announced that the Danish presidency had prepared two texts one on Kyoto Protocol and another on the Long Term Cooperative Action.\u000a\u000aThe delegates were stunned by this announcement with some describing it as unprecedented.\u000a\u000aPM will leave for Copenhagen today\u000a\u000aNew Delhi\u000a\u000aPrime Minister Manmohan Singh will travel to Copenhagen on Thursday for the climate talks amid Indias receding hopes for clinching a legal framework to arrest global warming even as it said that ambitious emission cuts by rich nations was at the heart of success.\u000a\u000aSingh is expected to make an intervention at the plenary of the 15th Conference of Parties on Friday which would be addressed by Denmark Prime Minister Lars Loekke Rasmussen and UN Secretary General Ban ki-Moon.
