aVMohan R. Lavi\u000a\u000a\u201cPlease don't breathe unless you absolutely have to\u201d, commented someone when asked about greenhouse gas (GHG) reductions since every time we breathe out, we release the deadliest GHG \u2014 carbon dioxide or CO 2 . With the focus of everyone concerned on the deliberations at Copenhagen, the accounting world cannot be left too far behind since whatever has been emitted has to be accounted.\u000a\u000aThere has been a call for a single standard on accounting and disclosing GHG emissions to ensure that the data are comparable across both industries and countries. Amongst many, the World Resources Institute (WRI), through the World Business Council for Sustainable Development, has issued a Product Life Cycle Accounting and Reporting Standard for GHG.\u000a\u000aPurpose of Standard\u000a\u000aThe Greenhouse Gas Product Standard provides guidance for companies and other organisations to prepare an inventory of emissions associated with a product. The primary purpose of this standard is to support public reporting of product lifecycle greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions to help users reduce these emissions by making informed choices about the products they design, manufacture, sell, purchase or use.\u000a\u000aIn the context of this standard, public reporting refers to providing emissions-related information for a product, in accordance with the reporting requirements specified under the standard, by making it available in the public domain. This standard is designed for companies and organisations of all sizes in all economic sectors.\u000a\u000aAs in other accounting standards, this standard too talks of five principles \u2014 relevance, completeness, consistency, transparency and accuracy. To begin understanding how to calculate the emissions of a product, the company first defines the functional unit, which is the quantified performance of a product system for use as a reference unit, and establishes the basis for which the GHG inventory is calculated and reported.\u000a\u000aFunctional units\u000a\u000aSome examples of functional units include drying 1,000 pairs of hands, delivery of 1,000 litres of fruit drink, transport of six people and cargo by a vehicle over 100,000 miles. The total GHG inventory over the functional unit of a product represent the sum of GHGs resulting from all stages of its associated lifecycle within the specified system boundaries, also referred to as the product system.\u000a\u000aThe steps required to perform a GHG inventory are to establish the methodology, define the functional unit, identify the product system boundary, collect data, perform allocation, calculate emissions, perform data quality assessment, conduct assurance and report emissions.\u000a\u000aThe document goes on to state that to calculate carbon dioxide equivalents (CO 2 {-e}) of all non-CO 2 gases, the company shall use and report the most recent 100-year IPCC global warming potentials (GWP). The 100-year GWP is a metric used to describe the time-integrated radiative characteristics of well-mixed greenhouse gases over a 100-year time horizon.\u000a\u000aGWPs represent the combined effect of the differing times GHGs remain in the atmosphere and their relative effectiveness in absorbing outgoing infrared radiation (IPCC). Although other time horizons are available 100 years is the widely accepted time horizon adopted by UNFCCC in the Kyoto Protocol.\u000a\u000aSignificantly, the document states that purchased offsets \u2014 meaning the increasingly well-known practice of purchasing carbon credits \u2014 would not be taken into account as an emission source. On reporting, the standard states that a company shall publicly disclose the GHG inventory in the form of both a summary and detailed report.\u000a\u000aAccessible by public\u000a\u000aBoth reports shall be disclosed together and be easily accessible by the public. Neither report shall be disclosed separately without reference to the other report. The summary report identifies key information and results, while the detailed report contains more information about the methodological assumptions and data used to calculate the inventory.\u000a\u000aThe draft standard released by the WRI marks a significant step in accounting and reporting GHG emissions. Standard-setters such as the International Accounting Standards Board (IASB) and the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB) could use this standard as a benchmark to write theirs.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 17, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
