aVAs the climate change conference slowly moved into its final few hours, US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton caused some excitement into the negotiations with an announcement on long-term finance for developing countries that was full of promise but devoid of details and laced with conditions.\u000a\u000aClinton said the US would help in raising a global climate fund over the next one decade that, by the year 2020, would be able to give out $100 billion every year to the developing countries for meeting their climate change needs.\u000a\u000aShe was only echoing the proposal put forward by British Prime Minister Gordon Brown long time back, and reiterated earlier Thursday morning, but her remarks led to quite an excitement nonetheless.\u000a\u000aClinton said this fund would be created with contributions from all "major economies"  a term that can include countries like India or China, but was not specified  and from all possible kind of sources  public, private, bilateral or multilateral funds.\u000a\u000aBut Clinton said such a fund could be created only if Copenhagen was able to deliver a "comprehensive and operational" agreement that included 'verifiable and transparent' actions by all major economies. "In the absence of an operational agreement there will not be a financial commitment of this nature, at least by the US," she said.\u000a\u000aClinton's offer was met with cautious optimism in all circles. Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh said the offer contained conditions whose presence were "slightly undesirable". He also ruled out any contributions from India in such a fund. "Let us be very clear on that. India, as a developing country, is not in a position to contribute to a global fund. This is a responsibility and an obligation of the developed countries," he said.\u000a\u000aThis is the first time that the US has talked about a definitive figure and a time-frame for raising long-term finance for the developing countries.\u000a\u000aEarlier in the day, Japan too came up with a financial offer, pledging to provide $15 billion over the next three years, up to 2012, $11 billion of which would come from public finances. "These are welcome statements of intent. But they still have to be translated into formal commitments. These countries have not yet put the papers here making any concrete commitment," said Raman Mehta of ActionAid.\u000a\u000aThere was some concrete movement in a different sphere though. Australia, France, Japan, Norway, the UK and the US have decided to provide US $3.5 billion as initial public finance towards slowing, halting and eventually reversing deforestation in developing countries. This has been done under what is known as the REDD-plus (or Reduction of Emissions through Deforestation and Degradation) scheme.\u000a\u000a"An agreement to slow, halt and eventually reverse deforestation has to be central to the outcome here in Copenhagen. Around $25 billion over the period of 2010-15 is needed to cut deforestation rates in developing countries by 25 per cent by 2015. Developed countries should provide the majority of this, supporting rainforest countries' own efforts," Gordon Brown said in a statement.\u000a\u000a"This collective fast start effort is a very significant building block towards that. The UK's contribution to this initial effort is $480 million, part of the overall UK fast start package I announced last week," he said.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Narendra Modi a monster, Trinamool has pact with him: Buddha\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
