aVWith lots of details still to be thrashed out, it seems increasingly certain now that the Copenhagen talks, much like the Doha Round of WTO talks, will conclude without a concrete implementable agreement.\u000a\u000aSuparna Karmakar\u000a\u000aWriting a column on the penultimate day of the ongoing 12-day climate summit at Copenhagen is surely foolhardy, as most columnists would reserve their remarks and analysis until after the conclusion of the talks. However, emerging parallels of the climate talks with the ill-fated Doha Round of WTO talks, prompted me to rush where angels fear to tread.\u000a\u000aTo quickly outline the facts, delegations from 193 countries are in Copenhagen for the past 10 days for talks aimed at paving the way for a new global treaty on climate change, intended to replace the Kyoto Protocol which lapses in 2012. Two years ago, at the UN climate talks held in Bali, governments agreed to start work on a new global climate agreement. The Copenhagen talks mark the end of that two-year period.\u000a\u000aDeadlocked for now\u000a\u000aHowever, the talks (technically known as the 15th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) and often abbreviated to COP15) at the moment are deadlocked over lack of developed country commitments on emission cut targets (and on choice of base year), and technology and financial aid for poorer countries. A recently leaked Danish draft, with proposals of mandatory peaking year for emissions for all countries and urging emission-reduction targets for emerging economies, has made the developing country participants more wary. The Danish move appeared to be an attempt to include non-controversial portions in the LAC (Latin American and Caribbean) and Kyoto Protocol drafts, leaving out contentious portions, especially from a developed country perspective.\u000a\u000aThe prospects of the talks appear bleak; it seems increasingly certain now that the Copenhagen talks will conclude without a concrete implementable agreement other than the usual statements of good intent. Such communiqus issued after formal meetings of heads of states, as has been seen almost once every two months since the beginning of the recession in late-2008, usually turns out to be toothless and empty promises.\u000a\u000aIndia's lead negotiator, the Environment Minister, Mr Jairam Ramesh, has gone on record stating that any last minute commitment by the US President, Mr Barack Obama, can at best outline the big-picture of a deal, but with lots of details remaining to be thrashed out over the coming months or years.\u000a\u000aIs a deal possible?\u000a\u000aPrognosis for the Copenhagen talks looks eerily similar to the ongoing Doha Round of WTO negotiations. In fact, in the weeks leading up to Copenhagen, it had already become clear that a full, legally-binding treaty may not be possible.\u000a\u000aA political agreement at the end of the talks appears more likely, with attempts to secure a legally-binding treaty deferred until some point after mid-2010.\u000a\u000aBut even attaining the political agreement is fraught by the ongoing disagreement between the US and China on transparency commitments from China on the curbs on carbon emissions that Beijing has promised, that is, an inspection regime. China adamantly refuses to allow international monitoring of its domestic policies and actions.\u000a\u000aOn the other hand, developed country financing promises are also conditional. The recent pledge of new funds by Japan (its $5 billion per year, payable between 2010-2012, adds to the fast-start funding of \u20ac2.4 billion per year commitment the EU leaders made last week over the same period) also calls for legally binding emission curbs from developing countries.\u000a\u000aBut in the absence of a legally binding and enforceable agreement on the contours of financing promises by developed countries, it is certain that promises of finance and technology for climate change adaptation measures will go the way of the Montreal Protocol agreement on reducing ozone-depleting substances.\u000a\u000aMany developing country industry lobbies complain that the funding and technology needed for mitigation and adaptation under the Montreal Protocol either didn't come on time or came at a very high price.\u000a\u000aDeveloping country negotiators in Copenhagen need to remember that experience while signing on the dotted line of the climate deal.\u000a\u000aThe experience from another closely related set of financing commitments, the rich-country pledges on development aid to Africa, feeds this anxiety; only a few countries have actually consistently honoured their financing commitments (notably Denmark, Luxembourg, the Netherlands, Norway and Sweden).\u000a\u000aTechnology transfer\u000a\u000aTo help developing countries constrain their greenhouse gas emissions and meet reduction targets, developed nations have agreed in principle to help them in areas such as renewable energy. However, unless the mechanisms that can speed up the technology transfer for low-carbon economic growth are agreed upon as a part of the Copenhagen deal, the real climate change mitigation is unlikely to take place.\u000a\u000aDeveloping countries therefore should focus their negotiating energies equally on technology pricing and technology transfer, and enforcement and implementation issues, together with parlays on emission peaking, targets and carbon-intensity of industrialisation.\u000a\u000aAs argued by Jeffrey Sachs in a recent article, commitments of large-scale technology transfer and large funding initiatives from the developed world are unlikely to be honoured in the absence of an assessment formula.\u000a\u000aLike the IMF and the UN requires member-states to pay an assessment for their budget and implementation, there is also a need for clear formulas and accountability for technology transfer and financing for climate change mitigation and adaptation. A Copenhagen deal without a transparent, enforceable and accountable mechanism for implementation will be akin to an agreement for non-action.\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 18, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated
