aVTop greenhouse gas emitter (6.8 billion tonnes annually, 5.5 tonnes per capita)\u000a\u000aWHAT CHINA IS GIVING\u000a\u000aEmissions: China said it will cut its carbon intensity  the amount of carbon dioxide emitted for each unit of GDP  by 40 to 45 per cent by 2020, compared with 2005. The domestic voluntary target will still allow its emissions to grow substantially over the next decade, analysts said. This is the first measurable curb on national emissions in China.\u000a\u000aWHAT CHINA WANTS\u000a\u000aIt said developed nations' targets to reduce their greenhouse gas emissions are not deep enough. Expects average cuts of at least 40 per cent from 1990 levels by 2020 and wants a promise of far more aid and green technology.\u000a\u000aUNITED STATES\u000a\u000aWorld's second largest greenhouse emitter (6.4 billion tonnes annually, 21.0 tonnes per capita)\u000a\u000aWHAT THE US IS GIVING\u000a\u000aEmissions: The US promised to cut 2005 emissions by 17 per cent by 2020. This amounts to about 3 per cent below 1990 levels, the benchmark used in the Kyoto Protocol. The US also said it would extend cuts to 30 per cent below 2005 levels by 2025, and 83 per cent by 2050. Legislation to cut emissions by 20 per cent from 2005 levels is stalled in the full Senate.\u000a\u000aFinance: Hillary Clinton announced the US is prepared to work with other countries toward a goal of jointly mobilising $100 billion a year by 2020 to address the climate change needs of developing countries.\u000a\u000aOn Wednesday, the US pledged $1 billion as part of a $3.5 billion scheme as initial financing towards slowing deforestation, a major contributor to climate change. Australia, France, Japan, Norway and Britain are also part of the forest protection plan.\u000a\u000aWHAT THE US WANTS\u000a\u000aObama wants an accord in Copenhagen that covers all the issues and that has immediate operational effect. Senator John Kerry warned if the talks fail, chances for the US approving its own carbon pollution-reduction plan will erode. US wants China to be transparent over its CO2 emissions.\u000a\u000aEUROPEAN UNION\u000a\u000a(5.03 billion tonnes, 10.2 tonnes/capita)\u000a\u000aWHAT THE EU IS OFFERING\u000a\u000aEmissions: EU leaders agreed in December 2008 to cut emissions by 20 per cent below 1990 levels by 2020 and by 30 per cent if other developed nations follow suit.\u000a\u000aFinance: Agreed that developing nations will need about $147 billion a year by 2020 to help them curb emissions and adapt to changes such as floods or heatwaves. Last week, they agreed to provide $10.8 billion in initial aid from 2010-12.\u000a\u000aWHAT THE EU WANTS\u000a\u000aThe EU wants developing nations to curb emissions by 15 to 30 per cent below a trajectory of business as usual by 2020.\u000a\u000aINDIA\u000a\u000a(1.4 billion tonnes, 1.2 tonnes per capita)\u000a\u000aWHAT INDIA IS OFFERING\u000a\u000aEmissions: India aims to cut its carbon intensity by between 20 and 25 per cent by 2020, from 2005 levels. India will not set a year when emissions will peak.\u000a\u000aWHAT INDIA WANTS\u000a\u000aLike China, India wants rich nations to cut emissions by at least 40 per cent by 2020 below 1990 levels.\u000a\u000aAFRICAN COUNTRIES\u000a\u000a(Negligible emissions, include some of the countries most hurt by climate change)\u000a\u000aWHERE THEY ARE WILLING TO COMPROMISE on\u000a\u000aScaled back demands for climate finance from rich countries, meeting proposals made by developed nations and signalling agreement on a core obstacle in the talks.\u000a\u000aWHAT AFRICA WANTS\u000a\u000aMany African nations want developed nations to cut greenhouse gas emissions by at least 45 per cent below 1990 levels by 2020 as part of a goal of limiting global warming to a maximum of 1.5 Celsius above pre-industrial times.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Narendra Modi a monster, Trinamool has pact with him: Buddha\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
