aVThey came. They met. And they spoke in one voice.\u000a\u000aThe one positive for India from the failed Copenhagen summit is the bonding it developed with China on climate change discussions and the way that kept the two Asian giants together.\u000a\u000aPrime Minister Manmohan Singh and Premier Wen Jiabao showed glimpses of this relationship, at least on climate change, to the entire world when they stuck to a common stand and matched word for word outlining the essential parameters within which they would like to see the negotiations to continue.\u000a\u000aThe two leaders, who met for half an hour early in the morning, stressed the primacy of the three international agreements  UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, Kyoto Protocol and Bali Action Plan  while negotiating a comprehensive global agreement on climate change that could not be achieved in Copenhagen and now needs to be completed sometime next year.\u000a\u000aBoth expressed disappointment with the outcome from Copenhagen and urged the rich countries to fulfill their international legal obligations under the Kyoto Protocol and make ambitious emission reduction targets for the second commitment period starting in 2013.\u000a\u000a"The Kyoto Protocol should continue to stand as a valid legal instrument. Parties to the Protocol should deliver on their solemn commitments under the Protocol. It would go against international public opinion if we acquiesce in its replacement by a new and weaker set of commitments," Manmohan Singh said.\u000a\u000aWen Jiabao agreed and said there was no point in talking about long-term goals if the rich countries were not ready to deliver on their near-term targets.\u000a\u000a"It is necessary to set a direction for our long-term efforts but it is even more important to focus on achieving near-term and mid-term reduction targets, honouring the commitments already made and taking real action," he said.\u000a\u000aSingh talked about the principles of equity and common but differentiated responsibilities and Wen Jiabao matched it statements on historical responsibility and per capita emissions.\u000a\u000a"India and China have been working very closely for a balanced and equitable agreement on climate change. Premier Wen Jiabao stressed this at the morning meeting with Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and said the understanding between the two countries on this issue was reflective of the close friendship between the two leaders and the peoples of the two countries," Foreign Secretary Nirupama Rao said.\u000a\u000aHere's how one echoed the other: On UNFCCC, Kyoto Protocol and Bali Action Plan.\u000a\u000aSingh: The need for action on our part is more and not less than what was envisaged at the time of the Rio Convention or the Kyoto Protocol. That is why the Bali Action Plan commits us to enhancing the implementation of the UNFCCC. To settle for something that would be seen as diminished expectations and diminished implementation would be the wrong message to emerge from this Conference. Kyoto Protocol should continue to stand as a valid legal instrument. Parties to the Protocol should deliver on their solemn commitments under the Protocol.\u000a\u000aWen: The outcome of this conference must stick to, rather than obscure, the basic principles enshrined in the Convention and the Protocol. It must follow, rather than deviate from the mandate of Bali Roadmap.\u000a\u000aOn Common but Differentiated Responsibilities and Per capita emission principle:\u000a\u000aSingh: Equitable burden-sharing should underlie any effective global climate change regime. Any new regime will have moral authority and credibility only if it acknowledges that every citizen of the globe has an equal entitlement to the global atmospheric space.\u000a\u000aWen: The principle of common but differentiated responsibilities represents the core and bedrock of international cooperation on climate change and it must never be compromised.\u000a\u000aDuring their meeting, Wen clarified to the PM that the reference to the India-Pakistan dispute in the joint statement between China and United States  during US President Barack Obama's visit to Beijing in November  was not "directed against India", Rao said. Wen said relations between the two countries were based on equality and there was no intention on Chinese part to interfere in India's internal affairs. Rao said Singh appreciated the clarification and expressed his desire to further strengthen India's relations and friendship with China.\u000a\u000aALSO READ In Orissas liberated zone, two villages take on the Maoists\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
