aVAfter two weeks of talks in the Danish capital, world leaders agreed to take note of a new Copenhagen Accord to fight global climate change. A summary of the decisions in the Copenhagen Accord, and other decisions adopted at the UN summit:\u000a\u000aA NEW TREATY?\u000a\u000a No decision on whether to agree to a legally binding successor to the Kyoto Protocol.\u000a\u000a No agreement on whether to sign one new treaty replacing Kyoto, or two treaties.\u000a\u000a Kyoto limits the emissions of nearly 40 richer countries from 2008-2012. US never ratified the Protocol and it does not bind the emissions of developing nations.\u000a\u000a Rich nations prefer one new treaty including all countries; developing countries want to extend and sharpen rich nation commitments under Kyoto, and add a separate deal binding the US and supporting action by poorer countries.\u000a\u000a No agreement on whether a new pact would run from 2013-2017 or 2013-2020.\u000a\u000aLONG-TERM GOAL\u000a\u000a Recognises the scientific view that the increase in global temperature should be below 2 degrees C.\u000a\u000a Agrees that deep cuts in global emissions are required.\u000a\u000a Agrees to stop global and national greenhouse gas emissions from rising as soon as possible.\u000a\u000a No agreement on goals for global emissions cuts in the long-term, such as by 2050.\u000a\u000a Implementation of the accord would be reviewed in 2015 to include consideration of strengthening the long-term goal  for example to limit temperature rise to 1.5 degrees Celsius.\u000a\u000aEMISSION CUTS BY DEVELOPED COUNTRIES\u000a\u000a Rich countries would commit to economy-wide emissions targets for 2020 to be submitted by 31 January, 2010.\u000a\u000a Rich nation parties to the Kyoto Protocol would strengthen their existing targets.\u000a\u000a No agreement on a base year for 2020 goals, for example compared with 1990 or 2005.\u000a\u000a Rich nations have so far offered 2020 targets of cuts, which is about 14-18 percent below 1990 levels.\u000a\u000a Developing nations including China want collective rich nation cuts of at least 40 percent by 2020.\u000a\u000aACTION BY DEVELOPING COUNTRIES\u000a\u000a Developing nations would start mitigation actions to slow growth in their carbon emissions, submitting these by January 31, 2010.\u000a\u000a They would report those actions once every two years via the UN climate change secretariat.\u000a\u000a Actions which rich nations paid for would be recorded in a registry.\u000a\u000aFINANCE\u000a\u000a Establishes a Copenhagen Green Climate Fund.\u000a\u000a Agrees a goal for the world to raise $100 billion per year by 2020 to help developing countries cut carbon emissions and adapt to climate change.\u000a\u000a Developed countries would raise funds of $30 billion from 2010-2012 to help developing nations fight climate change.\u000a\u000a No agreement on how much individual countries would contribute to or benefit from any funds.\u000a\u000a A chunk of the funds would flow through the Copenhagen Green Climate Fund, which would support projects to slow deforestation, help countries adapt to climate change and fund development and sharing of clean technologies.\u000a\u000aEXCLUDED SECTORS, looPholes\u000a\u000a No agreement on whether to include emissions from aviation and shipping in climate targets.\u000a\u000a Kyoto excludes greenhouse gases from aviation and shipping, responsible for at least 5 percent of global emissions.\u000a\u000a Under Kyoto, rich countries do not have to include in their targets emissions from land use, including forests and farming.\u000a\u000a Combined, farms and deforestation account for a third of all global greenhouse gases.\u000a\u000aADOPTED DECISIONS ON CARBON MARKETS\u000a\u000a No agreement on how to scale up carbon finance under Kyoto's existing $6.5-billion clean development mechanism (CDM).\u000a\u000a Under CDM, rich nations pay for emissions cuts in developing countries through trade in carbon offsets.\u000a\u000a The European Union wants the scheme to invest tens of billions of dollars annually in developing nations by 2020.\u000a\u000aALSO READ\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
