aVIt has been win-win for the US. The BASIC group should also be satisfied as it has been able to retain its cherished \u201cdifferentiated responsibility\u201d without much damage to its long-term energy plans, says N. R. KRISHNAN.\u000a\u000aDiscord between the developed and developing countries to the end overshadowed the last minute \u2018accord' arrived at between the US and the BASIC (Brazil, South Africa, India and China) at the Copenhagen Climate Summit. Except for the five-nation accord, which was no small step, the proceedings never went smoothly \u2014 thanks to the machinations of the developed countries and the brazenly partisan attitude of the Danish Chairs of the gathering.\u000a\u000aFrosty reception\u000a\u000aIn the end, even the accord, which its partners expected would break the deadlock, was met with a frosty reception by friends and foes alike. As the final whistle blew at the end of extra time, the stock of carbon dioxide (CO {-2}) in the air had gone up by about 42,000 tonnes. The delegates carried home a self-consoling resolution to work for a \u2018legally binding agreement' next year.\u000a\u000aTo understand the wide discord and the limited accord in Copenhagen, we need to look at the US, to any global climate agreement. The stated stance of the US has always been that it cannot join any global agreement which stood little chance of being ratified by its Congress.\u000a\u000aIn the 1990s, the Clinton administration had to go back on its commitment to join the Kyoto Protocol as it got the stick in the Senate for having made a commitment in anticipation of Senate approval. The Bush years saw no progress on the climate front and expectedly, Kyoto languished.\u000a\u000aThe US move\u000a\u000aHence, Mr Obama took care to have the \u201cAmerican Clean Energy and Security Act of 2009\u201d (known as the Waxman-Markey Bill) passed by the House of Representatives in May 2009. This has been followed up by the Bill on \u201cClean Energy Jobs and American Power Act\u201d (known as the Kerry-Boxer Bill), now before the Senate. The Senate Bill is only a variation in name but the objects are the same. It was quite clear months ago that the US Senate, for the reason that it was preoccupied with healthcare legislation, would not be taking up the Climate Bill for discussion before spring 2010 and hence the measure may, at best, secure Presidential assent and enter the statute book only in mid-2010.\u000a\u000aThe course of US climate action till 2050 is cast in the Senate legislation. The legislation, if we are to go by the draft Bill available, would, at best, reduce US emissions by a mere 20 per cent from 2005 levels by 2020 which translates to a paltry 4 per cent reduction from 1990 levels. Though the target for 2050 is kept at an impressive 83 per cent reduction compared to 2005, the US initiative has neither pleased the EU nor the developing countries which seek a minimum target of anything between 25 per cent and 40 per cent reduction to be achieved by the US by 2020. The US, clearly, is unable to agree to any such targets which it considers unrealistic and which would, in any way, hurt US economy badly.\u000a\u000aThe passage of the Bill in the House of Representatives was rough enough. A rougher path lies ahead in the Senate. The Senate would not approve of even the insignificant emission reduction targets the Bill has set out for the short and medium terms unless it is sure that the US can bring the new economic powerhouses called BASIC under an international emission control regime.\u000a\u000aHence, the US has been pursuing a two-track approach in its climate diplomacy in the last few months. One was to bring the EU around to giving up the Kyoto Protocol with its mandatory approach to emission reductions with allocated targets and instead have a new compact with voluntary targets set by each country based on its special circumstances. Strong allies like Japan and Canada which would like to wriggle out of Kyoto lend support to the US.\u000a\u000aThe second move of the US has been to soften up BASIC with the demand for time bound emission reductions on their part on the ground that they have emerged as significant emitters since the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC) 1992 was adopted. In fact, China is now the top emitter surpassing the US.\u000a\u000aIn the years to come, the developing countries would account for a substantial part of global emissions of greenhouse gases. Therefore, the US argument goes, major emitters like BASIC cannot ride on the exemption given to them in the UNFCCC and hide behind the poor. They have to discharge their \u201cdifferentiated responsibility\u201d in keeping with their emission volumes.\u000a\u000aThe US has assiduously spread the notion around that unless a major emitter like China and other members of BASIC took active steps to reduce emissions, the efforts of the developed countries would not be of much avail in achieving global reductions of the order needed to limit warming to a level of 2 {+o} Celsius above pre-industrial levels. The idea was to paint these newly industrialising countries into a corner, especially before the least developed and the most threatened by climate change like the small island states.\u000a\u000aBASIC targets\u000a\u000aTo avoid being held up as bad boys before the world community, BASIC started announcing their individual, voluntary targets for reducing the energy intensities of their economic growth. This differs from direct emission reduction in that total emissions of a country can continue to grow but the rate of growth of emissions as its economy progresses would slow down.\u000a\u000aChina announced a target of 40-45 per cent reduction in emission intensity compared to 2005 levels by 2020, and India 20-25 per cent. BASIC , however, would not like to have any restrictions on when they would reach the peak of their emissions, definitely not by 2015 or 2020 as demanded by the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC). What they needed was a recognition of their imperative of economic growth with passable concern for climate.\u000a\u000aGiven the above background it was not too difficult for the US to secure the Copenhagen Accord. The US knew that once it achieved an agreement, however general, with BASIC, that would form the basis for the rest of the world to work on. No wonder an African delegate later called the agreement a \u201ctemplate\u201d for future negotiations.\u000a\u000aMain points in deal\u000a\u000aThe main points of the Copenhagen Accord are:\u000a\u000aA global goal to reduce worldwide emissions by 50 per cent by mid-century;\u000a\u000aDeveloped countries to set their emission targets by February 2010 and developing countries to list their actions;\u000a\u000aAdherence to targets by developed countries would be subject to international monitoring;\u000a\u000aActions of developing countries supported by external assistance would be subject to external monitoring and verification;\u000a\u000aActions of developing countries supported locally shall be monitored and verified locally in accordance with international consultations and analysis without impinging on the sovereignty of nations\u000a\u000aLong-term funding to the tune of $100 million per year by 2020 and making available $10 million per year for short-term funding from 2010 to the poorest and most vulnerable to climate change; and\u000a\u000aA review of the overall agreement in 2016.\u000a\u000aThe US administration has got what it wants to satisfy a demanding Senate, namely, no targets imposed from outside on the US and BASIC falling in line with the developed countries by accepting a climate discipline, though slightly different from what the US would have wished for. The second part, in particular, should please the Senators and US industry because fears of energy intensive US goods getting priced out by cheaper imports from BASIC now stand dispelled.\u000a\u000aIt has been win-win for the US. BASIC should also be satisfied with the Accord as they have been able to retain their cherished \u201cdifferentiated responsibility\u201d without much damage to their long-term energy plans and independence from outside agencies prying on their self-supported actions.\u000a\u000aThe Accord, most importantly for them, is not legally binding, though in the words of Mr Yvo de Boer, the Chief of the Climate Secretariat, it is \u201cpolitically incredibly significant\u201d.\u000a\u000aIn the end, well past midnight, exhausted and exasperated delegates decided to \u201ctake note\u201d of the Accord in their future parleys in 2010 to arrive at, hopefully, a legally binding document. Let's wait for the screen to go up for Act Two.\u000a\u000aRelated Stories:\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 22, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
