aVScience is nothing but developed perception, interpreted intent, common sense rounded out and minutely articulated, noted the philosopher George Santayana, musing on modernity and progress. That was then, when the ill-effects of fossil-fuel usage, consequent emission of gaseous carbon and resultant global warming was not quite apparent.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aFast forward to the here and now, and it would seem that last week's global summit on climate change was in effect a rather damp squib. The Copenhagen Accord does elaborate on a dozen clauses and intent, but appears short on the actual specifics of mitigation action.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBut it would be plain short-sighted not to read between the lines and note the paradigm shift in the offing on climate action, the world over. The coming decade is likely to see rapid and stepped up mitigation action like never before.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe relative prices of conventional fuels like petroleum would likely rise over the medium term, and so incentivise mitigation action and 'green' solutions right across the energy economy and beyond. The point is that for various reasons and parallel developments, the economics of business-as-usual on global warming is just no longer attractive or paying. Hence the need for proactivity.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt is true that there's as yet no firm commitments on emission reduction by the developed economies read Annexure 1 Parties. Also, a panoply of operational issues in activating the Green Climate Fund for developing economies read non-Annex 1 Parties and the attendant Technology Mechanism, remain to be addressed. But the fact of the matter is that greener solutions in the emissions-intensive energy economy are beginning to gather a momentum of their own.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aMore important, the green systems now in the cards are likely to be economically attractive and with real possibilities of revving up energy efficiency at 'negative or zero net cost'. Hence the need for domestic policy action.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aHere in India, what's needed is a quantum increase in energy supply going forward. Further, we need more wheels and better transport infrastructure to keep up the economic growth momentum. Additionally, we have a massive backlog in real estate, housing and, generally speaking, built spaces. And given the energy shortages on the ground and poor usage, it cannot be gainsaid that we need proactive policy in place to boost efficiency in energy generation and supply, and purposefully tap non-conventionally energy sources as well.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt is disappointing that the summit led to no big deal and ended as it had begun, taking on the appearance of a huge talking shop. Nevertheless we do need to access novel super-critical boiler technologies and the like in energy generation, to significantly improve thermal efficiency in our power plants. It would mean producing much more power without any proportionate use in the fuel source. The speedy diffusion of such efficiency enhancing measures would pay rich dividends, for years. Better still, it's entirely possible that by learning by doing and using, we would foray into ultra super-critical boiler technology, for added efficiency improvement.\u000a\u000a
