aVMembers of the farmers' team watching the video on'The People's Coalition on Climate Change' led by theDeccan Development Society of Hyderabad during a pressmeet in Hyderabad. - K. Ramesh Babu\u000a\u000aAmit Mitra\u000a\u000aHyderabad, Dec. 24\u000a\u000aMasanagari Narsamma, a woman farmer from an obscure village in the semi-arid Zaheerabad region of Medak district in Andhra Pradesh, cannot spell Copenhagen or greenhouse effect.\u000a\u000aBut, when different countries were slugging it out at Copenhagen on how to (or who should) save the planet from climate changes, she took centre-stage in one of the public sessions at Bella Center to put across her views on how to heal the planet in her own bucolic Telugu.\u000a\u000aNarsamma and 20-odd farmers from across different regions in India were in Copenhagen as part of a team led by an NGO, Peoples Coalition on Climate Change, to share their experience of healthy and sustainable agricultural practices that can help clean the earth.\u000a\u000aThe team of farmers were drawn from different ecosystems, such as the arid ecosystem of Bhimora in Gujarat (Maldharis), Chilka Lake in Orissa having a coastal ecosystem, Paravas and Murhurayar fishing community from the Gulf of Mannar, Tamil Nadu, Chakhesang Naga tribes from Nagaland, fishermen-farmers from Sundarbans, Baiga tribe from Baigachak, Chhattisgarh and Santhals from Jharkhand.\u000a\u000aBack home, Narsamma relates her Copenhagen experience. \u201cI told the session in my own Telugu (which was translated) how we raise several varieties of crops and vegetables, most of which withstand climatic challenges. Especially crops such as millets, paddy, yam, sweet potato and banana grow well in dry and drought like conditions. Our jhums, Bewars and Podus have foundations of knowledge systems that are millennial old,\u201d she recalls.\u000a\u000aThe practice of shifting cultivation such as Bewar is known to enable farmers to grow and harvest 12 crops, 16 vegetables, 21 leafy eatable items and more than 17 grasses for their local food and seed requirement. \u201cThe traditional crops that we grow on our hills and semi-arid tracts can also fix carbon in the soil, helping us combat the climate crisis. The range of saline tolerant paddy varieties and other local crops for various ranges of salinity are our shield against the climate threats,\u201d she says.\u000a\u000aBut how was the response? \u201cWe actually got the chance to speak at two public events during the (Copenhagen) meet. But, the response was sadly not as good as we expected. Perhaps we were talking in a different language or maybe approaching the problem from a different perspective,\u201d says another farmer Tammali Manjula. Added Narsamma with a glint of triumph in her eyes: \u201cOn the last day of the meet, we collectively burnt our (participation) badges to convey our hurt sentiments.\u201d\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 25, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
