aVFactors such as decline in snowfall and fall in minimum temperature in the winter months over the last few years are posing serious threats to apple production in Himachal Pradesh. The hill state earns a considerable portion of its revenue from apple farming.\u000a\u000aIt, in turn, has started to threaten the Rs 1,500-crore industry in the state. Due to declining trend in production, prices of apple have already started increasing since the last one month.\u000a\u000aA study conducted by agricultural scientists in the key apple growing regions of Himachal Pradesh says that there has been remarkable increase in the area under off-season vegetable cultivation in place of apple cultivation. Decline in area under apple and other fruits was comparatively higher in marginal and small farms, a paper titled Weather Changes-related Shift of Apple Belt in Himachal Pradesh prepared by researchers from Himachal Pradesh Agricultural University, Palampur, has noted.\u000a\u000aThe study was carried out by the Indian Council of Agricultural Researchs network project on impact, adaptation and vulnerability of Indian agriculture to climate change.\u000a\u000aThe study said that productivity of apple has recorded a decrease of about 2% to 3% over the past years and the maximum decline of about 4% was witnessed in marginal farms. It covered key apple growing districts of Kullu, Shimla, Lahual and Spiti representing different elevations with large areas under apple cultivation.\u000a\u000aIn the Lahaul valley, more than 80% of farmers surveyed were of the opinion that reducing snowfall in winter, delay in start of winter, threat of floods in the valley in the last 4-5 years are also the signs of changing climate in the valley, the paper said.\u000a\u000aAn analysis of the last two decades database showed that minimum temperature is decreasing per year during November to April whereas maximum temperature has been showing an increasing trend from November to April. The analysis of rainfall for past 41 years recorded at Kullu district showed 77 mm increase during the period of November to May.\u000a\u000aIncrease in precipitation and decreased snowfall during winter consequently reflected in the low chilling hours in the region. Trend analysis indicated that snowfall is decreasing at the rate of 82.7 mm per annum in the entire region.\u000a\u000aThe apple crop starts flowering during January-February, which is followed by the appearance of small fruits. Apple trees need snowfall because they need moisture for good crop.\u000a\u000aPrices have jumped to Rs 60 per kg in Shimla this year compared with Rs 30-40 in the previous year. Consequently, the retail prices in Delhi are hovering around Rs 90 to Rs 110.\u000a\u000aMeanwhile, due to less snowfall this season, the Himachal Pradesh government has launched a pilot weather insurance scheme for safeguarding interest of apple growers. The Agriculture Insurance Co of India, incorporated in 2002, has launched the scheme in Shimla and Kullu districts. Himachal Pradesh is one of Indias major apple-producing regions, with more than 90% of the produce going to the domestic market. Area under cultivation increased to 94,726 hectare in 2007-08 from 400 hectare in 1960-61.\u000a\u000aApple is a cash crop in Himachal Pradesh and accounts for 46% of the total area under fruit crops and76% of the total fruit production. The crop is grown in most of the districts of the state.
