aVWhen it comes to reflecting our domestic obligation internationally, we have to be careful because we do not want to enter into any agreement which will impose binding obligations on us. \u2014 Mr Jairam Ramesh, Minister of State for Environment and Forests.\u000a\u000aG. Srinivasan\u000a\u000aNew Delhi, Dec. 27\u000a\u000aIn the run-up to the Copenhagen Conference on Climate Change and subsequently, the issue of ushering in a low-carbon growth path without diluting developmental goals of developing economies has taken centre-stage. The Minister of State for Environment and Forests, Mr Jairam Ramesh, accompanied the Prime Minister, Dr Manmohan Singh, to Copenhagen, leading the negotiations with the US President, Mr Barack Obama. With the Accord and especially Mr Ramesh coming under fire from principal Opposition Party led by the leader of the Rajya Sabha, Mr Arun Jaitley, the Environment Minister found time to share his thoughts on the subject with Business Line.\u000a\u000aWith his characteristic frills-free phrases, Mr Ramesh questioned the criticism that the sovereignty of the country was surrendered at Copenhagen, stating that \u201cthere are no self-restraint with us when people say every time you negotiate, don't sell yourself. We are not a tin pot banana republic\u201d.\u000a\u000aIncensed by the invectives, Mr Ramesh says when Mr Yashwant Sinha/Mr Jaswant Singh could subject India to Article IV consultations with IMF for six years and Mr Arun Jaitley to WTO Trade Policy Review when he was Commerce Minister, \u201cwe never accused them of surrendering sovereignty. When you can do consultations on trade policy, on fiscal and monetary policy, why can't you do consultations on environmental policy?\u201d\u000a\u000aExcerpts from Mr Ramesh's observations:The Accord is a small step forward in breaking the deadlock.\u000a\u000aHow the Accord will work itself out, I can't say now because there are negotiations that will continue on the multilateral process. This is an Accord 25 to 30 countries entered into and we hope more countries will become signatories. What the Accord does is to provide a starting-point. This Accord is not a recipe for saving humanity; nor is it a mantra. Every country went there with an intention to save humanity, but the primary purpose was to preserve the national interest in the process.\u000a\u000aFor me, I had only one objective \u2013 to preserve for India the right to economic development. I was not in a position to accept any agreement that imposes restrictions on our developmental agenda. This does not mean that India following prosperity is equal to taking the pollution route.\u000a\u000aWe have a historic opportunity of breaking the prosperity-pollution nexus and that is why we have declared our determination to move in a low-carbon growth strategy.\u000a\u000aThe Planning Commission, in a day or two, will announce the constitution of a Working Group with experts to prepare a roadmap for a low-carbon growth strategy. That is why we announced our emission intensity goal by 20-25 per cent by 2020 on our own on 2005 level.\u000a\u000aI have been saying that we must be aggressive and proactive domestically. But when it comes to reflecting our domestic obligation internationally, we have to be careful because we do not want to enter into any agreement which will impose binding obligations on us.\u000a\u000aI have been advocating strong domestic accountability. That is why I gave a call in September that it is not enough for India to have NAMA \u2013 Nationally Appropriate Mitigation Actions \u2014 as we are a country with no shortage of actions. That is the reason why I gave the concept of Nationally Appropriate Mitigation Outcome (NAMO).\u000a\u000aWe must move from an activity-surplus economy to an outcome-surplus one and nationally accountable is to our Parliament and not to some international organisation.\u000a\u000aI have been saying let us not link our action to international finance and technology. We are in a position to do things on our own. We are investing in supercritical power generation. Why should we say that we will not do this till you give us technology? Nobody will give us technology and we have to negotiate technology because it is in the private domain.\u000a\u000aWe think technology is there to be transferred which is wrong. Given India's size and capability, we can mobilise our resources and let us do things on our own. But if you want us to reflect what we are doing as part of an international agreement, then give us money and technology.\u000a\u000aThe fact is that for 17 years after Rio Convention, we have not really moved on the green energy path. Green energy-led growth is phenomenal business opportunity and in 10 years both Japan and China will be world leaders. So we too must act, as the Indian private sector which has created mobile phone and information technology revolutions can easily create the green-energy revolution.\u000a\u000aFinally, the Accord is a victory for BASIC Group comprising Brazil, China, India and South Africa when it wrested three important benefits from President Obama at Copenhagen. The US gave in to our proposals on global goals and the legally non-binding nature of the Accord. But on monitoring and verification and, in particular, on the US proposal of analysis/ assessment, we said consultations/analysis with the former being done in a manner to respect national sovereignty. This was also accepted.\u000a\u000aRelated Stories:\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated December 28, 2009)\u000a\u000aRelated Related
