aVSustainability has always been an intrinsic part of Tata Chemicals business philosophy. Right from the its inception, the company has been about care and commitment towards all stakeholders. With products and services that touch human lives every day, whether by means of the salt that makes our food tastier or the soda ash that is used to manufacture glass and detergents or the fertilisers that make a farmer smile.\u000a\u000aThe major drivers of our sustainability programmes and actions include climate change, which is to say, GHG emissions and the green manufacturing index. We are concerned about energy and water consumption, solid waste reuse, afforestation and also renewable energy. With respect to our workforce, we are concerned about safety, health and engagement with the community. We are further concerned with the CS Protocol Index, product stewardship and green chemistry investments.\u000a\u000aThe company is a signatory to Responsible Care and has adopted environment sustainability standards of the British Safety Council in its journey towards environmental excellence. ISO 14001:2004 Environment Management System framework supports us towards this.\u000a\u000aResource conservation through reuse, recycling and reduction of wastes and treatment at source is followed in all our manufacturing processes. We further seek to maximise recycling and reuse by innovating. Manufacturing of chemicals and fertilisers involves energy intensive processes that primarily depend on non-renewable energy sources. Solar energy is used for salt evaporation at Mithapur & domestic water heating at Babrala. Application of alternative materials is done in order to conserve energythis includes the maximisation of the use of pet coke in the boilers and anthracite coal in the soda ash lime kiln at Mithapur facility.\u000a\u000aWater management is also one of the areas where our efforts have yielded substantial results. Our facility at Mithapur has achieved 100% reduction in dependence on groundwater in the last three years by adopting various in-house water conservation measures as well as management of the rain-fed lake. Today, we do not draw any groundwater for plant operations. Though our urea-manufacturing process wholly depends on deep aquifer groundwater, which does not affect the water table adversity, specific water consumption here is a benchmark amongst the nitrogenous fertiliser manufacturers. Periodic water level and quality measurements are a part of the quality assurance system of Babrala. Babrala and Haldia fertiliser sections are zero discharge plants and mainly depend on recycled water, while chemical plants are major consumers of raw water.\u000a\u000aWe are continuing our effort that started way back in 1940, through exploiting solar energy in our salt pans to produce salt for our soda ash plant to investing in natural soda ash in Kenya and the US, which helps in the reduction of our energy intensity profile. The fertiliser plant at Babrala is benchmarked as one of the lowest in the world in specific energy consumption. We have utilised our knowledge of chemistry and agriculture to build capacities in biofuels by using alternative and environment-friendly feedstocks like Sweet Sorghum.\u000a\u000aClimate change is one of todays major environmental challenges and Tata Chemicals has established a corporate cell on climate change to respond to the challenge and to develop actions for a low carbon economy. The company is a responsible corporate citizen and monitors its GHG emissions and the corporate cell implements various initiatives for managing climate change. The cell has successfully developed CDM projects and has registered four projects. In April 2008, we undertook internal assessment of CO2 emissions across operations, with guidance by E&Y and McKinsey in accordance with WBSCD Protocol and ISO 14064.\u000a\u000aThe company has already been issued carbon credits for projects registered at UNFCCC. These are mostly related to energy reduction and methane reduction. We are also working on availing carbon credits for biomass fuel for hot air generators, coated urea, biofuels and natural soda ash projects. TCL is a member of the steering committee and working group on climate change formed by Tata Quality Management services for the Tata Group.\u000a\u000aThe company is actively involved in various advocacy forums on climate change and is a member of Teri-CoRE-BCSD, signatory to Global Roundtable on Climate at Earth Institute at Columbia University. It is actively participating in the activities of CII, Bombay Chamber of Commerce, Ficci, FAI and AMAI, IFA and the like on climate change.\u000a\u000aOur continuing focus on the human touch of chemistry and green technologies has been reinforced once again with the introduction of Tata Swatch Water Purifier launched on December 7, 2009. This water purifier does not use any electricity and is economically priced for India.\u000a\u000aThe author is managing director, Tata Chemicals Ltd
