aVWhat is the rationale behind setting up the new centre on low carbon futures?\u000a\u000aWhat is the centre's priority?\u000a\u000aWhat kind of opportunities would the centre offer to academics?\u000a\u000aHow does the centre plan to achieve excellence in terms of research?\u000a\u000aThe centre for low carbon futures , a joint venture of the Universities of York , Sheffield, Leeds and Hull, UK, was launched on January 14. Jon Price, Director of the Centre talks to Tirna RayIt was a necessity that evolved out of a need for collaborative academic research working alongside business to develop low carbon technologies in an academic institutional setting. A joint initiative of the Regional Development Authority (Yorkshire Forward) and the region's universities, the centre will address the questions posed in developing a low carbon future from two complementary perspectives \u2014 life-cycle carbon management and climate change impacts and adaptation.The 50 million UK-based research centre will harness the research power of leading universities both to develop clean technologies and help in the reduction of carbon emissions. The centre sets out to provide a practical solution, providing assistance to regional and international business with the practical application of new technologies into usable products. Clearly, climate change is not just about low carbon technologies, it's also about a change in behaviour \u2014 the way we live in a low carbon society.The centre has already identified the first four pilot research projects covering the regional economics of climate change, low carbon supply chains, bio-renewables and carbon capture technology.It is a multi-disciplined institution, drawing on the social sciences, natural sciences, engineering and economics, which harnesses the firepower from four leading universities of Hull, Leeds, Sheffield and York along with many other higher education institutions in the region. For academics, the centre provides the opportunity to be involved in multi-disciplinary, translational research and training activities with new collaborators from academic, policy and commercial organisations, which will shape the development of a low carbon future within the region and beyond.Also, it will offer scholars and academicians a chance to make an impact with low carbon solutions in society. Meanwhile, the centre can leverage funds from regional, national, European government and research councils. The centre is creating teams of natural scientists, engineers and social scientists, working across traditional boundaries, in a research centre developed in close liaison with private and public sector stakeholders.It will draw on the expertise of world-class researchers in the region as a focal point for understanding and demonstrating how business can evolve and adapt in a low-carbon world. In fact, by conducting 'translational' research into clean technologies, the centre will be a conduit for the practical application of low carbon technologies, helping both to attract inward investment and enhance business growth and economic output.
