aVIntergovernmental Panel on Climate Change\u000a\u000aBANGALORE:(IPCC) has goofed up so badly on its Himalayan glacier melting forecast that it's close to losing credibility among the people. But The Energy and Resources Institute ( TERI ) fellow and climate negotiator Prodipto Ghosh hits back: "If you don't trust scientists, who else will you trust?" From terming the demand for resignation of IPCC head R K Pachauri "knee-jerk" reaction to admitting there is no substantial evidence to prove the extent of glaciers melting, Ghosh tells TOI what went wrong: How could such a goof-up occur?We don't have much data going back in time. The data we have is from the Zoological Survey of India, but it's not sufficient to arrive at any conclusion or any generalization on the state of the Himalayan glaciers. The IPCC problem arose because Prof Hasnain (who first went public that glaciers would disappear by 2035) said there is a rapid decline of glaciers attributing it to climate change. It was not rectified by IPCC. Due diligence was not done, carelessness happens sometimes.There are demands for R K Pachauri's resignation. Will he resign?Pachauri has nothing to do with this. He is not the author of the report. When he spoke about the deadline of glaciers melting, Prof Hasnain was not even with Teri \u2014 he was with JNU. Pachauri has been appointed by governments, not a bunch of people. The issue about his resignation is only a knee-jerk reaction. He will not resign.Do we have any real data at all on the receding Himalayan glaciers?We have data from the Wadia Institute, the Zoological Survey of India, Govind Ballabh Pant Institute of Himalayan Environment and Development which is nearly 50 years old.
