aVNEW DELHI: The US government sees the Copenhagen Accord as the beginning of a diminished role for the formal UNtalks. The chief US negotiator, Jonathan Pershing, was reported stating that US was not confidant of the UN managing the start up finance of US $30 billion the rich countries have offered under the accord."I am not sure that any of us are particularly confident that the UN managing the near-term financing is the right way to go," he was reported saying.His statement made at a think tank meeting came against the backdrop of Cuba taking on the UN Secretary General in very strong words, formally demanding to know what Ban ki-Moon's legal status was to intervene in a biased-fashion in the debate. The UNSG had come under increasing criticism at Copenhagen for reflecting US views on the climate talks and again drawn flack recently for suggesting that each country put its economy-wide targets under the accord, which would turn into a legally binding agreement in future. The BASIC countries, which includes India, had fought hard at the Danish capital to ensure that the contentious accord does not become a legally binding document.While the rich countries have promised in the Copenhagen Accord to mobilize US $30 billion as a start up fund for the most vulnerable countries developing countries have been wary that the funds and other mechanisms could now be managed under less democratic institutions like the G20 (a meeting of which is due in February) or the US-backed Major Economies Forum. Pershing's statement seemed to confirm the apprehensions of the poor countries.India had also agreed to international analysis and consultation on its domestic mitigation actions under the accord. The Copenhagen Accord left it open as to who would determine the guidelines under which such scrutiny would take place. Fears were expressed that with not explicitly mandating that the guidelines would be made under UNFCCC, other forums, tilted in the favour of rich countries could take over the mandate at the cost of the UN Framework Convention onwhich hosts the Kyoto Protocol too.The BASIC countries had already gone back on their earlier red lines at Copenhagen not insisting that all funds foradaptation and mitigation to poor countries come from public finance and routed through the UN. But Pershing's statements in the US further strengthened the suspicion that the give aways had only begun and not ended at Copenhagen and that India could expect to give in more in the hectic negotiations slated for 2010.
