aVOur Bureau\u000a\u000aNew Delhi, Jan. 23\u000a\u000aRuling out his resignation over an error in predicting the melting of Himalayan glaciers by 2035, Mr R.K. Pachauri, head of Inter-Governmental Panel on Climate Change, said that the UN body will use more rigorous research systems in future.\u000a\u000a\u201cI have no intentions of resigning. I have got a task to complete the Fifth Assessment report and I shall do it,\u201d Mr Pachauri told reporters.\u000a\u000aAdmitting that there was a mistake in concluding that Himalayan glaciers would melt by 2035, Mr Pachauri said: \u201cIt was a human error. We will do everything to see that such mistakes were not repeated.\u201d\u000a\u000aHowever, the report's overall conclusions that glaciers in the Himalayan region were receding were still valid.\u000a\u000aThe possibility of more errors in the Fourth Assessment Report was \u201cminimal, if not non-existent\u201d. \u201cOur systems were very robust. All we have to ensure is better implementation,\u201d he said.\u000a\u000aCommenting on IPCC's credibility being impacted in view of the controversy, Mr Pachauri said: \u201cRational people see larger picture. I am confident that world leaders would continue to repose their faith in IPCC and there will be no deviation from that\u201d.\u000a\u000aRejecting allegations that The Energy and Resources Institute (TERI) headed by him had benefitted from the conclusions of the Fourth Assessment Report of IPCC, Mr Pachauri said the focus would now be on bringing out a robust and credible Fifth Assessment Report in the next four years.\u000a\u000aMr Pachauri said that IPCC with its Nobel Prize money has set up a fund to create scientific capabilities to study the impact of climate change especially in the developing countries. \u201cWe are trying to muster support from other sources,\u201d he added.\u000a\u000aWhile stating that there was no research on glacier melting in India, Mr Pachauri said: \u201cWe should make a plan for proper evaluation and calculation of melting of glaciers\u201d.\u000a\u000aRelated Stories:\u000a\u000a(This article was published in the Business Line print edition dated January 24, 2010)\u000a\u000aRelated
