aVNEW DELHI: Diesel, it seems, is tired of playing second fiddle to other fuel variants, looking to trudge up the popularity charts in a cleaner avatar and with some government help.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aDiesel engine and component manufacturers such as Cummins, Bosch and Delphi are showcasing their clean technology wares at the Auto Expo, taking aim at a booming market hammered out by an eco-friendly government. These companies expect big sales in fuel injection systems, exhaust-control apparatuses and advanced engines after 13 cities are to compulsorily embrace the stricter Bharat Stage IV emission standards from this April.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe new government rules mandate a reduction of 80% in particulate matter and 30% in oxides of nitrogen \u2014 the main pollutants in vehicles. Climate change concerns are driving the adoption of diesel applications globally, according to the Society of Indian Automobile Manufacturers (SIAM). Governments worried about burning fossil fuels such as petrol, diesel, CNG and LPG adding to the emission of greenhouse gases, particularly CO 2, are fast turning environment custodians.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aDiesel engines score in an eco-friendly market as they emit 25% less greenhouse gases than a gasoline engine. And when new-generation engines and exhaust treatments combine with clean diesel, which is almost sulphur-free compared to previous blends, emissions are reduced by 95%.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aTaking note, the Indian automobile sector is looking at a 40% diesel penetration by 2013, according to SIAM. "Diesel vehicles are fast shedding their sluggish and rickety tag," says SIAM director-general Dilip Chenoy.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aBut diesel will not replace other fuel variants like CNG and gasoline in a hurry, says Mr Chenoy. Though almost all trucks and buses in India run on diesel, only 17% passenger vehicles are said to have embraced the fuel. That number is going to make a laborious climb of only 2-3 % in the near future while growth will come mostly from commercial vehicles.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aDiesel's uphill journey may look surprising when viewed against the raft of benefits spawned by its engines. Cars running on diesel engines are said to consume 30% less fuel compared to gasoline engines and are also powerful, with around 50% higher degree of torque.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a"Adopting emission standards doesn't mean diesel engines compromise on performance," says Fredrick A, development deputy manager, Bosch. The company's latest product , the Common Rail System, claims to control fuel injections , giving the maximum fuel efficiency along with the lowest emissions. "Diesel is the fuel of today and tomorrow."\u000a\u000aThough no more a fuel-gulping monster or a smoking dinosaur , diesel engines are still a pariah of sorts in India due to the high costs involved. The technological upgrade and pricier components increase the costs of a diesel vehicle by up to 8%.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a"Consumers are still not willing to pay for cleaner fuel despite the many benefits," says Arun Ramachandran, automative business unit vice-president, Cummins.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThough their investments on an average diesel engine have shot up to Rs 30-40 crore, companies are skittish about hiking prices keeping in mind the downturn. That may change when recovery gathers more pace. But companies such as Cummins, which is displaying engines that use the selective catalytic reduction technology, are not overtly worried thanks to the government playing environment disciplinarian . So much so that the company's engines are designed to underperform if "a driver cheats on emission standards" .\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a"Emission standards provide a level playing field for vehicle makers to lower pollutants and ensure a cleaner environment," says Mr Ramachandran, adding that rules are changing in a manner that emissions will soon be fuelneutral.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a"We need to flip our way of thinking for cleanertechnology vehicles to spread," says Mr Ramachandran.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe initial costs are high, but consumers need to keep in mind the 10% fuel savings in just a year as well as the dilution in maintenance costs, he adds.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn any case, the government is watching.
