aVIndia's climate policy is at a crossroads. The Copenhagen Accord has transformed the global climate discourse, fostered new groupings of countries and created a policy vacuum at the global level.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWe now need to develop our vision of a climate constrained future. For eight years after the Rio Conference we were in a state of denial. Seven years ago, when the annual climate conference was held in Delhi, we stated what we will not do \u2014 our per capita emissions will never exceed the developed country average. While our National Action Plan on Climate Change focuses on energy efficiency and demand side management, at Copenhagen we announced targets for reducing carbon intensity of GDP, reflecting an ad-hoc approach to events rather than a strategic vision.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWithin the BASIC group of countries we have the lowest per-capita emissions as well as per-capita GDP, and with a demographic profile that will peak in 2050 some 20 years after the others, we not only have to calibrate our approach with the group's but also shape their collective response in terms of a long-term strategic framework to impact on global trends.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWhile the BASIC group now has the influence to refuse unacceptable deals, it faces the dilemma that it must also be responsive to the concerns of other developing countries, in a situation where its rapid economic growth is perceived by the least developed countries to be at variance with their concerns for adaptation to the adverse effects of climate change. We must project a credible vision with a larger purpose than national self interest to re-establish solidarity amongst developing countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aCurrently there are two distinct but related approaches for dealing with climate change. According to the Centre for European Policy Studies, for the European Union Copenhagen was about the final sharing of the remaining carbon budget of about 1,550 billion tonnes that are left until 2050. The 80% cut collectively in developed country emissions by 2050, while serving as a powerful communication tool, would have fixed their share of the atmospheric space at two tonnes of carbon dioxide equivalent per-capita per year, leaving developing to fight amongst themselves for less than half that amount.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe United States is seeking to legitimise emissions reduction based on the respective capabilities of countries, rather than on their historical responsibilities. In this framework, it would maintain its energy use per capita while developing countries, because of their future economic growth, will have to bear a disproportionate share of the burden.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWe need to develop a third approach to shape the shared vision, rather than just focus on the architecture of the new arrangement. For example, the way legally binding commitments under the Kyoto Protocol are being ignored highlights the limitations of the multilateral system, and we must explore new approaches for long-term cooperation. Similarly, traditional concerns of safeguarding sovereignty need to be revisited while dealing with global concerns, and the review of our actions will not be intrusive if we can restrict the reporting to data elements and fix the benchmark to assess performance as the gap between the tonnes of carbon reduced/avoided and the fair share of the carbon budget for that country.\u000a\u000a
