aVNEW DELHI: The BASIC countries will meet the January 31 deadline to associate with the Copenhagen accord and submit their voluntary emission reduction actions. In a joint statement, the ministers from Brazil, South Africa, India and China "expressed their intention to communicate information on their voluntary mitigation actions" to the UNFCCC on schedule.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAmong the issues that were considered by the ministers was the letter from UN Secretary General Ban Ki-moon and Danish Prime Minister Lars Locke Rasmussen earlier this month, the notification issued by the UNFCCC secretariat on January 18 and the implications of the Copenhagen Agreement.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe New Delhi meeting took place amidst calls for converting the Copenhagen Accord into a legally binding agreement by the European Union. Apprehensions that the Copenhagen Accord would supplant the existing process were only strengthened by the UN Secretary General's letter.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aMr Ban Ki-moon and Mr Rasmussen described the Accord as an "essential first step in a process leading to a robust international climate change treaty." Though clarifications had been sought and provided by the UN, which described the Accord as a "political document", the BASIC countries chose a cautious path.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe BASIC countries did not reject the Copenhagen Accord \u2014 they were key players in its framing \u2014 but there appeared to be some unease with the future trajectory that this text may make. The ministers "underscored the centrality of the UNFCCC process and the decision of the parties to carry forward the negotiations on the two-track of ad hoc working groups."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThis emphasis on the centrality of the UNFCCC comes on the heels on suggestions by European Union to make the Accord legally binding. "All four countries played a crucial role in finalising support the Copenhagen Accord. The unanimous view was that the value of the Accord was not as a stand alone document but as input to the two track negotiation process under the UNFCCC", Mr Jairam Ramesh said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe joint statement issued at the end of the day long meeting called for convening of the two negotiating groups \u2014 the Kyoto and the Bali tacks \u2014 by March 2010. They also said that there should be at least six meetings of the negotiating groups prior to the conference in Mexico in December 2010. This, the ministers said, "would help for a successful conclusion in Mexico". What would constitute a "successful conclusion to ongoing negotiations" was not clear.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aApprehension that the Copenhagen Accord could supplant the UNFCCC process could be the reason why the BASIC did not canvass the Accord to other countries. In doing so, it disregarded UN Secretary General and Danish PM letter which asked countries to make "efforts with regional and negotiating groups...to encourage support for the Accord."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe limited operationalisation of the Accord, as was abundantly clear from the notification issued by the UNFCCC, the BASIC countries stressed on the issue of finance.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a"The proof of commitment of rich countries will be if the $10 billion actually flows to small island states, Africa, less developed countries in 2010. If it doesn't happen that would mean they are not serious. The $10 billion promise is one that the BASIC can't keep for them," Mr Ramesh said.\u000a\u000aClearly, the BASIC countries sought to sent out the message that they would use their position of dialogue to pressure the developed countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aAs part of its effort to mend bridges with the G-77, the ministers stressed that the BASIC was not a negotiation bloc, instead it was a "strategic platform to reflect and strategise on negotiations".
