aVThe evolution of the policy framework for renewable energy dovetails dual national considerations: the need to enhance energy availability for rapid growth, and mitigating impact of climate change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe policy thrust for rapid energy growth has been built over the past two decades as the country embarked on the path of rapid economic growth.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn recent years, specific to the growing concerns on climate change, the government has released the National Action Plan on Climate Change (NAPCC), comprising eight National Missions \u2014 in specific areas of solar energy, enhanced energy efficiency, sustainable habitat, and water, sustaining the Himalayan ecosystem, Green India, sustainable agriculture and strategic knowledge for climate change \u2014 representing multi-pronged, long-term and integrated strategies for achieving key goals in the context of climate change.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aSimultaneously, the government has embarked on the roadmap for tax reforms, involving the introduction of the goods and services tax and the new direct taxes code. The alignment of these policies for energy growth, climate change and fiscal framework is critical for effective and sustainable growth.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe developments so far: The renewable energy potential (excluding solar) is estimated at 90,000 mw for energy / power generation \u2014 India proposes to leverage 50% (i.e., 15,000 mw during each Plan period) of the potential over the next three Plans.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aTo foster country's economic development led by clean and energy-efficient fuels, there is a need to gradually shift its dependence of energy from fossil fuels to non-fossil fuels comprising solar, wind, hydro, biomass, fuel wood, hydrogen, fuel cells, tidal, geo-thermal, etc.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn the initial years, the policy thrust for renewable energy was delivered primarily by fiscal incentives. In the 1990s, tax holidays and accelerated tax depreciation was introduced that has predominantly provided impetus to the growth of the wind energy capacity in the country.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aCurrently, renewable energy has a 9% share of the country's installed power generation capacity, with wind energy accounting for 70% of the total installed renewable energy generation capacity. The balance is being contributed by small hydro, grid and off-grid solar, co-generation, biomass, urban and industrial waste.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aSince the initial years, the scale and size of the energy demand and the imperatives for renewable energy have undergone a paradigm shift. This is coupled with the profound technology breakthroughs in the previous decade, along with heightened concerns on the emission of greenhouse gases by traditional energy options.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aTo address the opportunities from new technologies and thinking and challenges from climate change, the government in the recent years has revamped the regulatory framework for these sectors, comprising of the following:\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a*Creating Bureau of Energy Efficiency to promote energy-efficiency,\u000a\u000a*New and improved tariff regulations for procurement of energy from renewable sources,\u000a\u000a*Generation-based incentive schemes for solar and wind, and\u000a\u000a*Obligation for renewable energy purchase and creation of platform for trading in renewable energy certificates.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a
