aVTwo years after it was conceived, the National Solar Mission, which can address problems of India's energy security as well as climate change, was on Monday officially launched, with Prime Minister Manmohan Singh giving his full backing to\u000a\u000athe ambitious targets to harness solar energy in the next one decade.\u000a\u000aThe programme, which figures as one of the eight missions in India's National Action Plan on Climate Change, seeks to generate 20,000 MW of electricity through solar energy by the end of 13th Five-Year Plan in 2022. "I do sincerely believe that the target is doable and that we should work single-mindedly to achieve it as a priority national endeavour," Manmohan Singh said at\u000a\u000athe launch.\u000a\u000a"Its success has the potential of transforming India's energy prospects, and contributing also to national as well as global efforts to combat climate change."\u000a\u000aThe Prime Minister said technological innovation would be the key factor in ensuring the success of the mission and appealed to the business houses to promote research and development\u000a\u000ain this area.\u000a\u000a"The role of industry in this mission's success will be critical. Eventually, if the ambitious roll out of the mission is to become a living reality, we will have to create many 'solar valleys' on the lines of the Silicon Valleys that are spurring our IT industry across the four corners of our country," he said.\u000a\u000aThe three-phased project aims to generate 1,000 MW of electricity through solar energy by the next three years, and an additional 3,000 MW in the minimum by the year 2017.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Narendra Modi a monster, Trinamool has pact with him: Buddha\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
