aVWith an aim to increase awareness about efficient use of energy, the Ministry of New and Renewable Energy and the Chandigarh-Punjab Chapter of the Indian Institute of Architects (IIA) organised a symposium on urban sustainability and green buildings at Government Museum and Art Gallery, Sector 10, Chandigarh on Sunday.\u000a\u000aThe event was part of an awareness programme by the Ministry of New and Renewable Energy, which is providing technical and financial support to all states for implementation of various energy-efficiency projects. The symposium was attended by architects, town planners, engineers and students from across Chandigarh, Punjab and Haryana.\u000a\u000aIIA president Vinay Parlekar, who was the chief guest on the occasion, said: "All around the world, buildings and construction consume a major share of\u000a\u000aglobal energy. There is close connection between our building designs and the increasing energy crisis."\u000a\u000aArchitect Surinder Bagha, chairman of the Chandigarh-Punjab Chapter of IIA, delivered the keynote address.\u000a\u000a"A green building uses less energy, water and natural resources, creates less waste and is healthier for the people in general as compared to a standard building. Various mechanisms should be adopted for reducing power consumption in a bid to combat climate change," said Bagha.\u000a\u000aOther prominent speakers included Architect-Planner Jeet Malhotra who spoke on environmental planning units, Shiva Kishan, chief executive officer of Green Rating for Integrated Habitat Assessment (GRIHA) and engineer R K Kaura, secretary general of Solar Energy Society of India.\u000a\u000aALSO READ A day after, Modi bricks disappear\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
