aVNon-vegetarian waste, vegetable leftovers and kitchen garbage are all set to become productive.\u000a\u000aThe Delhi government is roping in the Bhaba Atomic Research Centre (BARC) for three pilot projects under which animal carcass waste matter from the Ghazipur abattoir, canteen waste from the Delhi Secretariat and vegetable leftovers from Azadpur Mandi will be converted into energy. The mixture thus produced will be used to generate biogas, which can be used to produce cooking gas and electricity. The Delhi Technical College, formerly Delhi College of Engineering, will oversee this project.\u000a\u000a"We have decided to set up the three pilot projects. As per our interactions with BARC, the cost of each plant should be around Rs 21 lakh. We have been told that the plant at the Delhi Secretariat should be able to create energy worth Rs 7 to Rs 8 lakh annually. This means we can recover the costs in three years," says Chief Secretary Rakesh Mehta.\u000a\u000aBARC's Plant Pathology and Pesticide Residue department has earlier implemented projects which have converted waste into biogas. "BARC is also running a project wherein power in their campus is generated from waste," Mehta said. BARC scientist Sharad Kale has been asked to make a final presentation on the projects to Chief Minister Sheila Dikshit in February.\u000a\u000aIf successful, the projects are likely to be extended to hotels, temples, canteens and langars.\u000a\u000aThe President's Estate recently began cooking through biogas. Nearly 600 kg cow dung from 54 cows on the Estate is processed in a biogas plant to generate cooking gas  the President's Bodyguard has been using the medium since April 2009.\u000a\u000aEfficient generation of organic and biodegradable animal and vegetable waste is a concern area for Delhi. A carbon mapping report had revealed a staggering 74 kilotonnes of methane, a greenhouse gas, was released in 2008 through the three landfills (Bhalaswa, Ghazipur and Okhla) in Delhi.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Sisodia moves into Mayur Vihar flat\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
