aVPower tends to corrupt, and absolute power corrupts absolutely. Like so many other sayings that have stood the test of time, this one has also seen plenty of exceptions. Not all powerful people or institutions are crooked. Not all the accusations planted against them are creditable. But what remains cross-contextually proper is that powerful people and institutions must be subjected to constant, close scrutiny. And no one can deny that a lot of power is floating around in the climate change orbit today, especially with the stars of the United Nations Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change.\u000a\u000aIn 2007, the Nobel Peace Prize was shared between Al Gore and the IPCC, represented by its chair Rajendra Pachauri. They were being rewarded for their efforts to build up and disseminate greater knowledge about man-made climate change, and to lay the foundations for the measures that are needed to counteract such change. Today, beyond the Nobel, the IPCC has a far-reaching influence on people, policymakers and markets. What kind of cars should people drive and companies manufacture Should all humans switch to vegetarianism What kind of power plants should fuel the global economy Should we work from home instead of putting in time at offices What kind of agriculture can sustain both the planet and its inhabitants IPCC has taken on the mantle of decisively answering a host of questions for not just todays but also tomorrows generations.\u000a\u000aThe global community accepted IPCCs directions because of the belief that the organisation was providing them the best possible scientific advice on climate change, a phenomenon that was so conceptually novel, complex and momentous that traditional, nationalistic policymaking couldnt wing solo solutions. Even the international formulations for trade and suchlike that were already in place desperately needed the guidance of a technically educated mediator. It has been to the credit of the international community that it accepted IPCC as both an indispensable intermediary and an objective representative of science.\u000a\u000aTrouble in paradise\u000a\u000aA London-based newspapers investigations have now forced IPCC to reexamine one of its central research claimsthat climate change will melt most of the Himalayan glaciers by 2035. This claim was part of a benchmark report that claimed to represent the latest and most detailed research on the impact of global warming. Once this claim is retracted, and the IPCC has little room to do otherwise, a lot of its other assertions will also come into dispute. Before getting into the impact of that, lets understand the magnitude of the IPCCs glacier blunder.\u000a\u000aIn its 2007 report on climate change and its impacts, IPCC noted that the Himalayan glaciers form the largest body of ice outside the polar caps and are the source of water for the innumerable rivers that flow across the Indo-Gangetic plains. They form a unique reservoir supporting perennial rivers that represent the lifeline for millions of people, with the Gangetic basin alone being home to 500 million. The report said that Himalayan glaciers were receding faster than in any other part of the world.\u000a\u000aUnder current circumstances, there was a high likelihood posited for their disappearance by 2035 and perhaps sooner.\u000a\u000aWhat has now emerged is that the IPCC warning was based on a news story in the New Scientist. Worse, the popular science journal had published the relevant story eight years before the IPCCs 2007 report. Even worse, the news story was based on a short telephone interview with a scientist who has admitted that his claims were speculative rather than based on any formal research.\u000a\u000aThis raises troubling questions about the IPCCs review process. Every respectable PhD studenteven in the humanities!is taught to trace his or her material back to its source. The peer review process has been created to weed out guesswork. Hearsay is expected to be buried rather than built over, especially by internationally recognised institutions. Extreme claims, whether in the petty cause of self-aggrandisement or the more noble pursuit of human progress, are not expected to make it to the publication stage.\u000a\u000aThe glacier claim broke through all such checks and balances. Whats drawn extra attention to the breach is a) the other controversies that have lately rocked the climate change czars and b) the fact that the Indian environment and forests minister has been diligently drawing attention to the glacier issue since he took office in May 2009.\u000a\u000aTo be fair, the first of the big new scandals had nothing to do with IPCC. Thousands of e-mails and documents were stolen from a server at the University of East Anglias climatic research centre in the UK. A hue and cry over the theft itself soon took a backstage as people actually read the stolen documents. One e-mail had the head of the climatic research unit writing, I cant see either of these papers being in the next IPCC report. Kevin and I will keep them out somehoweven if we have to redefine what the peer-review literature is! Scientists are not always scientific, the leaks cried out loud. This could have been played down as just a simple instance of human idiosyncrasy but for the fact that the IPCC head initially played down the incident, as did Gore. The champions of science didnt do a good job of standing by their cause.\u000a\u000aSince then, questions have been raised about the profit-making motives of the Teri and IPCC head. Whether or not its fair, people in power, especially those who espouse a self-righteous cause, have to repeatedly prove themselves as exemplars. Otherwise the cause takes a beating. The IPCC process has to come across as living up to the best scientific practices. If it lets the horse of public opinion ride away, would it really matter how conscientious it had actually been
