aVNEW DELHI: With Brazil and South Africa informing the UNFCCC of their decision to associate with the Copenhagen Accord, India is now revisiting the issue. Sources said that the "highest levels" of government were considering the whether or not India should associate with the Accord, and the "political costs" of not doing so. India will be consulting China, which has held out on associating with the Accord.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aA senior ministry official said, "we always consult our partners before finalising on our stand." Till now India has sidestepped associating with the Accord, instead pledging its full support. In keeping with the terms of the Copenhagen Accord, India had in a letter dated January 30, to the UNFCCC secretariat submitted its domestic emission reduction figures and fell short of associating with the Accord.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIndia's considering the "political costs" of the decision comes at a time when unlike the US, the United Nations appears to be ready to move forward working on elements of the Accord, such as finance. UN Secretary-General's Climate Change Support Team director Janos Pasztor stressed that finance would not be used as a "stick" to get countries to associate with the Accord. "the Copenhagen Accord is done.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIt is in the past. We must move on," Mr Pasztor said. It would appear that as far as the UN is concerned not associating is unlikely to "cost" India. However, there has been increasing pressure from the United States to associate with the Accord. On Tuesday, US Special Envoy for Climate Change Todd Stern said, "India and China have said something close to that, and I think the UN is just trying to make sure that they understand what the intention is."\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe US made it amply clear that advanced developing countries need to be a part of the Accord. "I think it's important that the major countries be part of it", Mr Stern stressed. Referring to Brazil and South Africa "wish to be associated with the accord", Mr Stern said that "China and India have conveyed something which is not entirely clear. I think that'll get clarified, though, is my guess over the course of the next few days".\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe Americans would like the Accord to remain as a viable option in climate change negotiations, rather than be just an input to the two track process under the UNFCCC. The Accord's viability would be greatly improved if key players in its formulation like India and China were to have their name listed in its preamble. On Tuesday, US Special Envoy for Climate Change Todd Stern made this abundantly clear.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000a"The - going forward this year, I think will be a combination of both of making elements of the accord operational as well as further discussions under the umbrella of the UN Framework Convention toward additional agreements in Mexico," Mr Stern said.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIndia has maintained that it has shown full support for the Accord, and the steps it has taken have been "as good as associating".
