aVNEW DELHI: In a move that could change the dynamics of the climate talks, the executive secretary of the UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, Yvo De Boer, resigned from his post on Thursday. India has already made the first moves to get the Union environment and forests secretary, Vijai Sharma, appointed as the next executive secretary of the UN body.The convention under which the formal negotiations are held is serviced by a secretariat. The secretariat is headed by the executive secretary. The name of the post takes much away from the position of power the seat holds. The position is powerful as at a point of flux the secretariat is able to mould and push decision making as was seen recently in the post-Copenhagen Accord period.De Boer, who is a former Dutch civil servant, was appointed to the post in 2006. The executive secretary for the UNFCCC is nominated by the UN secretary general in consultation with countries member to the convention.A UNFCCC secretariat release on Thursday said that De Boer would serve only till June 1 and not till October when his term expires.His role during the Copenhagen talks had come under cloud with the developing country delegates on several occasions accusing the secretariat of being biased in favour of the European Union. As the talks had progressed the secretariat had found itself sidelined as the US along with the Basic countries -- India, China, South Africa and Brazil -- took charge.As a consequence of the five big players becoming the key to the game, the EU was seen to have lost the most and the secretariat to have lost credibility among negotiators from across the board.De Boer had also come under fire recently from countries like India and China for hardselling the Copenhagen Accord even as the key developing countries opposed hoisting it over the formal UN process.While the government has begun exploring the possibility of putting Vijai Sharma, who has long experience in international environmental issues, in the hot seat, experts point out that the process would need wide international support, including that of the US, the EU and the Chinese, if the proposal has to pass muster. While these are early days in the process, sources said, the government would have to reach out to all the key players to seek support.
