aVNEW DELHI: Differences over India's climate negotiations that contributed to Prime Minister's special envoy Shyam Saran opting out of PMO seem to centre on differing appreciations of what constitutes the "quid pro quo" for India to consider altering its stance on binding commitments.As chief negotiator, Saran was clear that in the absence of any preparedness on part of the developed world to support technology transfer and adaptation or a meaningful fiscal plan India could not dilute its opposition to legally binding emission cuts. A global deal could not retard India's growth but had to be an "additionality" that helped it grow.The former foreign secretary saw himself working within the confines of a brief approved by Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and the cabinet. Any conditionality that slows growth was simply not acceptable politically as it would hurt not the upper crust of India but those who are economically and socially most at risk.While India had not crossed any red line at Copenhagen, the post-summit pressure of developed nations to further blur existing legal commitments while nudging countries like India to accept cuts was bound to increase. Beyond a point, negotiations could not be "popularity contests" and India would have to mark out its territory.While Saran's discomfort with environment minister Jairam Ramesh's "flexibility" mantra was evident, the decision to move on was his own. Saran conveyed this to the Prime Minister who suggested he reconsider. There would be no "embarrassment" over Shiv Shankar Menon becoming national security adviser. Saran would be elevated to MoS rank. Saran explained he felt it was time to get on. "One should know when to walk away," said sources.India's climate negotiations in the next few years would be crucial in terms of wider implications for the economy. Developed nations, reeling under an economic slowdown and viewing emerging economies as likely rivals, were not willing to pass up sale of new technology. They felt nations like China and India could now pay for these while trying to wriggle out of what was agreed at Kyoto and earlier at Rio de Janeiro.With Ramesh having accepted his differences with Saran and stressing the "final say" of the political executive, a replacement for the special envoy is not expected. With the climate negotiating team being recast, it needed to be seen whether it will move to the environment ministry from the PMO. So far, the negotiating team had adopted an intensely debated, but collaborative approach.Ahead of the Copenhagen summit, aware that the meet is part of a process that will settle a new global pecking order, the Indian team had worked to ensure it would not be seen as a hold-out. Formal submissions were made with those on technology innovations being accepted. While India was at risk as a tropical nation and also needed to do its bit, it had to be clear about what was being offered in return for a global binding deal.After three-and-a-half years as special envoy, Saran can look back on a job well done after being initially brought in for the India-US nuclear deal. While at PMO, he also handled the solar mission and infrastructure development along the China border.There was no "offer" to handle ties with China -- former NSA M K Narayanan's charge -- but during his tenure Saran had been more than prepared to deal with whatever came his way. His expertise with Nepal, China and Pakistan were obvious plusses.
