aVNEW DELHI: India's largest natural gas transportation and marketing company Gail India has commissioned its first wind farm in Gujarat and plans to enter into commercial power generation through conventional and non-conventional energy resources.State-owned Gail 's first wind power plant of 4.5 MW capacity at Sinoi in Kutch (Gujarat) will go on-stream by April.The company is also considering to set up two natural gas-based power plants in Usar (Maharastra) and Bettiah (Bihar) each, a Gail official said, requesting anonymity. The capacity of the projects could be between 250 MW and 1,000 MW, he added.Gail chairman & managing director BC Tripathi confirmed that commercial power generation is part of the company's business diversification strategy. "We are evaluating various power projects across the country," he said without disclosing details of proposed projects.Mr Triparti said Gail will also set up solar power plants. "We are focusing on power generation through various non-conventional energy sources ... PM's Solar Mission is one such area," he said.The Rs 4,337-crore mission was launched in November last year under the National Action Plan on Climate Change. The mission aims at generating 1,000 MW solar power by 2013 and 20,000 MW by 2022. Companies setting up solar power projects will get several benefits from the government, such as tax incentives, under the scheme.Suzlon has commissioned Gail's first wind power plant at Sinoi. It has three wind turbine generators of 1.5 MW each. "Power generated from this project will be wheeled for GAIL's captive consumption units in Gujarat. It is expected to meet around 30% of company's power requirements in Gujarat," a Gail official said. Gail will generate power for both captive consumption as well as commercial use, he said.For the proposed gas-based power plants in Usar, Gail has adequate land available at its liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) recovery plant in Ushar. But the project is still at an initial stage. The LPG processing capacity of Usar plant is 1.39 lakh tonne per annum.The company is also considering a proposal to set up 250-300 MW power plant in Bettiah, which will be fuelled by gas supplied through its 876 km Jagdishpur-Haldia natural gas pipeline which will pass through Uttar Pradesh, Bihar, Jharkhand and West Bengal.
