aVNEW DELHI: With BASIC countries \u2014 Brazil, South Africa, India and China \u2014 emerging as an influential grouping in climate change negotiations, Mexico, Argentina and Indonesia have expressed interest in associating themselves with the group. But the April meeting of BASIC, which to be held in Cape Town is unlikely to broaden the alliance.Sources said that Brazil and China have indicated that they are not keen on having either Mexico or Argentina participate in BASIC meetings. A senior Indian government functionary said that there has been no formal discussion among BASIC countries on this issue. However, the general sense is that they are not keen on the idea.The growing interest in BASIC comes on the back of the crucial role that the group of four played in climate negotiations in Copenhagen . A source close to the development said that China was not keen on Indonesia and Mexico's participation because of their proximity to the United States. India, too, is unlikely to be eager to include Mexico in the group as there were differences on key issues such as finance.Mexico had formally proposed that all countries contribute to a global fund while India is clear that finances have to be provided by industrialised countries.In the immediate aftermath of the December summit, apprehensions were expressed that the four "advanced developing countries" had broken ranks with the G-77 and struck out on their own.At their post-Copenhagen meeting in January, BASIC countries stressed that they are part of the G-77 and that BASIC was merely a platform for strategising and not taking decisions. Making it clear that the four country group was part of the G-77, they stressed that the G-77 chair was always part of BASIC meetings.The need to ensure that right signals are sent out have become greater as the chairmanship of the G-77 is now with Yemen. A gravitation of countries to BASIC could undermine the G-77 chair, which is seen as weaker than its predecessor Sudan, and consequently weaken the 132 developing country grouping.If the BASIC becomes the grouping of the more advanced developing countries, it is likely to lead to greater rifts within the G-77.As in earlier climate summits, in Copenhagen there was a clear attempt to split the developing world by positing the small island states and the less developed countries against the other developing countries. BASIC needs to retain its key position within the G-77 if it has to successfully leverage its negotiating space.Senior negotiators suggest that including countries like Mexico, Argentina and Indonesia in the BASIC would only serve to weaken it. "None of these three countries have as geo-political clout as the four constituents of the BASIC. There appears to be no advantage in including these countries," a senior negotiator said.
