aVAs the world works to a global climate deal in Cancun later this year, advanced developing countries like India will come under increasing pressure to commit to higher targets to reduce greenhouse gas emissions than these countries have put on the table.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aWhile the industrialised countries are understood to be responsible for the stock of greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions created during the first 200 years of industrialisation, the developing countries with fast-growing economies are expected to increasingly contribute to the flow or current emissions.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe pressure on these economies would be to limit their emissions in the imminent future, in a bid to keep global emissions at safe levels. This would require working out an effort or burden sharing formula, which would decide the steps taken by different countries as well has how much finance and technology is provided to developing countries.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aPressures are likely to increase, as the Copenhagen Accord acknowledges the need to limit global average temperature to 2 degrees Celsius above pre-industrial temperature.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn accepting the temperature threshold as a guiding principle, the world has also accepted that a limit has been set on the total global carbon emission. Experts say that carbon budget between 1990 and 2100 is at 1800 giga tonne (GT) of carbon dioxide equivalent. With global emissions on the rise since 1990, the net cumulative carbon budget between 2009 and 2100 is limited to 870 GT of carbon dioxide equivalent.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aEmission between 2000 and 2006 was at around 234 GT, and assuming constant rate of 36.3 GT per year, the existing carbon budget could be exhausted anywhere between 2024 and 2039. To ensure that the world does not have to contend with the adverse impacts of climate change, it is important that GHG emissions are limited to this budget.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe developing countries, whose primary goal is development, have to operate within the constraints of a limited carbon budget. Given that unlike the West, the developing world has to operate in this constrained scenario, the model of development that is adopted will be critical to the occupation of the carbon space.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe debate over which model should India choose while deciding on burden sharing gives India two pathways. The first, low carbon development pathway, where development is decoupled from emissions. Using renewable, developing countries are able to occupy negligible carbon space and yet develop.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aIn this scenario as low carbon development technology is expensive, the developed world provides technology and finance to move to a low carbon development model. This would mean that the developing world would ask for a small share of the carbon space, allowing the rich countries to occupy it.\u000a\u000a\u000a\u000aThe second is the per capita convergence model where carbon space is let go of by developed countries and then developing countries occupy this space. In the meantime, developed countries would go on a zero carbon emission pathway where they will use renewable energy and energy efficiency measures which will lead to reduction in the price of green technology.\u000a\u000a
