aVMore than a month after the end of the initial January 31 deadline, India has finally decided to formally associate itself with the Copenhagen Accord, a political statement that was the only outcome of the climate change conference in the Danish capital last December and one that New Delhi had played a key role in finalising.\u000a\u000aAlmost simultaneously, China  another major developing country which had been holding back from explicitly supporting the Accord  also informed the UN climate convention that it was willing to associate itself with the Copenhagen Accord.\u000a\u000aA formal declaration of association with the Accord by all the participating countries had become essential since the climate change conference at Copenhagen had only taken note of the presence of this political document and could not adopt it as the formal outcome.\u000a\u000a"On February 3, 2010, India received a letter from the Executive Secretary of the UNFCCC (UN Framework Convention on Climate Change) asking whether India wishes to be listed in the Chapeau (preamble) of the Copenhagen Accord. Listing in the Chapeau of the Accord implies that we participated in the negotiations on Copenhagen Accord and that we stand by the Accord. After careful consideration, India has agreed to such a listing," Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh told Parliament on Tuesday.\u000a\u000aThe letter that Ramesh referred to had come after India did not explicitly mention its support to the Copenhagen Accord in the communication it had sent informing the UNFCCC about the steps that it was planning to take to reduce the growth of its greenhouse gas emissions. These steps are supposed to become part of the Annexure to the Copenhagen Accord.\u000a\u000aLike India, China had also refrained from mentioning the Accord in its earlier communication. But like India again, Beijing on Tuesday informed the UNFCCC that it was ready to be included in the Chapeau of the Accord now.\u000a\u000a... contd.\u000a\u000aALSO 