aVNEW DELHI: The power ministry may be the government's main instrument for implementing measures to reduce carbon emissions and improve efficiency in the energy sector but a group of experts put together by the Planning Commission to prepare a roadmap to turn the country on a low carbon growth pathway has left out the ministry, much to the chagrin of power minister Sushilkumar Shinde.In a letter to plan panel deputy chairman Montek Singh Ahluwalia, Shinde pointed out that the omission -- "perhaps inadvertently" -- may hamper the panel from doing justice to its objectives. The panel, under the chairmanship of Kirit Parikh, is to suggest suitable legislation, rules and policies for turning India into a low-carbon economy. It is to do so after reviewing existing studies and conduct fresh ones for reducing emissions.Shinde said the ministry's input was vital for formulating green legislation or policies. "The ministry, based on the knowledge and overview of the sector, would be able to highlight concerns relevant to the sector during formulation of the strategy for low-carbon economy," he said. The minister, however, acknowledged that the panel included two of his ministry's technical bodies -- Bureau of Energy Efficiency and the Central Electricity Authority.The power sector accounts for nearly 60% of carbon emissions as nearly two-thirds of electricity is generated by coal-burning plants in the country. The ministry is spearheading several initiatives such as preparing ground for trading in energy efficiency certificates and induction of clean-coal and `super-critical' power plant technologies.Shinde said his ministry believed that emissions in the energy sector could be reduced by 10-15% by 2021-22, provided the projections in capacity addition of hydro power, gas-fired plants, nuclear energy, solar and other renewable sources were met. This could happen only if pertinent or concerned ministries such as petroleum, environment and renewable resources played a proactive role in their respective spheres.
