aVChina on Wednesday said it would work closely with India in future negotiations on Climate Change and is keen to step up cooperation with New Delhi in areas of forestry, energy efficiency and renewable energy.\u000a\u000aThe two countries had yesterday formally backed the Climate Change Accord hammered out in Copenhagen last year calling for voluntary cut in greenhouse gas emissions.\u000a\u000a"In future negotiations and cooperation on climate change, we will continue to be good partners. The government of India and China have signed an MOU enhancing our climate partnership," Xie Zhenhua, top Chinese Climate negotiator, told a news conference here.\u000a\u000aHe said the two countries have conducted policy dialogue and consultations very frequently between China and India. "We are willing to step up cooperation in the areas of forestry, energy efficiency and renewable energy (with India)," he said in reply to a question.\u000a\u000aHe said China and India would continue their cooperation at the negotiations being held by ad-hoc groups to reach a deal at the next climate conference to be held in Mexico.\u000a\u000aIndia, China, Brazil and South Africa brokered a deal at the Copenhagen Climate Summit that calls for limiting warming to two degree Celsius and commits rich countries to provide USD 100 billion to developing countries besides USD 30 billion to the poorest and most vulnerable countries in the next three years to fight climate change.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Islamists rally in Egypt ahead of referendum vote, 3 killed\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
