aVA first-of-its-kind assessment of the impact of climate change on agriculture, health, water and forests on four major terrains of India will be released to the public in May, Union Minister for Environment and Forests Jairam Ramesh announced at IIT-Bombay on Saturday.\u000a\u000aThe study, called 4-by-4 assessment, will evaluate the official climate data across the country since 2007 in the Western Ghats, the coastal regions, the Himalayan terrain and the North-East. "Climate change is for real and no country is more vulnerable to it as India," Ramesh, who was interacting with students and faculty at his alma mater, said.\u000a\u000aHowever, he said the latest year of official data on greenhouse gases available here was 1994. "Now on, we will release an annual 4-by-4 assessment based on Indian monitoring," he said.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Despite notices to housing societies, BMC yet to provide waste collection vehicles\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
