aVBetween 1950 and 2004, the Indian roads sector has grown at an average annual rate of 4.64%, whereas motor vehicles have grown at a rate of 10.94%. Several indicators on roads and roads transport indicate that India is far behind other emerging countries. The government is aware of the mismatch between demand and supply of roads. As a result, road development has become the highest priority of the Government of India, with 79% of the Eleventh Five Year Plan infrastructure budget being allocated to the roads sector.\u000a\u000aThe fact that we are falling behind our road building targets is a story for another day. Another statistic of interest to our story here is that India is the fourth largest emitter of carbon dioxide emissions in the world, but its per-capita emissions are very low. Transport sector is the second-largest sector contributor to carbon dioxide emissions in India. We can always choose to be sceptical about global warming forecasts, but the ironical part about climate change is that if the average temperature in the world actually increases, we will bear the burden of those changes and not the developed countries.\u000a\u000aWe have two paths open to us in our road building endeavours. One is the business-as-usual path or we can take the less travelled routebuilding a green road network. It is important to make an optimum decision at the outset, as we are going to be locked into that investment for a substantial period of time. Further, as the US is discovering, it is very difficult and costly to change habits and overhaul infrastructure from top to bottom.\u000a\u000aBuilding a green road network involves both changes in attitudes and planning right at the beginning. I want to illustrate my point about changes in attitudes using the Delhi road network. For example, if you want to signal that you belong to the higher social class in Delhi, what do you do - buy cars, bigger the better. The fact that Delhi drivers think they are James Deanrebels without a causeonly adds to the traffic woes.\u000a\u000aObviously, it does not help the cause of a green road transport network if the public transportation system sucks. As a result, people are forced to buy cars as a mode of transportation. Then people choose to travel alone in their cars, which add to the jam. Instead, carpooling needs to be encouraged by the government as a sensible, green practice. Carpooling reduces our carbon footprint in this world (and increases mental peace since one is not driving and cursing). Even non-regular users are forced to buy cars, occupying scarce parking space. Maybe we can adopt the concept of Zipcar, like in big cities in the US. In the Zipcar, one can rent a car for a few hours. Perhaps, the Zipcar in India can come with a driver. As a further disincentive for driving, the Indian government is thinking of imposing congestion fees. Secondly, we need to think about roads and roads transport in a holistic framework. They are two separate sectors, but joined at the hip. Using the Delhi urban roads as an example, building roads should be part of an urban planning process.\u000a\u000aLet us think about the new urban planning, now so popular in the West. That concept is nothing but re-discovering the co-existence of residence and markets. That means one does not have to take the car to go grocery shopping every time. In India, we already have that in existence, in an informal manner. Perhaps we can make it formal. We do not have to make separate trips to home and then shops. We can just stop in the market on the way to home. The convenience of buying groceries from the carts is irreplaceable.\u000a\u000aComing to markets, there is very little provision for parking or for people selling fruits and vegetables on the carts. Everybody just mills about on the main roads with cars parked everywhere and one tries to get through the traffic without hitting or getting hit by somebody. We may want to develop a model for markets that takes into account local habits and above concerns.\u000a\u000aRoads also need footpaths where pedestrians can walk. Unfortunately, most of the cars are typically parked on the footpaths, resulting in the pedestrians and bicyclists using one lane. It is so clogged up that people prefer to bring cars because it is impossible to walk or cross roads, resulting in more jams! If we had paid parking on streets, regulations for building parking inside houses and congestion fees, this scenario might change.\u000a\u000aWhile designing roads, we may want to think about incorporating traffic lights in our designs or anything that will make it easier for pedestrians to cross roads. The idea is that people should choose to walk to their neighbourhood markets rather than drive to them. Or, if people are picking up groceries on the way home, they should be able to do so conveniently without creating traffic jams.\u000a\u000aMost important, we may want to introduce speed limits within roads. That may bring security to neighbourhoods petrified of speeding cars. As a result, some of the inner streets may be opened up. The inner streets may only be opened in a selective manner to small vehicles like two-wheelers, auto-rickshaws and non-motorised traffic. All these may result in taking the pressure off the main streets.\u000a\u000aA sustainable road network in India will connect people smoothly without people always worrying whether this is their last day on earth every time they venture out on the roads. It will encourage people to walk or cycle short distances and use public transport or cars for long distances.\u000a\u000aFor that we need good quality roads that are well-maintained. However, road building activity may not be just limited to laying the roads and maintaining them, but also building footpath, subways, traffic lights, etc. Further, it also involves building market places thinking of Indian habits. A good green road network also involves making rules for driving on the roads, which cause minimal losses to human life, national income and our environment. It is necessary to ensure that the traffic rules are implemented. Perhaps technology can play a part in that.\u000a\u000aWe can also continue on the business-as-usual path. The problem is that with the rapid rise in the number of motor vehicles and scarce land, residents face trade-offs like the need to convert public parks to public parking places in the future. The Indian public at least should think about the options, the costs and benefits associated with each path of road building. Unfortunately, climate change is not fair, but hard choices will have to be made. It will be either now or in the future.\u000a\u000aThe writer is Fellow, NCAER. The views expressed are personal
