aVNEW DELHI: If the climate talks weren't already confounding enough and full of intrigue for the rest to follow, here is another aspect of it emerging in India. Industry lobby groups are getting along with other experts to kickstart track-II diplomacy with the US.The move has been initiated by Aspen Strategy Group, supported by the Confederation of Indian Industries, and will have names like Nitin Desai, member of the PM's council on climate change, and Kirit Parikh, retired Planning Commission member and co-author of the Integrated Energy Policy from the Indian side. Industrialist Jamshyd N Godrej along with Tarun Das of Aspen India are taking the lead from India and Navroz Dubash with the Centre for Policy Research is also on board.While the government is not directly represented, the presence of several individuals who are also members of various climate related committees of the government including Nitin Desai, who is on the apex body -- the PM's council -- could lend weight to the talks.Desai, when asked about the initiative, told TOI that he is in favour of discrete closed-door talks as well as open dialogue. He said track-II talks with the US held quietly would help explore options beyond entrenched existingpositions. He said there were different advantages to both formats.But some confusion about the character of the talks initiated by Aspen and CII remain with one member of the formation, not wishing to be named, said that he had was willing to join only if the talks were done in a more open fashion and by broadening the base of participants rather than sticking to the few already enlisted.Yet another enlisted member admitted that with lack of trust and a general suspicion in the air about India changing its climate stance rapidly over the past year the track-II approach needed to be taken carefully in order to not raise doubts about its purpose.Union environment and forest ministry officials while claiming they were aware of the move said that they were not involved with the process. Tarun Das and Jamshyd N Godrej, the two leading the intitiative, remained unavailable for comment.
