aVThe state government may soon conduct a study to assess the impact of climate change on agricultural and water sector across the state.\u000a\u000aThe two-year study, 'Vulnerability and Adaptation Programme'  with a cost of around Rs 1.5 crore  will be undertaken in each district by Development Alternatives, a Delhi-based Non-Government Organisation. Technical assistance from institutes like Indian Institute of Tropical Meteorology, Pune and Indian Institute of Technology, Delhi, will also be taken.\u000a\u000a"We are already conducting a similar study in Madhya Pradesh and have submitted our proposal to the Uttar Pradesh government," said Anand Kumar Shrivastava, Programme Manager, Development Alternatives. "Once the study is complete, we will also suggest an adaptation plan to be implemented by the state government."\u000a\u000a"We are keen to implement the proposal. We will submit it to Lucknow Chief Secretary Atul Kumar Gupta in a meeting scheduled in the first week of next month," said Yashpal Singh, Director, Environment Directorate.\u000a\u000aFor the study, the state will be divided into eight agro-climate regions depending on soil type, rainfall and temperature. A specified area in these zones will be selected, where the study will be conducted in which different climate variations and characteristics will be studied.\u000a\u000aTie-ups will be made with the local NGOs and a member each from the NGO, state government, the local community, Indian Institute of Tropical Meteorology, Pune and IIT-Delhi will be part of the committee at the district level.\u000a\u000aClimate modelling maps of the areas will be taken from the Indian Institute of Tropical Meteorology, Pune.\u000a\u000a"We will compare current data with data 50 years ago," said Shrivastava. "This way, we will be able to ascertain the changes in crops over a period of time and suggest solutions accordingly."\u000a\u000aThe present scenario of water resources will also be assessed through remote sensing technique. "We will also train the staff so the programme can be executed with their help as well," said Shrivastava.\u000a\u000aALSO READ Curtains on Saifai event as stars praise CM, Mulayam\u000a\u000aPlease read our terms of use before posting comments
