aVMUMBAI: Private equity (PE) funds are eyeing investments in clean technology companies, in the belief that the sector will do well because of rising ecological awareness, sustained government spending and entry of corporate players into the segment.Clean technology is a process of creating electricity and fuels that do not pollute the environment. The first three months of 2010 have already seen five private equity deals in clean-tech sector aggregating to $150 million, according to Venture Intelligence rolls. The sector also logged two venture capital deals aggregating to $11 million during the considered period. TPG Growth's (and others) $115-million investment in renewable energy company Greenko Group and IFC's $10-million early stage investment in renewable energy firm Auro Mira Energy are some of the recent deals in the clean-tech space."Clean technology is a very interesting space and it cuts across different sectors. Factors like declining cost curve for new technologies (within the sector), active government support and under-representation in the capital market make it a good avenue for capital investments," said Raja Parthasarathy, managing director, IDFC Private Equity. IDFC PE has invested in Moser Baer Photo Voltaic and wind energy company SE Forge.Big government budgets for clean energy are encouraging private capital investors to invest in the clean-tech sector. The extension of budgetary sops \u2014 reduction in duties for clean-tech equipment \u2014 and support for clean-tech companies along with government stimulus and regulatory requirements to meet renewable portfolio standards, are helping drive continued investments by private investors in clean technology companies.Investments into clean technologies will grow even further in the event of the government readying itself to implement a 20-25% reduction without any binding in carbon emission intensity by 2020 as part of its Copenhagen Climate Summit plan. The Indian government, in its recent budget, has stressed on the need for clean technologies to replace processes in polluting businesses.Setting up greenfield projects, expanding brownfield facilities and technology modernisation are the broader categories into which private equity funds infuse capital. Private equity and venture capital investors assess factors like market opportunity, product or service positioning, competitive advantage and span for expansion as part of their pre-investment due diligence."Renewable energy is a capital-intensive sector. Companies functioning in that space would need both equity and debt to cover its capital structure. Source for future funds has to be ascertained, prior to investing in clean-tech companies," Mr Parthasarathy added.According to PE investors, gestation period, or company turning profitable, in clean-tech companies could be anything between six months to about seven years. Hydro-electricity plants take 3-7 years to yield profits, while wind energy projects could start yielding profits in about six months if implemented properly. While private equity investors expect an annualised return of 25-30% in general investments, it would be around 20%."Current investment trend in the clean-tech space is skewed towards energy. Going forward, we expect the funds to invest in water-related business and waste management businesses as well. We are also seeing several global specialist funds like Aloe PE and Climate Change Capital scouting for Indian clean-tech assets," said Arun Natarjan, managing director, Venture Intelligence.Some of the top PE deals in clean-tech sectors till date are Arcapita's $230-million investment in Suzlon Energy , Masdar's $174-million investment in Winwind, Merrill Lynch's $55 million worth of investments in Vestas RRB and SCI Asia's $40-million investment in Ramky Enviro Engineers (waste management experts).
